mon]]\"\n| \"[[Johnny Angel (song)|Johnny Angel]]\" by [[Shelley Fabares]]\n|- \n| \"[[2007 National Football League videotaping controversy|Stupid Cheat]]\"\n| \"[[Super Freak]]\" by [[Rick James]]\n|-\n| \"These Boots Were Made in [[Brockton, Massachusetts|Brockton]]\"\n| \"[[These Boots Are Made for Walkin']]\" by [[Nancy Sinatra]]\n|-\n| \"[[Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim|The Angels]] Song\"\n| \"[[Hotel California]]\" by the [[Eagles (band)|Eagles]]\n|-\n| \"[[Foxboro Stadium|Foxboro]]\"\n| \"[[Kokomo (song)|Kokomo]]\" by [[the Beach Boys]]\n|-\n| \"Very Key People\"\n| \"[[Indian Reservation (song)|Indian Reservation]]\" by [[Paul Revere & the Raiders]]\n|-\n| \"Try A Sausage On The Mild Side\"\n| \"[[Walk on the Wild Side (Lou Reed song)|Walk on the Wild Side]]\" by [[Lou Reed]]\n|-\n| \"[[2007 New England Patriots season|You're 16-0]]\" (later \"17 and 0\" and \"18 and 0\")\n| \"[[You're Sixteen]]\" by [[Ringo Starr]]\n|-\n| \"It's Time To Beat the [[New York Giants|Giants]]\"\n| \"[[She Blinded Me With Science]]\" by [[Thomas Dolby]]\n|-\n| \"[[Pornography addiction|Addicted to Porn]]\"\n| \"[[Addicted to Love (song)|Addicted to Love]]\" by [[Robert Palmer (singer)|Robert Palmer]]\n|-\n| \"[[2008 NBA Finals|Beat L.A.]]\"\n| \"[[Walk This Way]]\" by [[Aerosmith]]\n|-\n| \"[[Manny Ramirez|Manny]] Song\"\n| \"[[Brandy (You're a Fine Girl)]]\" by [[Looking Glass (band)|Looking Glass]]\n|-\n| \"The [[401(k)]] Song\"\n| \"[[Play That Funky Music]]\" by [[Wild Cherry (band)|Wild Cherry]]\n|-\n| \"[[Hazel Mae]]\"\n| \"[[Maggie May]]\" by [[Rod Stewart]]\n|-\n| \"Pat's Life\"\n| \"[[That's Life (song)|That's Life]]\" by [[Frank Sinatra]]\n|-\n| \"You Don't Mess Around With [[Lynn, Massachusetts|Lynn]]\"\n| \"You Don't Mess Around With Jim\" by [[Jim Croce]]\n|-\n| \"[[Bourne Bridge]]\"\n| \"[[The Unicorn (song)|The Unicorn]]\" by [[the Irish Rovers]]\n|-\n| \"[[North Shore (Massachusetts)|North Shore]] People\"\n| \"Short People\" by [[Randy Newman]]\n|-\n| \"Everybody Plays the Pool\"\n| \"Everybody Plays the Fool\" by [[The Main Ingredient (band)|The Main Ingredient]]\n|-\n| \"[[Sal DiMasi|I'm So Indicted]]\"\n| \"[[I'm So Excited]]\" by [[The Pointer Sisters]]\n|-\n| \"Batter Named Shinchuchu\"\n| \"[[Chattanooga Choo-Choo]]\"\n|-\n| \"[[Chatham, Massachusetts|Chatham]]\"\n| \"Shattered\" by [[the Rolling Stones]]\n|-\n| \"Bring [[James J. Bulger|Whitey]] In\"\n| \"Mighty Quinn\" by [[Manfred Mann]]\n|-\n| \"[[Saugus, Massachusetts|Saugus]] Nights\"\n| \"[[Summer Nights (John Travolta and Olivia Newton-John song)|Summer Nights]]\" from ''[[Grease (film)|Grease]]''\n|-\n| \"Dominic the [[Bookie]]\"\n\n\"[[Stephen Gostkowski|Gostkowsi]] The [[Placekicker|Kicker]]\"\n| \"[[Dominick The Donkey]]\" by [[Lou Monte]]\n|-\n| \"Sue Cope Got Pulled Over by a [[Massachusetts State Police|Trooper]]\"\n| \"[[Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer]]\" by [[Elmo Shropshire|Elmo]] and Patsy\n|-\n| \"All My [[Harvard University|Harvard]] Friends Are Coming Over Tonight\"\n| \"[[All My Rowdy Friends Are Coming Over Tonight]]\" by [[Hank Williams Jr.]]\n|-\n| \"[[MBTA|T]] Breakdown\"\n| \"Breakdown\" by [[Tom Petty]]\n|-\n| \"Lovely [[Humarock]]\"\n| \"Loves Me Like A Rock\" by [[Paul Simon]]\n|-\n| \"[[Wonderland Greyhound Park|Wonderland]]\"\n| \"Winter Wonderland\"\n|-\n| \"The [[Pothole]] Song\"\n| \"On The Road Again\" by [[Willie Nelson]]\n|-\n| \"[[Natick Mall|The Natick Collection]]\"\n| \"[[Rainbow Connection]]\" by [[Kermit the Frog]]\n|-\n| \"[[Lowell, Massachusetts|Lowell]] Man\"\n| \"[[Soul Man (song)|Soul Man]]\" by [[Sam & Dave]]\n|-\n| \"He's [[Kim Jong-un]]\"\n| \"[[Undun (song)|Undun]]\" by [[the Guess Who]]\n|-\n| \"We Got the Beards\"\n(during the 2013 ALDS, ALCS, and World Series)\n| \"[[We Got the Beat]]\" by [[The Go-Go's]]\n|-\n| \"We're Market Basket\"\n| \"[[We are the Champions]]\" by [[Queen (band)|Queen]]\n|}\n\n\n==Current programming==\nThe weekday schedule includes WROR personalities Bob Bronson, Lauren Beckham Falcone and Brian Bell (mornings), Julie Devereaux (middays) and Jaybeau Jones (afternoons).\n\nThe station now focuses on hit songs from the 1970s, 1980s, and some 1990s hits. It\u2019s slogan is \u201c80s & more!\u201d Therefore the station has an emphasis on 80s music.\n\nThe HD2 [[digital subchannel]] once broadcast a [[classic rock]] format under the brand \"The Bone\". Previous formats on WROR-HD2 have included all-comedy and [[1970s in music|70s hits]], respectively.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tucker|first1=Ken|title=Greater Media, Emmis Unveil HD2 Strategies|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1358988/greater-media-emmis-unveil-hd2-strategies|accessdate=January 19, 2016|work=Billboard|date=January 19, 2006}}</ref>\n\nFrom July 2020, the HD2 subchannel flipped to a loop of \u201cMen from Maine\u201d segments from the Loren and Wally Archive. This article will be updated if the sub channel has closed since. <ref> https://www.reddit.com/r/boston/comments/c8c64r/wth_happened_to_wror_hd2_the_bone/</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://wror.com/}}\n*{{FM station data|WROR}}\n\n{{Boston Radio}}\n{{Classic Hits Radio Stations in Massachusetts}}\n{{Beasley Broadcast Group}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations in Boston|ROR]]\n[[Category:Beasley Broadcast Group radio stations|ROR]]\n[[Category:Classic hits radio stations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1960]]\n[[Category:Framingham, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Media in Middlesex County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:1960 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Classic hits radio station in Framingham\u2013Boston, Massachusetts}}\n{{More footnotes|date=April 2009}}\n{{Infobox radio station\n| name = WROR-FM\n| image = [[File:WROR-FM logo.png|200px]][[File:WROR-HD2 logo.png|200px]]\n| city = [[Framingham, Massachusetts]]\n| area = [[Greater Boston]]\n| branding = '''105.7 WROR'''\n| slogan = 80s & More!\n| frequency = {{Frequency|105.7|MHz}} {{HD Radio}}\n| airdate = {{start date and age|1960|2|10}}<ref name=bostonradio-start>{{cite web|title=The Boston Radio Dial: WROR-FM|url=http://www.bostonradio.org/stations/20438|work=The Archives @ BostonRadio.org|accessdate=January 28, 2012}}</ref>\n| format = [[Classic hits]]\n| language = \n| power = \n| erp = 23,000 [[watt]]s\n| haat = 224 [[meter]]s\n| class = B\n| facility_id = 20438\n| coordinates = {{coord|42|20|50|N|71|4|59|W|region:US-MA_type:landmark|name=WROR-FM}}\n| callsign_meaning = Previously used on the former WROR (98.5 FM) in Boston, now [[WBZ-FM]]\n| former_callsigns = WKOX-FM (1960&ndash;71)<br>WVBF (1971&ndash;93)<br>WCLB-FM (1993&ndash;95)<br>[[WKLB-FM]] (1995&ndash;96)\n| owner = [[Beasley Broadcast Group]]\n| licensee = Beasley Media Group Licenses, LLC\n| sister_stations = [[WBOS]], [[WBQT (FM)|WBQT]], [[WBZ-FM]], [[WKLB-FM]], [[WRCA]]\n| webcast = {{listenlive|https://wror.com/}}<br>{{IHeartRadio|1057-wror-5280}}\n| website = {{URL|https://wror.com/}}<br>HD2: {{URL|https://wror.com/wror-hd2-the-bone/}}\n}}\n\n'''WROR-FM''' (105.7 [[FM broadcasting|FM]]) \u2013 branded as '''105.7 WROR''' \u2013 is a commercial [[classic hits]] [[Radio broadcasting|radio station]] licensed to [[Framingham, Massachusetts|Framingham]], [[Massachusetts]]. Owned by the [[Beasley Broadcast Group]], the station serves [[Greater Boston]] and much of surrounding [[New England]], including portions of the [[Portsmouth, New Hampshire|Portsmouth]] and [[Providence, Rhode Island|Providence]] radio markets. The WROR studios are located in the [[Boston]] neighborhood of [[Dorchester, Boston|Dorchester]], while the station transmitter resides on the [[Prudential Tower]] in [[Downtown Boston]]. WROR is continually ranked as one of the highest-rated radio stations in the Boston media market, as well as one of the highest-rated classic hits stations in the United States.\n\nWROR's [[transmitter]] is on the lower FM [[Radio masts and towers|mast]] of the [[Prudential Tower]] in Downtown Boston. The signal reaches as far north as [[Portsmouth, New Hampshire]], and as far south as [[Providence, Rhode Island]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://radio-locator.com/cgi-bin/patg?id=WROR-FM|title=WROR-FM Radio Station Coverage Map|website=radio-locator.com|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Besides a standard [[analog transmission]], WROR broadcasts on [[HD Radio]], and is also available online.\n\n==History==\n===WKOX-FM (1960-1971)===\n{{Distinguish||text=Everett, Massachusetts radio station [[WKOX (AM)]]}}\nThe station signed on as WKOX-FM on February 10, 1960, the [[FM radio|FM]] companion of [[WXKS (AM)|WKOX (1190 AM)]].<ref>[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1961-62/section%20B%201%20Radio%20%20Broadcasting%20Yearbook%201961-1962-9.pdf Broadcasting Yearbook 1961-62 page B-81]</ref> Initially a simulcast of WKOX's daytime programming, WKOX-FM would exclusively air [[classical music]] programming at night oriented towards Boston's [[MetroWest]] suburbs.\n\nIn January 1969, the station began broadcasting a [[contemporary hit radio|top 40]]/[[album rock]] format as ''The New FM 105'', and then later as ''FM Stereo 105''. WKOX-FM was the Boston area's first FM top 40 station featuring live [[disc jockey]]s, including hosts Bill Thomas, Brother Bill Heizer, FM Douglas, program director Dick Stevens, John Leisher, Alan Fraser, J. William Charles, with Kenny McKay and Jimmy Conlee. WKOX-FM converted to [[Stereophonic sound|stereo broadcasting]] that July.\n\n===WVBF (1971-1993)===\n{{Distinguish||text=Middleborough Center, Massachusetts radio station [[WVBF]]}}\nWKOX and WKOX-FM were acquired by Fairbanks Communications in July 1971. After the sale, WKOX-FM became WVBF (also known as the ''Electronic Mama''), as a hybrid top 40/rock station, initially retaining some of the WKOX-FM personalities. The call letters officially stood for \"Welcome, Virginia Brown Fairbanks\", the wife of station owner Richard M. Fairbanks; Richard also had a station named after himself, [[WRMF]] in [[West Palm Beach, Florida|West Palm Beach]]. WVBF improved its signal coverage, targeting the [[Greater Boston]] area. Some hosts added to WVBF during their early months included Buddy Ballou, John \"Big John\" Gillis, Bill \"BLF Bash\" Freeman and Charlie Kendall.\n\nDuring Fairbanks ownership in the 1970s, WVBF evolved from being a high energy top 40/rock hybrid station in 1971/1972, to becoming a mainstream [[top 40]] station by 1975, and eventually evolved into a [[hot adult contemporary]] format over the years. WVBF also had many different nicknames in that era, including ''WVBF FM 105'', ''WVBF Stereo 105'', ''F105 WVBF'' and ''The New WVBF Boston 105''.\n\nWVBF debuted a morning show in 1981 hosted by the team of Loren Owens and Wally Brine; eventually joined on-air by [[character actor]]/[[Parody music|parody musician]] Tom Doyle, newscaster Lauren Beckham Falcone, traffic reporter Hank Morse and producer Brian \"Lung Boy\" Bell. ''Loren and Wally'' would continue to air on the station even with multiple ownership, format and call letter changes until Brine's retirement in 2016.<ref name=\"tbg-landw2001\">{{cite news|last=Simon|first=Clea|title=Loren and Wally: 20 years on air|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-8668570.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924201610/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-8668570.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 24, 2015|accessdate=December 8, 2012|newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]]|date=July 26, 2001}}</ref>\n\nIn the early 1990s, [[Delilah Rene|Delilah]] was a host on WVBF before she moved to [[Seattle]] and entered national syndication.\n\n===WCLB/WKLB (1993-1996)===\n{{For|the current incarnation of WKLB on 102.5 FM|WKLB-FM}} \n{{Distinguish||text=Manchester, Kentucky radio station [[WKLB (AM)]]}}\nOn February 12, 1993, citing the growing popularity of [[country music]], WVBF became WCLB, \"The Country Club\".<ref>http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-RandR/1990s/1993/RR-1993-02-19.pdf</ref><ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8_roUYfhZ24/ 105.7 WCLB TV Commercials 1993]</ref> The format change was made in an effort to throw off [[Greater Media]] from launching a country format on newly acquired [[WBQT (FM)|WCDJ (96.9 FM)]]; that station's format switch to WBCS happened anyway. Confusion with other FM stations and [[WCVB-TV]] led to a call sign change to WKLB in 1995.\n\nIn 1995, WKLB was to be sold to Evergreen Media, and was widely expected to become a talk station. However, a series of subsequent trades in 1996 placed WKLB under common ownership with WBCS via Greater Media.<ref>[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/doc/403763793.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Jun+15%2C+1996&author=Bickelhaupt%2C+Susan&pub=Boston+Globe&edition=&startpage=23&desc=WBCS-FM+owners+to+take+over+WKLB-FM/ WBCS-FM owners to take over WKLB-FM], ''[[Boston Globe]]'', June 15, 1996</ref>\n\nOn August 24, 1996, the intellectual property of WKLB \"merged\" with WBCS, with the newly merged country station utilizing the 96.9 frequency of WBCS along with the WKLB call letters, combining personalities from both stations. Some WKLB personalities remained at the station for the new format, including ''Loren and Wally''. The two stations simulcast for eleven days.\n\n===WROR (1996-present)===\nAfter the simulcast ended, on September 5, 1996, Greater Media changed WKLB's call letters to WROR, and changed the station's format to [[oldies]].<ref>[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/boston/doc/290798345.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Sep+5%2C+1996&author=Bickelhaupt%2C+Susan&pub=Boston+Globe+%28pre-1997+Fulltext%29&edition=&startpage=E.8&desc=%27ROR-FM+back+in+letter+and+spirit/ ROR-FM back in letter and spirit], ''Boston Globe'', September 5, 1996</ref> The WROR callsign had previously been used on [[WBZ-FM|98.5 FM]] until 1991, later being been \"[[Domain parking|parked]]\" first on [[WMFN|WMFN (640 AM)]] in [[Zeeland, Michigan]], then on [[WWDJ|WROR (1150 AM)]]; the latter was also owned by Greater Media at the time.\n\nThe \"new\" WROR played 1970s pop and rock oldies, [[disco]], some 1960s oldies, 1980s soft rock and top-40 crossovers, along with some [[classic rock]], and hired several staffers connected to the \"old\" WROR. Leading broadcasters involved with WROR in the 1970s and early 1980s included program director [[Gary Berkowitz]] and personalities such as: Joe Martell, Phil Redo, Larry Justice, Frank Kingston Smith, and current WROR General Manager Tom Baker.\n\nBy 1999, the format had been modified to classic rock, similar to co-owned [[WMGK]] in [[Philadelphia]], but gradually moved back to more of a pop-based classic hits format in 2006, emphasizing pop adult rock hits while mixing in some R&B, disco, and harder rock songs. The station continues to emphasize the 1970s and 1980s, but also plays some well-known 1960s and 1990s hits. WROR became the market's lone classic hits station in 2012 following [[WODS]]'s format switch to top 40. ''[[The Lost 45s]]'' hosted by [[Barry Scott]] returned to WROR on September 2, 2012; it was dropped on April 2014.\n\nOn July 19, 2016, [[Beasley Broadcast Group|Beasley Media Group]] announced it would acquire Greater Media and its 21 stations (including WROR) for $240 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://radioinsight.com/headlines/107315/beasley-acquires-greater-media/|title=Beasley Acquires Greater Media|date=2016-08-03|website=RadioInsight|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref> The FCC approved the sale on October 6, 2016, and the sale closed on November 1, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://radioinsight.com/headlines/108958/beasley-closes-on-greater-media-purchase-makes-multiple-staff-moves/|title=Beasley Closes On Greater Media Purchase; Makes Multiple Staff Moves|date=2016-11-01|website=RadioInsight|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref> Following Beasley's acquisition of [[WBZ-FM]] in 2017, WROR-FM began broadcasting [[Boston Celtics]] games that conflict with broadcasts of the [[Boston Bruins]] or the [[New England Patriots]]; WBZ-FM is the flagship station for all three teams.\n\nTom Doyle was let go from the morning show on November 19, 2014; in December 2016, Wally Brine announced his retirement.<ref>http://wror.com/wally/#thanksservingb Wally Set To Retire His Alarm Clock! </ref> Hank Morse was let go on June 24, 2019, four days before Owens retired, citing an inability to reach terms on a contract extension. Bob Bronson, formerly of [[WLTW]] in [[New York City]] and [[WZID]] in [[Manchester, New Hampshire|Manchester]], was teamed up with ''Loren and Wally'' holdovers Lauren Beckham Falcone and Brian Bell.\n\n===Christmas music===\nFrom 2007 through 2011, WROR broadcast [[Christmas music]] format throughout the [[Christmas and holiday season|holiday season]];<ref name=\"bh-earlyxmas08\">{{cite news|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/bostonherald/access/1590807231.html?dids=1590807231:1590807231&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Nov+07%2C+2008&author=JESSICA+HESLAM&pub=Boston+Herald&desc=Oh%2C+joy!+Radio+stations+take+Christmas+carol+plunge+early&pqatl=google|title=Oh, joy! Radio stations take Christmas carol plunge early|last=Heslam|first=Jessica|date=November 7, 2008|newspaper=[[Boston Herald]]|accessdate=December 8, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"wbz-xmas2010\">{{cite news|url=http://boston.cbslocal.com/2010/11/18/radio-stations-kick-off-holiday-season/|title=Radio Stations Kick Off Holiday Season|date=November 18, 2010|newspaper=[[WBZ-TV|CBS Boston]]|accessdate=December 8, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Radio-Info\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.radio-info.com/news/bostons-wror-fm-flips-to-christmas-just-after-oldies-1031-does|title=WROR flips to oldies music|accessdate=May 23, 2012}}</ref> the station would also air a nightly call-in program for children hosted by \"[[Santa Claus]]\". After WODS's 2012 format switch, then-sister station [[WMJX]] assumed the role of playing Christmas music annually.\n\n==Loren and Wally==\nThe station may be best known for its former morning team, Loren Owens and Wally Brine, co-starring Tom Doyle who contributed character voices and parody songs, along with Lauren Beckham Falcone reporting news and Hank Morse with traffic, and produced by Brian \"Lung Boy\" Bell. (Doyle was let go on November 19, 2014.) The program aired on the station since 1981 (when it was still WVBF).<ref name=tbg-landw2001>{{cite news|last=Simon|first=Clea|title=Loren and Wally: 20 years on air|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-8668570.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924201610/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-8668570.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=September 24, 2015|accessdate=December 8, 2012|newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]]|date=July 26, 2001}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, Wally Brine announced his retirement.<ref>http://wror.com/wally/#thanksservingb Wally Set To Retire His Alarm Clock! </ref>  Hank Morse was let go on June 24, 2019, a few days before the show concluded.  Owens did his final show on June 28, 2019, citing an inability to reach terms on a contract extension.  WROR now has \"The ROR Morning Show\" as its wake-up program, hosted by Bob Bronson (formerly with [[WLTW]] [[New York City]] and [[WZID]] [[Manchester, New Hampshire]]) joined by Lauren Beckham Falcone as co-host and Brian Bell as producer.\n\nThe Loren & Wally Show had several segments:\n\n===Men from Maine===\n'''Men from Maine''' was a one- to two-minute comedy segment, opening with [[soap opera]] organ music and Loren stating something varying along the lines of, \"Welcome to another thrilling episode of the exciting adventures of Men from Maine. As today's action packed drama begins...\". Episodes typically revolve around the two main characters Lem (played by Tom) and Ephus (played by Wally), and other residents of [[Bangor, Maine]], such as Ephus' wife Effie and son Ephus Junior, Doc Cider (after Dock Sider shoes) and Pastor Fazool (after ''[[pasta e fagioli]]''). The same characters have been used in songs about Maine on the segment \"Tom's Townie Tunes\" (see below). The humor of the segment is at its root generic \"[[Redneck (stereotype)|redneck]] humor\", but set in very rural, backwoods Maine as opposed to the [[American South]]. Episode themes can run all the way from industrial accidents handled in incompetent ways (many residents, including Lem and Ephus work in the local [[sawmill]]), to bestiality. In all cases, the humor comes from the stupidity of the characters, and their obliviousness to it. Every episode ends with the characters going \"Ayuh!\"\n\nAt least one listener has found the show offensive, as heard on the first Men from Maine CD (sold during the holiday season to raise money for charity). Offended by the humor poking fun at her home state, a woman called the station, threatening to continue protesting the show until it is taken off the air. But the segment continued on the Loren and Wally show until Owens' departure from the program. Some can still be found as a \"Loren & Wally Podcast of the Day\" on iTunes and 2 episodes are posted on [[YouTube]].\n\n===Tom's Townie Tunes===\n'''Tom's Townie Tunes''' is a segment created by morning crew member Tom Doyle that spoofs [[classic rock]] hits, using humorous lyrics to poke fun at towns in Massachusetts (and an additional few songs about the surrounding region, such as Maine). Often the songs are about high crime rates, poverty, and the general misery of residents in low class areas, while other songs satirize [[Harvard]] graduates and [[Kerry Healey]]'s failed run for [[Governor of Massachusetts]] (sung to the tune of \"[[867-5309 (Jenny)]]\" by [[Tommy Tutone]]). The first ever Townie Tune was about [[Provincetown, Massachusetts]] (sung to the tune of [[Funkytown]]). Doyle's sports-related songs have occasionally gained airplay on other stations during championship seasons. During the holiday season, Tom often sings parodies of classic Christmas songs.\n\nOther Townie Tunes include:\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Townie Tune\n! Song parodied\n|-\n| \"Stuck With a Kid at [[Boston University|B.U.]]\" \n| \"[[Stuck in the Middle With You]]\" by [[Stealers Wheel]]\n|-\n| \"[[Fung Wah Bus]]\"\n| \"[[Magic Bus (song)|Magic Bus]]\" by [[The Who]]\n|-\n| \"F-You [[Curse of the Bambino|Babe]]\"\n| \"[[I Got You, Babe]]\" by [[Sonny & Cher]]\n|-\n| \"[[Somerville, Massachusetts|Somerville Song]]\"\n| \"[[The Jamies|Summertime, Summertime]]\"\n|-\n| \"Buying A Sheep Tonight\" (Men From Maine song Posted on YouTube)\n| \"[[The Lion Sleeps Tonight]]\" by [[The Tokens]]\n|-\n| \"[[Tom Brady|Brady]] Shuffle\"\n| \"[[The Curly Shuffle]]\" by [[Jump 'N The Saddle Band]]\n|-\n| \"I Heard You Came From [[Brookline, Massachusetts|Brookline]]\"\n| \"[[I Heard It Through the Grapevine]]\"\n|-\n| \"You Ain't Seen [[Newton, Massachusetts|Newton]] Yet\"\n| \"[[You Ain't Seen Nothing Yet (Bachman-Turner Overdrive song)|You Ain't Seen Nothing Yet]]\" by [[Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive]]\n|-\n| \"The Rectum of Edmund Fitzgerald\"\n| \"[[The Wreck of the Edmund Fitzgerald|The Wreck of the ''Edmund Fitzgerald'']]\" by [[Gordon Lightfoot]]\n|-\n| \"Come To [[Medford, Massachusetts|Medford]]\"\n| \"[[Come Together]]\" by [[The Beatles]]\n|-\n| \"[[Haverhill, Massachusetts|Haverhill]]\"\n| \"[[Margaritaville]]\" by [[Jimmy Buffett]]\n|-\n| \"Naked Bare in [[Ipswich, Massachusetts|Ipswich]]\"\n| \"[[Takin' Care of Business (song)|Takin' Care of Business]]\" by [[Bachman\u2013Turner Overdrive]]\n|-\n| \"[[Weymouth, Massachusetts|Weymouth]]\"\n| \"[[Tequila (Champs song)|Tequila]]\" by [[The Champs]]\n|-\n| \"[[Curt Schilling|Curt]]'s So Good\"\n| \"[[Hurts So Good]]\" by [[John Cougar Mellencamp]]\n|-\n| \"Don't Worry, [[David Ortiz|Big Papi]]\"\n| \"[[Don't Worry, Be Happy]]\" by [[Bobby McFerrin]]\n|-\n| \"Fifty Ways To Kill A [[Plover]]\"\n| \"[[50 Ways to Leave Your Lover]]\" by [[Paul Simon]]\n|-\n| \"In [[Maine]]\" (