 Wanna Do (Is Wipe My Bum)\"\n| \"[[All I Wanna Do (Sheryl Crow song)|All I Wanna Do]]\" by [[Sheryl Crow]]\n|-\n| \"[[Hideki Okajima|Okajima!]]\"\n| \"[[Oklahoma (state song)|Oklahoma!]]\" by [[Rodgers and Hammerstein]]\n|-\n| \"[[Daisuke Matsuzaka|Matsuzaka]]\"\n| \"[[Macarena (song)|Macarena]]\" by [[Los del R\u00edo]]\n|-\n| \"Garbage Man\"\n| \"[[Piano Man (song)|Piano Man]]\" by [[Billy Joel]]\n|-\n| \"The Panty Song\"\n| \"Shanty\" by [[Jonathan Edwards (musician)|Jonathan Edwards]]\n|-\n| \"[[Roger Clemens#New York Yankees (2007)|Groin Fatigue]]\"\n| \"[[Centerfield (song)|Centerfield]]\" by [[Creedence Clearwater Revival]]\n|-\n| \"I Want a Girl Like [[Lindsay Lohan]]\"\n| \"[[Slow Hand]]\" by [[the Pointer Sisters]]\n|-\n| \"Casino Song\"\n| \"[[Do You Want to Know a Secret]]\" by [[The Beatles]]\n|-\n| \"Donald the [[Coroner]]\"\n| \"[[Down on the Corner]]\" by [[Creedence Clearwater Revival]]\n|-\n| \"The [[Norwood, Massachusetts|Norwood]] Song\"\n| \"[[I'm Into Something Good]]\" by [[Herman's Hermits]]\n|-\n| \"Spin The Wheel of Meat\"\n(promotional song for \"Wheel of Meat\" giveaway)\n| \"Lights\" by [[Journey (band)|Journey]]\n\"[[We Are Family (song)|We Are Family]]\" by [[Sister Sledge]]\n\n\"I Just Want to Celebrate\" by [[Rare Earth (band)|Rare Earth]]\n\n\"[[Shining Star (Earth, Wind & Fire song)|Shining Star]]\" by [[Earth, Wind & Fire]]\n\n\"Don't Bring Me Down\" by [[Electric Light Orchestra]]\n|-\n| \"You're Still [[Johnny Damon|Juan Dam\u00f3n]] To Me\"\n| \"[[It's Still Rock and Roll to Me]]\" by [[Billy Joel]]\n|-\n| \"[[Johnny Damon]]\"\n| \"[[Johnny Angel (song)|Johnny Angel]]\" by [[Shelley Fabares]]\n|- \n| \"[[2007 National Football League videotaping controversy|Stupid Cheat]]\"\n| \"[[Super Freak]]\" by [[Rick James]]\n|-\n| \"These Boots Were Made in [[Brockton, Massachusetts|Brockton]]\"\n| \"[[These Boots Are Made for Walkin']]\" by [[Nancy Sinatra]]\n|-\n| \"[[Los Angeles Angels of Anaheim|The Angels]] Song\"\n| \"[[Hotel California]]\" by the [[Eagles (band)|Eagles]]\n|-\n| \"[[Foxboro Stadium|Foxboro]]\"\n| \"[[Kokomo (song)|Kokomo]]\" by [[the Beach Boys]]\n|-\n| \"Very Key People\"\n| \"[[Indian Reservation (song)|Indian Reservation]]\" by [[Paul Revere & the Raiders]]\n|-\n| \"Try A Sausage On The Mild Side\"\n| \"[[Walk on the Wild Side (Lou Reed song)|Walk on the Wild Side]]\" by [[Lou Reed]]\n|-\n| \"[[2007 New England Patriots season|You're 16-0]]\" (later \"17 and 0\" and \"18 and 0\")\n| \"[[You're Sixteen]]\" by [[Ringo Starr]]\n|-\n| \"It's Time To Beat the [[New York Giants|Giants]]\"\n| \"[[She Blinded Me With Science]]\" by [[Thomas Dolby]]\n|-\n| \"[[Pornography addiction|Addicted to Porn]]\"\n| \"[[Addicted to Love (song)|Addicted to Love]]\" by [[Robert Palmer (singer)|Robert Palmer]]\n|-\n| \"[[2008 NBA Finals|Beat L.A.]]\"\n| \"[[Walk This Way]]\" by [[Aerosmith]]\n|-\n| \"[[Manny Ramirez|Manny]] Song\"\n| \"[[Brandy (You're a Fine Girl)]]\" by [[Looking Glass (band)|Looking Glass]]\n|-\n| \"The [[401(k)]] Song\"\n| \"[[Play That Funky Music]]\" by [[Wild Cherry (band)|Wild Cherry]]\n|-\n| \"[[Hazel Mae]]\"\n| \"[[Maggie May]]\" by [[Rod Stewart]]\n|-\n| \"Pat's Life\"\n| \"[[That's Life (song)|That's Life]]\" by [[Frank Sinatra]]\n|-\n| \"You Don't Mess Around With [[Lynn, Massachusetts|Lynn]]\"\n| \"You Don't Mess Around With Jim\" by [[Jim Croce]]\n|-\n| \"[[Bourne Bridge]]\"\n| \"[[The Unicorn (song)|The Unicorn]]\" by [[the Irish Rovers]]\n|-\n| \"[[North Shore (Massachusetts)|North Shore]] People\"\n| \"Short People\" by [[Randy Newman]]\n|-\n| \"Everybody Plays the Pool\"\n| \"Everybody Plays the Fool\" by [[The Main Ingredient (band)|The Main Ingredient]]\n|-\n| \"[[Sal DiMasi|I'm So Indicted]]\"\n| \"[[I'm So Excited]]\" by [[The Pointer Sisters]]\n|-\n| \"Batter Named Shinchuchu\"\n| \"[[Chattanooga Choo-Choo]]\"\n|-\n| \"[[Chatham, Massachusetts|Chatham]]\"\n| \"Shattered\" by [[the Rolling Stones]]\n|-\n| \"Bring [[James J. Bulger|Whitey]] In\"\n| \"Mighty Quinn\" by [[Manfred Mann]]\n|-\n| \"[[Saugus, Massachusetts|Saugus]] Nights\"\n| \"[[Summer Nights (John Travolta and Olivia Newton-John song)|Summer Nights]]\" from ''[[Grease (film)|Grease]]''\n|-\n| \"Dominic the [[Bookie]]\"\n\n\"[[Stephen Gostkowski|Gostkowsi]] The [[Placekicker|Kicker]]\"\n| \"[[Dominick The Donkey]]\" by [[Lou Monte]]\n|-\n| \"Sue Cope Got Pulled Over by a [[Massachusetts State Police|Trooper]]\"\n| \"[[Grandma Got Run Over by a Reindeer]]\" by [[Elmo Shropshire|Elmo]] and Patsy\n|-\n| \"All My [[Harvard University|Harvard]] Friends Are Coming Over Tonight\"\n| \"[[All My Rowdy Friends Are Coming Over Tonight]]\" by [[Hank Williams Jr.]]\n|-\n| \"[[MBTA|T]] Breakdown\"\n| \"Breakdown\" by [[Tom Petty]]\n|-\n| \"Lovely [[Humarock]]\"\n| \"Loves Me Like A Rock\" by [[Paul Simon]]\n|-\n| \"[[Wonderland Greyhound Park|Wonderland]]\"\n| \"Winter Wonderland\"\n|-\n| \"The [[Pothole]] Song\"\n| \"On The Road Again\" by [[Willie Nelson]]\n|-\n| \"[[Natick Mall|The Natick Collection]]\"\n| \"[[Rainbow Connection]]\" by [[Kermit the Frog]]\n|-\n| \"[[Lowell, Massachusetts|Lowell]] Man\"\n| \"[[Soul Man (song)|Soul Man]]\" by [[Sam & Dave]]\n|-\n| \"He's [[Kim Jong-un]]\"\n| \"[[Undun (song)|Undun]]\" by [[the Guess Who]]\n|-\n| \"We Got the Beards\"\n(during the 2013 ALDS, ALCS, and World Series)\n| \"[[We Got the Beat]]\" by [[The Go-Go's]]\n|-\n| \"We're Market Basket\"\n| \"[[We are the Champions]]\" by [[Queen (band)|Queen]]\n|}\n\n\n==Current programming==\nThe weekday schedule includes WROR personalities Bob Bronson, Lauren Beckham Falcone and Brian Bell (mornings), Julie Devereaux (middays) and Jaybeau Jones (afternoons).\n\nThe station now focuses on hit songs from a the 1970s, 1980s, and some 1990s hits. It\u2019s slogan is \u201c80s & more!\u201d Therefore the station has an emphasis on 80s music.\n\nThe HD2 [[digital subchannel]] once broadcast a [[classic rock]] format under the brand \"The Bone\". Previous formats on WROR-HD2 have included all-comedy and [[1970s in music|70s hits]], respectively.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Tucker|first1=Ken|title=Greater Media, Emmis Unveil HD2 Strategies|url=http://www.billboard.com/biz/articles/news/1358988/greater-media-emmis-unveil-hd2-strategies|accessdate=January 19, 2016|work=Billboard|date=January 19, 2006}}</ref>\n\nFrom July 2020, the HD2 subchannel flipped to a loop of \u201cMen from Maine\u201d segments from the Loren and Wally Archive. This article will be updated if the sub channel has closed since. <ref> https://www.reddit.com/r/boston/comments/c8c64r/wth_happened_to_wror_hd2_the_bone/</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|https://wror.com/}}\n*{{FM station data|WROR}}\n\n{{Boston Radio}}\n{{Classic Hits Radio Stations in Massachusetts}}\n{{Beasley Broadcast Group}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations in Boston|ROR]]\n[[Category:Beasley Broadcast Group radio stations|ROR]]\n[[Category:Classic hits radio stations in the United States]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1960]]\n[[Category:Framingham, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Media in Middlesex County, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:1960 establishments in Massachusetts]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Stray word removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WROR-FM"}
{"title_page": "Fish oil", "text_new": "{{short description|Oil derived from the tissues of oily fish}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}\n\n[[File:Lachs\u00f6lkapsel.jpg|thumb|Fish oil capsules]]\n\n'''Fish oil''' is [[oil]] derived from the [[biological tissue|tissues]] of [[oily fish]]. Fish oils contain the [[omega-3 fatty acid]]s [[eicosapentaenoic acid]] (EPA) and [[docosahexaenoic acid]] (DHA), precursors of certain [[eicosanoid]]s that are known to reduce [[inflammation]] in the body<ref>{{cite journal |pages=402\u201310 |doi=10.1080/10408390701424303 |title=Advances in Dietary Enrichment with N-3 Fatty Acids |year=2008 |last1=Moghadasian |first1=Mohammed H. |journal=Critical Reviews in Food Science and Nutrition |volume=48 |issue=5 |pmid=18464030}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |pages=679\u201381 |doi=10.1186/ar1876 |year=2006 |last1=Cleland |first1=Leslieg |last2=James |first2=Michaelj |last3=Proudman |first3=Susannam |journal=[[Arthritis Research & Therapy]] |volume=8 |pmid=16542466 |pmc=1526555 |title=Fish oil: What the prescriber needs to know |issue=1}}</ref> and improve [[hypertriglyceridemia]]. There has been a great deal of controversy in recent years about the role of fish oil in [[cardiovascular disease]], with recent [[meta-analysis|meta-analyses]] reaching different conclusions about its potential impact. The most promising evidence supports supplementation for prevention of [[cardiac arrest|cardiac death]].<ref name=\"half full\"/>\n\nFish oil and omega-3 fatty acids have also been studied in a wide variety of other conditions such as [[clinical depression]],<ref name=\"Su2003\">{{cite journal |pages=267\u201371 |doi=10.1016/S0924-977X(03)00032-4 |title=Omega-3 fatty acids in major depressive disorder |year=2003 |last1=Su |first1=Kuan-Pin |last2=Huang |first2=Shih-Yi |last3=Chiu |first3=Chih-Chiang |last4=Shen |first4=Winston W. |journal=European Neuropsychopharmacology |volume=13 |issue=4 |pmid=12888186}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |pages=91\u201399 |doi=10.1080/10284150410001704525 |title=Effects of Fish Oil on the Central Nervous System: A New Potential Antidepressant? |year=2004 |last1=Naliwaiko |first1=K. |last2=Ara\u00fajo |first2=R.L.F. |last3=Da Fonseca |first3=R.V. |last4=Castilho |first4=J.C. |last5=Andreatini |first5=R. |last6=Bellissimo |first6=M.I. |last7=Oliveira |first7=B.H. |last8=Martins |first8=E.F. |last9=Curi |first9=R. |journal=Nutritional Neuroscience |volume=7 |issue=2 |pmid=15279495 |last10=Fernandes |first10=L.C. |last11=Ferraz |first11=A.C.}}</ref> [[anxiety]],<ref>{{cite journal |pages=107\u201313 |doi=10.1016/j.euroneuro.2005.07.005 |title=Red cell membrane omega-3 fatty acids are decreased in nondepressed patients with social anxiety disorder |year=2006 |last1=Green |first1=Pnina |last2=Hermesh |first2=Haggai |last3=Monselise |first3=Assaf |last4=Marom |first4=Sofi |last5=Presburger |first5=Gadi |last6=Weizman |first6=Abraham |journal=European Neuropsychopharmacology |volume=16 |issue=2 |pmid=16243493}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |pages=265\u201367 |doi=10.1080/10284150500445795 |title=Mixture of essential fatty acids lowers test anxiety |year=2005 |last1=Yehuda |first1=Shlomo |last2=Rabinovitz |first2=Sharon |last3=Mostofsky |first3=David I. |journal=Nutritional Neuroscience |volume=8 |issue=4 |pmid=16491653}}</ref><ref name=\"Pp\">{{cite journal |pages=477\u201379 |doi=10.1176/appi.ajp.159.3.477 |title=Addition of Omega-3 Fatty Acid to Maintenance Medication Treatment for Recurrent Unipolar Depressive Disorder |year=2002 |last1=Nemets |first1=B. |journal=American Journal of Psychiatry |volume=159 |issue=3 |pmid=11870016 |last2=Stahl |first2=Z |last3=Belmaker |first3=RH}}</ref> [[cancer]], and [[macular degeneration]], yet their benefit in these conditions has also not been verified.<ref name=\"medline\"/> \n\nThe fish used as sources do not actually produce omega-3 fatty acids, but instead accumulate them by consuming either [[microalgae]] or [[prey fish]] that have accumulated [[omega-3 fatty acid]]s. Fatty predatory fish like [[shark]]s, [[swordfish]], [[tilefish]], and [[albacore tuna]] may be high in omega-3 fatty acids, but due to their position at the top of the [[food chain]], these species may also accumulate [[toxic]] substances through [[biomagnification]]. For this reason, the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]] recommends limiting consumption (especially for women of childbearing age) of certain (predatory) fish species (e.g. [[albacore tuna]], [[shark]], [[king mackerel]], [[tilefish]] and [[swordfish]]) due to high levels of the toxic contaminant [[Mercury (element)|mercury]]. [[Polychlorinated dibenzodioxins|Dioxin]], [[polychlorinated biphenyl|PCBs]] and [[chlordane]] are also present.<ref name=petsworldtoday>{{cite web|url=https://www.petsworldtoday.in/2020/02/best-fish-to-eat.html |title= Best fish to eat|author=Venus Nandi|date=2020-02-09|accessdate=9 February 2020}}</ref> Fish is rich in protein and other vitamins [[aquaculture]] feed. More than 50 percent of the world's fish oil used in [[Commercial fish feed|aquaculture feed]] is fed to [[Aquaculture of salmon|farmed salmon]].<ref>[[FAO]]: World Review of Fisheries and Aquaculture 2008: [ftp://ftp.fao.org/docrep/fao/011/i0250e/i0250e03.pdf Highlights of Special Studies]|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Rome.</ref>\n\nMarine and freshwater fish oil vary in contents of [[arachidonic acid]], EPA and DHA.<ref name=\"pmid7666244\">{{cite journal |pmid=7666244 |year=1995 |last1=Innis |first1=Sheila M. |last2=Rioux |first2=France M. |last3=Auestad |first3=Nancy |last4=Ackman |first4=Robert G. |title=Marine and freshwater fish oil varying in arachidonic, eicosapentaenoic and docosahexaenoic acids differ in their effects on organ lipids and fatty acids in growing rats |volume=125 |issue=9 |pages=2286\u201393 |journal=The Journal of Nutrition |url=http://jn.nutrition.org/content/125/9/2286.short|doi=10.1093/jn/125.9.2286 }}</ref> The various species range from lean to fatty and their oil content in the tissues has been shown to vary from 0.7% to 15.5%.<ref name=Gruger1964>{{cite journal |last1=Gruger |first1=E. H. |author2=Nelson, R. W.; Stansby, M. E.|title=Fatty acid composition of oils from 21 species of marine fish, freshwater fish and shellfish|journal=Journal of the American Oil Chemists' Society|date=1 October 1964|volume=41|issue=10|pages=662\u201367|doi=10.1007/BF02661403}}</ref> They also differ in their effects on organ lipids.<ref name=\"pmid7666244\" /> Studies have revealed that there is no relation between total fish intake or estimated omega\u22123 fatty acid intake from all fish, and serum omega\u22123 fatty acid concentrations.<ref name=\"pmid17158409\">{{cite journal|last1=Philibert|first1=A|author2=Vanier, C; Abdelouahab, N; Chan, HM; Mergler, D|title=Fish intake and serum fatty acid profiles from freshwater fish|journal=The American Journal of Clinical Nutrition|date=December 2006|volume=84|issue=6|pages=1299\u2013307|pmid=17158409|doi=10.1093/ajcn/84.6.1299}}</ref> Only fatty fish intake, particularly salmonid, and estimated EPA + DHA intake from fatty fish has been observed to be significantly associated with increase in serum EPA + DHA.<ref name=\"pmid17158409\" />\n\nAs of 2019, the US [[Food and Drug Administration]] has approved four fish oil-based prescription drugs, such as Lovaza, Omtryg (both [[omega-3 acid ethyl esters]]), Vascepa ([[ethyl eicosapentaenoic acid]]), and Epanova ([[omega-3 carboxylic acids]]).<ref name=\"skulas19\">{{cite journal |last1=Skulas-Ray |first1=Ann C. |last2=Wilson |first2=Peter W.F. |last3=Harris |first3=William S. |last4=Brinton |first4=Eliot A. |last5=Kris-Etherton |first5=Penny M. |last6=Richter |first6=Chesney K. |last7=Jacobson |first7=Terry A. |last8=Engler |first8=Mary B. |last9=Miller |first9=Michael |last10=Robinson |first10=Jennifer G. |last11=Blum |first11=Conrad B. |last12=Rodriguez-Leyva |first12=Delfin |last13=de Ferranti |first13=Sarah D. |last14=Welty |first14=Francine K. |title=Omega-3 Fatty Acids for the Management of Hypertriglyceridemia: A Science Advisory From the American Heart Association |journal=Circulation |date=2019 |volume=140 |issue=12 |doi=10.1161/CIR.0000000000000709 |pmid=31422671 |display-authors=8}}</ref>\n\n== Uses ==\nOften marketed and sold for consumption as part of the diet or in dietary supplements in contemporary societies, fish oils also have found roles in external use, as [[emollient]]s<ref>\n{{cite book\n| last1                 = Talakoub\n| first1                = Lily\n| last2                 = Neuhaus\n| first2                = Isaac M.\n| last3                 = Yu\n| first3                = Siegrid S.\n| chapter               = Chapter 2: Cosmoceuticals\n| editor1-last          = Alam\n| editor1-first         = Murad\n| editor1-link          = Murad Alam\n| editor2-last          = Gladstone\n| editor2-first         = Hayes B.\n| editor3-last          = Tung\n| editor3-first         = Rebecca\n| title                 = Cosmetic Dermatology\n| chapter-url                   = https://books.google.com/books?id=lUI9zg7GDuUC\n| series                = Requisites in dermatology\n| publisher             = Elsevier Health Sciences\n| date      = 2008\n| page                  = 9 \n| isbn                  = 9780702031434\n| accessdate            = 2014-10-23\n| quote                 = Other oils used as emollients include fish oil, petrolatum, shea butter, and sunflower seed oil.\n}}\n</ref>\nor as general [[ointment]]s<ref>\n{{cite book\n| last1                 = Burch\n| first1                = Ernest S.\n| title                 = Social Life in Northwest Alaska: The Structure of I\u00f1upiaq Eskimo Nations\n| url                   = https://books.google.com/books?id=tfQzWXTtifsC\n| publisher             = University of Alaska Press\n| date      = 2006\n| page                  = 278\n| isbn                  = 9781889963921\n| accessdate            = 2014-10-23\n| quote                 = Oil was also used externally as an ointment to heal cold sores, cuts, insect bites, frostbite, rashes - in short, skin problems of all kinds. Duck or goose body-cavity fat was apparently as useful as seal or fish oil in dealing with skin problems.\n}}\n</ref>\nas well as in [[body art]],<ref>\n{{cite book\n| last1                 = Heartney\n| first1                = Eleanor\n| chapter               = Zhang Huan: Becoming the Body\n| title                 = Zhang Huan: Altered States\n| chapter-url                   = http://www.zhanghuan.com/ShowText.asp?id=30&sClassID=1\n| publisher             = Charta and Asia Society\n| date      = 2007\n| isbn                  = 978-8881586417\n| accessdate            = 2014-10-23\n| quote                 = This becomes abundantly clear in the work of Chinese body artist Zhang Huan. In the course of his career, Zhang Huan has subjected himself to painful trials: sitting motionless for hours in an outhouse covered in honey and fish oil while flies crawled over his body [...].\n}}\n</ref>\nor for alleged insulation against cold.<ref>\nIlse Schreiber: ''Die Schwestern aus Memel'' (1936), quoted, and extract translated in:\n{{cite book\n| last1                 = Strzelczyk\n| first1                = Florentine\n| chapter               = 16: 'Fighting against Manitou': German Identity and Ilse Schreiber's Canada Novels ''Die Schwestern aus Memel'' (1936) and ''Die Flucht in Paradies'' (1939)\n| editor1-last          = McFarland\n| editor1-first         = Rob\n| editor2-last          = James\n| editor2-first         = Michelle Stott\n| title                 = Sophie Discovers Amerika: German-Speaking Women Write the New World\n| chapter-url                   = https://books.google.com/books?id=G_ezAwAAQBAJ\n| series                = Studies in German Literature Linguistics and Culture\n| volume                = 148\n| publisher             = Boydell & Brewer\n| date      = 2014\n| page                  = 207\n| isbn                  = 9781571135865\n| quote                 = Hoffentlich zogen die Eltern in eine Gegend, wo es recht viele Eingeborene gab. Indianer, die nur von Jagd und Fischfang leben. Ach, und wom\u00f6glich Eskimos, die sich mit Tran einschmieren, um sich gegen die K\u00e4lte zu sch\u00fctzen und rohes Fleisch essen [...]. [She hoped her parents would move to an area where there were many aboriginals. Indians who live solely by hunting and fishing. Oh, and if possible Eskimos who smear themselves with fish oil to protect themselves from the cold, and who eat raw meat.]\n}}\n</ref>\n\n[[File:FMIB 36337 Rendering Room where the Fish Waste was Treated to Separate the Valuable Oil Content, Port Dover, Ont.jpeg|thumb|Fish oil rendering in [[Port Dover, Ontario]], 1918]]\n\n== Nutritional details ==\nThe most widely available dietary source of EPA and DHA is cold-water [[oily fish]], such as [[salmon]], [[herring]], [[mackerel]], [[anchovies]], and [[sardine]]s. Oils from these fish have a profile of around seven times as much [[omega-3 oil]]s as [[Omega-6 fatty acid|omega-6 oils]]. Other oily fish, such as [[tuna]], also contain omega-3 in somewhat lesser amounts. Although fish is a dietary source of omega-3 oils, fish do not synthesize them; they obtain them from the [[algae]] ([[microalgae]] in particular) or [[plankton]] in their diets.<ref>\n{{cite journal \n|id={{INIST|2356641}} \n|doi=10.1007/s003000050274 \n|title=Lipids and fatty acids in ice algae and phytoplankton from the Marginal Ice Zone in the Barents Sea |year=1998 |last1=Falk-Petersen |first1=S. |last2=Sargent |first2=J. R. |last3=Henderson |first3=J. |last4=Hegseth |first4=E. N. |last5=Hop |first5=H. |last6=Okolodkov |first6=Y. B. |journal=Polar Biology |volume=20 |issue=1 \n|pages=41\u201347\n}}\n</ref>\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=1 style=\"border-collapse:collapse;width:300px;\"\n|+Grams of omega-3 fatty acids per 3oz (85g) serving of popular fish.<ref name=\"ahao3\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.americanheart.org/presenter.jhtml?identifier=3013797\n| title = Fish, Levels of Mercury and Omega-3 Fatty Acids\n| publisher = American Heart Association\n| accessdate = 6 October 2010\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100709203304/http://www.americanheart.org/presenter.jhtml?identifier=3013797\n| archive-date = 9 July 2010\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref><ref name=\"KrisEtherton2002\">{{Cite journal\n | last1 = Kris-Etherton\n | first1 = Penny M.\n | author2 = William S. Harris, Lawrence J. Appel\n | title = Fish Consumption, Fish Oil, Omega-3 Fatty Acids, and Cardiovascular Disease\n | journal = Circulation\n | volume = 106\n | issue = 21\n | pages = 2747\u201357\n | year = 2002\n | doi = 10.1161/01.CIR.0000038493.65177.94\n | pmid=12438303}}</ref>\n!| Common name             || grams\n|-\n| [[Herring]], [[sardine]]s  || 1.3\u20132\n|-\n| [[Spanish mackerel]], [[Atlantic mackerel|Atlantic]], [[Pacific mackerel|Pacific]]        || 1.1\u20131.7\n|-\n| [[Salmon]]               || 1.1\u20131.9\n|-\n| [[Halibut]]              || 0.60\u20131.12\n|-\n| [[Tuna]]                 || 0.21\u20131.1\n|-\n| [[Swordfish]]            || 0.97\n|-\n| [[New Zealand green-lipped mussel|Greenshell/lipped mussels]] || 0.95<ref name=\"o3c\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.omega-3centre.com/sources_long_chain.html |title=Omega-3 Centre\n|accessdate=27 July 2008\n|work=Omega-3 sources\n|publisher=Omega-3 Centre\n|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080718174524/http://www.omega-3centre.com/sources_long_chain.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2008-07-18}}</ref><!--Source: Fatty acid database, RMIT University-->\n|-\n| [[Tilefish]]             || 0.9\n|-\n| [[Tuna]] (canned, light) || 0.17\u20130.24\n|-\n| [[Pollock]]              || 0.45\n|-\n| [[Cod]]                  || 0.15\u20130.24\n|-\n| [[Catfish]]              || 0.22\u20130.3\n|-\n| [[Flounder]]             || 0.48\n|-\n| [[Grouper]]              || 0.23\n|-\n| [[Mahi mahi]]            || 0.13\n|-\n| [[Orange roughy]]        || 0.028\n|-\n| [[Red snapper (fish)|Red snapper]]          || 0.29\n|-\n| [[Shark]]                || 0.83\n|-\n| [[King mackerel]]        || 0.36\n|-\n| [[Blue grenadier|Hoki (blue grenadier)]]          || 0.41\n|-\n| [[Silver gemfish]]                                       || 0.40\n|-\n| [[Cod#Perciformes|Blue eye cod]]                  || 0.31\n|-\n| [[Sydney rock oyster]]               || 0.30\n|-\n| [[Canned tuna|Tuna, canned]]                  || 0.23\n|-\n| [[Lutjanidae|Snapper]]                                       || 0.22\n|-\n| [[Barramundi|Barramundi, saltwater]]               || 0.100\n|-\n| [[Giant tiger prawn]]                             || 0.100\n|}\n\nFor comparison, note the omega-3 levels in some common non-fish foods:\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=1 style=\"border-collapse:collapse;width:300px;\"\n|+Grams of omega-3 fatty acids per 3oz (85g) serving of common non-fish foods.<ref name=\"ahao3\" />\n!| Name             || grams\n|-\n| [[Flaxseeds]]                || 19.55\n|-\n| [[Chia seeds]]                || 14.8\n|-\n| [[Hemp seeds]]                || 7.4\n|-\n| [[Walnut]]                || 1.7\n|-\n| [[Soybean]]                || 1.1\n|-\n| [[Butter]]          || 0.27\n|-\n| [[Egg (food)|Eggs, large regular]]                || 0.109<ref name=\"o3c\"/>\n|-\n| [[Red meat|Lean red meat]]                        || 0.031\n|-\n| [[Turkey]]                                        || 0.030\n|-\n| [[Cereal|Cereals, rice, pasta, etc.]]             ||   0.00\n|-\n| [[Fruit]]                                         ||   0.00\n|-\n| [[Milk|Milk, regular]]                             ||   0.00\n|-\n| [[Bread|Bread, regular]]                           ||   0.00\n|-\n| [[Vegetables]]                                    ||   0.00\n|}\n\n== Health effects==\n[[File:Kepler Cod Liver Oil, by Burroughs Wellcome & Co Wellcome L0016947.jpg|thumb|Kepler Cod Liver Oil with Malt Extract]]\n\n=== Various recommendations ===\nIn a 2009 letter on a pending revision to the Dietary Guidelines for Americans, the American Heart Association recommended 250\u2013500&nbsp;mg/day of EPA and DHA.<ref name=\"AHA-2012\">{{cite web |title=Re: 2010 Dietary Guidelines for Americans |url=http://www.heart.org/idc/groups/heart-public/@wcm/@adv/documents/downloadable/ucm_312853.pdf |work=Jan 2009 |publisher=American Heart Association}}</ref> The Guidelines were revised again for 2015-2020; included is a recommendation that adults consume at least eight ounces of a variety of types of fish per week, equating to at least 250&nbsp;mg/day of EPA + DHA.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}} The Food and Drug Administration recommends not exceeding 3 grams per day of EPA + DHA from all sources, with no more than 2 grams per day from dietary supplements.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fda.gov/NewsEvents/Newsroom/PressAnnouncements/2004/ucm108351.htm|title=2004 \u2013 FDA Announces Qualified Health Claims for Omega-3 Fatty Acids|website=www.fda.gov|language=en|access-date=2016-05-25}}</ref>\n\n=== Prostate cancer ===\nThe effect of fish oil consumption on [[prostate cancer]] is controversial,<ref name=Hein2012>{{cite journal|last1=Heinze|first1=VM|author2=Actis, AB|title=Dietary conjugated linoleic acid and long-chain n-3 fatty acids in mammary and prostate cancer protection: a review|journal=International Journal of Food Sciences and Nutrition|date=February 2012|volume=63|issue=1|pages=66\u201378|pmid=21762028|doi=10.3109/09637486.2011.598849}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title = Circulating fatty acids and prostate cancer risk: individual participant meta-analysis of prospective studies|journal = Journal of the National Cancer Institute|date = 2014-09-01|issn = 1460-2105|pmc = 4188122|pmid = 25210201|volume = 106|issue = 9|doi = 10.1093/jnci/dju240|first = Francesca L.|last = Crowe|first2 = Paul N.|last2 = Appleby|first3 = Ruth C.|last3 = Travis|first4 = Matt|last4 = Barnett|first5 = Theodore M.|last5 = Brasky|first6 = H. Bas|last6 = Bueno-de-Mesquita|first7 = Veronique|last7 = Chajes|first8 = Jorge E.|last8 = Chavarro|first9 = Maria-Dolores|last9 = Chirlaque|page=dju240}}</ref> as one study showed decreased risk with higher blood levels of [[Docosapentaenoic acid#all-cis-7,10,13,16,19-docosapentaenoic acid (clupanodonic acid)|DPA]], whereas another reported increased risk of more aggressive prostate cancer with higher blood levels of combined [[Eicosapentaenoic acid|EPA]] and [[Docosahexaenoic acid|DHA]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Chua|first1=Michael E.|last2=Sio|first2=Maria Christina D.|last3=Sorongon|first3=Mishell C.|last4=Morales Jr|first4=Marcelino L. Jr.|date=May\u2013June 2013|title=The relevance of serum levels of long chain omega-3 polyunsaturated fatty acids and prostate cancer risk: a meta-analysis|journal=Canadian Urological Association Journal|volume=7|issue=5\u20136|pages=E333\u201343|doi=10.5489/cuaj.1056|pmid=23766835|pmc=3668400}}</ref> Some evidence indicated an association between high blood levels of omega-3 fatty acids and an increased prostate cancer risk.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Brasky TM, Darke AK, Song X |title=Plasma phospholipid fatty acids and prostate cancer risk in the SELECT trial |journal=J. Natl. Cancer Inst. |volume=105 |issue=15 |pages=1132\u201341 | date=August 2013 |pmid=23843441 |pmc=3735464 |doi=10.1093/jnci/djt174|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n\n=== Cardiovascular ===\nThere has been a great deal of controversy in recent years about the role of fish oil in cardiovascular disease, with recent meta-analyses reaching different conclusions about its potential impact.<ref name=\"half full\">{{cite journal |last1=Maki |first1=KC |last2=Dicklin |first2=MR |title=Omega-3 Fatty Acid Supplementation and Cardiovascular Disease Risk: Glass Half Full or Time to Nail the Coffin Shut? |journal=Nutrients |date=4 July 2018 |volume=10 |issue=7 |pages=864 |doi=10.3390/nu10070864 |pmid=29973554|pmc=6073248 }}</ref> Multiple evaluations suggest fish oil has little or no reduction in cardiovascular mortality, in distinction to earlier observational data, though there appears to be a small reduction in the incidence of actual cardiac events and strokes with its use.<ref name=\"Cochrane 2018 1\">{{cite journal|last1=Abdelhamid|first1=AS|last2=Brown|first2=TJ|last3=Brainard|first3=JS|last4=Biswas|first4=P|last5=Thorpe|first5=GC|last6=Moore|first6=HJ|last7=Deane|first7=KH|last8=AlAbdulghafoor|first8=FK|last9=Summerbell|first9=CD|last10=Worthington|first10=HV|last11=Song|first11=F|date=November 2018|title=Omega-3 fatty acids for the primary and secondary prevention of cardiovascular disease.|url=|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|volume=11|pages=CD003177|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD003177.pub4|pmc=6517311|pmid=30521670|last12=Hooper|first12=L}}</ref><ref name=\"Cochrane 2018 2\">{{cite journal|last1=Abdelhamid|first1=AS|last2=Martin|first2=N|last3=Bridges|first3=C|last4=Brainard|first4=JS|last5=Wang|first5=X|last6=Brown|first6=TJ|last7=Hanson|first7=S|last8=Jimoh|first8=OF|last9=Ajabnoor|first9=SM|last10=Deane|first10=KH|last11=Song|first11=F|date=November 2018|title=Polyunsaturated fatty acids for the primary and secondary prevention of cardiovascular disease.|url=|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|volume=11|pages=CD012345|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD012345.pub3|pmc=6517012|pmid=30484282|last12=Hooper|first12=L}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Goel |first1=A |last2=Pothineni |first2=NV |last3=Singhal |first3=M |last4=Paydak |first4=H |last5=Saldeen |first5=T |last6=Mehta |first6=JL |title=Fish, Fish Oils and Cardioprotection: Promise or Fish Tale? |journal=International Journal of Molecular Sciences |date=22 November 2018 |volume=19 |issue=12 |pages=3703 |doi=10.3390/ijms19123703 |pmid=30469489|pmc=6321588 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |pmid=30763028 |year=2007 |author1=John M. Eisenberg Center for Clinical Decisions Communications Science |title=Omega-3 Fatty Acids and Cardiovascular Disease: Current State of the Evidence }}</ref>  In 2007, the [[American Heart Association]] had recommended the consumption of 1 [[gram]] of fish oil daily, preferably by eating fish, for patients with [[coronary artery disease]], but cautioned pregnant and nursing women to avoid eating fish with high potential for [[mercury (element)|mercury]] contaminants including mackerel, shark, and swordfish.<ref name=\"AHA-2007\">{{cite web |url=http://www.americanheart.org/presenter.jhtml?identifier=4632 | title= Fish and Omega-3 Fatty Acids|accessdate=9 February 2007 |publisher=American Heart Association}}</ref> (Optimal dosage was related to body weight.)\n\nThe US [[National Institutes of Health]] lists three conditions for which fish oil and other omega-3 sources are most highly recommended: [[hypertriglyceridemia]] (high triglyceride level), preventing secondary [[cardiovascular disease]], and [[hypertension]] (high blood pressure). It then lists 27 other conditions for which there is less evidence. It also lists possible safety concerns: \"Intake of 3 grams per day or greater of omega-3 fatty acids may increase the risk of bleeding, although there is little evidence of significant bleeding risk at lower doses. Very large intakes of fish oil/omega-3 fatty acids may increase the risk of hemorrhagic (bleeding) stroke.\"<ref name=\"medline\">{{cite web |url=https://nccih.nih.gov/health/omega3/introduction.htm#hed4|title=Omega-3 Supplements: In Depth |author = NIH Medline Plus |date=August 2015|accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nThere is also some evidence that fish oil may have a beneficial effect on certain [[cardiac dysrhythmia|abnormal heart rhythms]].<ref>{{cite journal|author=Charnock John S |year=1999 |title=The role of omega-3 polyunsaturated fatty acid-enriched diets in the prevention of ventricular fibrillation |url=http://apjcn.nhri.org.tw/server/apjcn/Volume8/vol8.3/Charnock.pdf |journal=Asia Pacific Journal of Clinical Nutrition |volume=8 |issue=3 |pages=226\u201330 |doi=10.1046/j.1440-6047.1999.00115.x |pmid=24394167}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Li GR, Sun HY, Zhang XH, Cheng LC, Chiu SW, Tse HF, Lau CP |year=2009 |title=Omega-3 polyunsaturated fatty acids inhibit transient outward and ultra-rapid delayed rectifier K+currents and Na+current in human atrial myocytes|url=http://cardiovascres.oxfordjournals.org/content/81/2/286.full |journal=Cardiovasc Res |volume=81 |issue=2 |pages=286\u201393 |doi=10.1093/cvr/cvn322 |pmid=19029136 }}</ref> However, a 2012 [[meta-analysis]] found no such significant benefit.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = A meta-analysis of omega-3 fatty acids and incidence of atrial fibrillation|journal = Journal of the American College of Nutrition|date = 2012-02-01|issn = 1541-1087|pmid = 22661621|pages = 4\u201313|volume = 31|issue = 1|first = Owais|last = Khawaja|first2 = J. Michael|last2 = Gaziano|first3 = Luc|last3 = Djouss\u00e9|doi=10.1080/07315724.2012.10720003}}</ref>\n\nA 2008 [[meta-study]] by the ''[[Canadian Medical Association Journal]]'' found fish oil supplementation did not demonstrate any preventative benefit to cardiac patients with [[ventricular arrhythmia]]s.<ref>{{cite journal |pages=181\u201382 |doi=10.1503/cmaj.071654 |title=Should patients with cardiovascular disease take fish oil? |year=2008 |last1=Nair |first1=G. M. |last2=Connolly |first2=S. J. |journal=Canadian Medical Association Journal |volume=178 |issue=2 |pmid=18195293 |pmc=2174997}}</ref> A 2012 meta-analysis published in the [[Journal of the American Medical Association]], covering 20 studies and 68,680 patients, found that Omega-3 Fatty Acid supplementation did not reduce the chance of death, cardiac death, heart attack or stroke.<ref>{{cite journal |pages=1024\u201333 |doi=10.1001/2012.jama.11374 |title=Association Between Omega-3 Fatty Acid Supplementation and Risk of Major Cardiovascular Disease Events: A Systematic Review and Meta-analysis |year=2012 |last1=Rizos |first1=E. C. |last2=Ntzani |first2=E. E. |journal=Journal of the American Medical Association |volume=308 |issue=10 |pmid=22968891 |last3=Bika |first3=E |last4=Kostapanos |first4=MS |last5=Elisaf |first5=MS}}</ref>\n\n=== Hypertension ===\nThere have been some human trials that have concluded that consuming omega-3 fatty acids slightly reduces blood pressure (DHA could be more effective than EPA). It is important to note that because omega-3 fatty acids can increase the risk of bleeding, a qualified healthcare provider should be consulted before supplementing with fish oil.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mayoclinic.org/drugs-supplements/omega-3-fatty-acids-fish-oil-alpha-linolenic-acid/evidence/HRB-20059372 |title=Omega-3 fatty acids, fish oil, alpha-linolenic acid |url-status=live |accessdate=4 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Mental health ===\nA 2008 [[Cochrane Library|Cochrane]] [[systematic review]] found that limited data is available. In the one eligible study, omega-3s were an effective adjunctive therapy for depressed but not manic symptoms in [[bipolar disorder]]. The authors found an \"acute need\" for more randomised controlled trials.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Montgomery P, Richardson AJ|title=Omega-3 fatty acids for bipolar disorder |journal=Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews |year=2008 |issue=2 |doi=10.1002/14651858.CD005169.pub2 |pmid=18425912 |page=CD005169 |editor1-last=Montgomery |editor1-first=Paul}}</ref>\n\nA 2009 metastudy found that patients taking omega-3 supplements with a higher EPA:DHA ratio experienced fewer depressive symptoms. The studies provided evidence that EPA may be more efficacious than DHA in treating depression. However, this metastudy concluded that due to the identified limitations of the included studies, larger, randomized trials are needed to confirm these findings.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1080/07315724.2009.10719785 |title=EPA but Not DHA Appears to Be Responsible for the Efficacy of Omega-3 Long Chain Polyunsaturated Fatty Acid Supplementation in Depression: Evidence from a Meta-Analysis of Randomized Controlled Trials |year=2009 |last1=Martins |first1=Julian G |journal=Journal of the American College of Nutrition |volume=28 |issue=5 |pages=525\u201342 |pmid=20439549}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2011 [[meta-analysis]] of [[PubMed]] articles about fish oil and depression from 1965 to 2010, researchers found that \"nearly all of the treatment efficacy observed in the published literature may be attributable to publication bias.\"<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/mp.2011.100 |title=Omega-3 fatty acids for the treatment of depression: Systematic review and meta-analysis |year=2011 |last1=Bloch |first1=M H |last2=Hannestad |first2=J |journal=Molecular Psychiatry |volume=17 |issue=12 |pages=1272\u201382 |pmid=21931319 |pmc=3625950}}</ref>\n\nA 2014 meta-analysis of eleven trials conducted respectively on patients with a DSM-defined diagnosis of major depressive disorder (MDD) and of eight trials with patients with depressive symptomatology but no diagnosis of MDD demonstrated significant clinical benefit of omega-3 PUFA treatment compared to placebo. The study concluded that: \"The use of omega-3 PUFA is effective in patients with diagnosis of MDD and on depressive patients without diagnosis of MDD.\"<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Grosso | first1 = G. | last2 = Pajak | first2 = A. | last3 = Marventano | first3 = S. | last4 = Castellano | first4 = S. | last5 = Galvano | first5 = F. | last6 = Bucolo | first6 = C. | last7 = Caraci | first7 = F. | year = 2014 | title = Role of Omega-3 Fatty Acids in the Treatment of Depressive Disorders: A Comprehensive Meta-Analysis of Randomized Clinical Trials | journal = PLoS ONE | volume = 9 | issue = 5| page = e96905 | doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0096905 | pmid=24805797 | pmc=4013121| bibcode = 2014PLoSO...996905G }}</ref>\n\n=== Alzheimer's disease ===\nA [[Cochrane Library|Cochrane]] [[meta-analysis]] published in June 2012 found no significant protective effect for cognitive decline for those aged 60 and over and who started taking fatty acids after this age. A co-author of the study said to ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', \"Our analysis suggests that there is currently no evidence that omega-3 fatty acid supplements provide a benefit for memory or concentration in later life\".<ref>{{cite news |author=Sifferlin, Alexandra |date=13 June 2012|title=Fish Oil Fail: Omega-3s May Not Protect Brain Health After All |url=http://healthland.time.com/2012/06/13/fish-oil-fail-omega-3s-may-not-protect-brain-health-after-all/ |work=Time |accessdate=19 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Psoriasis ===\nDiets supplemented with [[cod liver oil]] have shown beneficial\neffects on [[psoriasis]].<ref>{{cite journal |pages=706\u201314 |doi=10.1111/j.1365-2133.2005.06781.x |title=Diet and psoriasis: experimental data and clinical evidence |year=2005 |last1=Wolters |first1=M. |journal=British Journal of Dermatology |volume=153 |issue=4 |pmid=16181450}}</ref>\n\n=== Pregnancy ===\nSome studies reported better psychomotor development at 30 months of age in infants whose mothers received fish oil supplements for the first four months of lactation.<ref name=Jensen10>{{cite journal |pages=900\u201305 |doi=10.1016/j.jpeds.2010.06.006 |title=Effects of Early Maternal Docosahexaenoic Acid Intake on Neuropsychological Status and Visual Acuity at Five Years of Age of Breast-Fed Term Infants |year=2010 |last1=Jensen |first1=Craig L. |last2=Voigt |first2=Robert G. |last3=Llorente |first3=Antolin M. |last4=Peters |first4=Sarika U. |last5=Prager |first5=Thomas C. |last6=Zou |first6=Yali L. |last7=Rozelle |first7=Judith C. |last8=Turcich |first8=Marie R. |last9=Fraley |first9=J. Kennard |journal=The Journal of Pediatrics |volume=157 |issue=6 |pmid=20655543 |last10=Anderson |first10=Robert E. |last11=Heird |first11=William C.}}</ref> In addition, five-year-old children whose mothers received modest algae based docosahexaenoic acid supplementation for the first 4 months of breastfeeding performed better on a test of sustained attention. This suggests that [[docosahexaenoic acid]] intake during early infancy confers long-term benefits on specific aspects of neurodevelopment.<ref name=Jensen10 />\n\nIn addition, provision of fish oil during pregnancy may reduce an infant\u2019s sensitization to common food allergens and reduce the prevalence and severity of certain skin diseases in the first year of life. This effect may persist until adolescence with a reduction in prevalence and/or severity of eczema, hay fever and asthma.<ref name=Calder10>{{cite journal |pages=373\u201380 |doi=10.1017/S0029665110001552 |title=Is there a role for fatty acids in early life programming of the immune system? |year=2010 |last1=Calder |first1=Philip C. |last2=Kremmyda |first2=Lefkothea-Stella |last3=Vlachava |first3=Maria |last4=Noakes |first4=Paul S. |last5=Miles |first5=Elizabeth A. |journal=Proceedings of the Nutrition Society |volume=69 |issue=3 |pmid=20462467}}</ref>\n\n=== Crohn's disease ===\nA 2014 Cochrane review found that, based on two large studies, fish oil supplements did not appear to be effective for maintenance of remission in [[Crohn's disease]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lev-Tzion|first1=R|last2=Griffiths|first2=AM|last3=Leder|first3=O|last4=Turner|first4=D|title=Omega 3 fatty acids (fish oil) for maintenance of remission in Crohn's disease.|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|date=28 February 2014|volume=2|issue=2|pages=CD006320|pmid=24585498|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD006320.pub4}}</ref>\n\n==Supplement quality and concerns==\nFish oil is a commonly used [[dietary supplement]], with sales in the U.S. alone reaching $976 million in 2009.<ref name=clpr>{{cite web |title=ConsumerLab.com Finds Quality Problems with Nearly Thirty Percent of Fish Oil Supplements Reviewed; \"Fishy\" Claims Identified: Softgels and Liquids for Adults, Children and Pets Tested, Including Krill Oil and Algal Oil Supplements|url=http://www.consumerlab.com/news/fish_oil_supplements_reviewed/09_28_2010/|publisher=ConsumerLab.com|accessdate=20 October 2012|date=28 September 2010}}{{dubious|date=December 2012}}</ref>\nProblems of quality have been identified in periodic tests by independent researchers of marketed supplements containing fish oil and other marine oils. These problems include contamination, inaccurate listing of EPA and DHA levels, spoilage and formulation issues.<ref>[http://www.consumerlab.com/results/index.asp Reviews of Supplements and Health Products] ''ConsumerLab''.</ref>\n\n===Contamination===\nFish can accumulate toxins such as mercury, dioxins, and [[polychlorinated biphenyl]]s (PCBs), and spoiled fish oil may produce peroxides.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Levels of dioxins, dibenzofurans, PCB and DDE congeners in pooled food samples collected in 1995 at supermarkets across the United States|journal = Chemosphere|date = 1997-04-01|issn = 0045-6535|pmid = 9134677|pages = 1437\u201347|volume = 34|issue = 5\u20137|first = A.|last = Schecter|first2 = P.|last2 = Cramer|first3 = K.|last3 = Boggess|first4 = J.|last4 = Stanley|first5 = J. R.|last5 = Olson|doi=10.1016/s0045-6535(97)00440-2|bibcode = 1997Chmsp..34.1437S}}</ref> There appears to be little risk of contamination by microorganisms, proteins, lysophospholipids, cholesterol, and trans-fats.<ref name=norstudy>{{cite book |title=Description of the processes in the value chain and risk assessment of decomposition substances and oxidation products in fish oils |url=http://english.vkm.no/dav/0fd42c8b08.pdf |publisher=Norwegian Scientific Committee for Food Safety |accessdate=19 October 2012 |year=2011 |isbn=978-82-8259-035-8 |first1=Marit |last1=Aursand |first2=Revilija |last2=Mozuraityte |first3=Kristin |last3=Hamre |first4=Helle |last4=Knutsen |first5=Amund |last5=Maage |first6=Augustine |last6=Arukwe |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160909213119/http://english.vkm.no/dav/0fd42c8b08.pdf |archive-date=9 September 2016 |url-status=dead }}{{page needed|date=December 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Dioxins and PCBs===\nDioxins and PCBs may be carcinogenic at low levels of exposure over time. These substances are identified and measured in one of two categories, dioxin-like PCBs and total PCBs. While the U.S. FDA has not set a limit for PCBs in supplements, the Global Organization for EPA and DHA (GOED) has established a guideline allowing for no more than 3 picograms of dioxin-like PCBs per gram of fish oil. In 2012, samples from 35 fish oil supplements were tested for PCBs. Trace amounts of PCBs were found in all samples, and two samples exceeded the GOED\u2018s limit.<ref name=review12>{{cite web |title=ConsumerLab.com Review: Fish Oil and Omega-3 Fatty Acid Supplements Review (Including Krill, Algae, and Calamari Oil)|url=https://www.consumerlab.com/reviews/fish_oil_supplements_review/omega3/ |publisher=ConsumerLab.com |accessdate=19 October 2012 |date=13 August 2012}}{{registration required|date=December 2012}}</ref> Although trace amounts of PCBs contribute to overall PCB exposure, Consumerlab.com claims the amounts reported by tests it ordered on fish oil supplements are far below those found in a single typical serving of fish.<ref name=review12 />\n\n===Spoilage===\nPeroxides can be produced when fish oil spoils. A study commissioned by the government of Norway concluded there would be some health concern related to the regular consumption of oxidized (rancid) fish/marine oils, particularly in regards to the gastrointestinal tract, but there is not enough data to determine the risk. The amount of spoilage and contamination in a supplement depends on the raw materials and processes of extraction, refining, concentration, encapsulation, storage and transportation.<ref name=norstudy /> ConsumerLab.com reports in its review that it found spoilage in test reports it ordered on some fish oil supplement products.<ref name=review12 />\n\n===EPA and DHA content===\nAccording to [[ConsumerLab.com]] tests, the concentrations of EPA and DHA in supplements can vary from between 8 and 80% fish oil content. The concentration depends on the source of the omega-3s, how the oil is processed, and the amounts of other ingredients included in the supplement.<ref name=review12 />\nA 2012 report claims 4 of 35 fish oil supplements it covered contained less{{quantify|date=December 2012}} EPA or DHA than was claimed on the label, and 3 of 35 contained more.{{quantify|date=December 2012}}<ref name=review12 />\nA ConsumerLab.com publication in 2010 claims 3 of 24 fish oil supplements it covered contained less{{quantify|date=December 2012}} EPA and/or DHA than was claimed on the label.<ref name=clpr /> However, the bioavailability of EPA and DHA from both capsular and emulsified fish oils has been shown to be high.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Raatz | first1 = SK | last2 = Redmon | first2 = JB | last3 = Wimmergren | first3 = N | last4 = Donadio | first4 = JV | last5 = Bibus | first5 = DM | year = 2009 | title = Enhanced absorption of omega-3 fatty acids after emulsified compared with encapsulated fish oil | url = | journal = Journal of the American Dietetic Association | volume = 109 | issue = 6| pages = 1076\u201381 | doi=10.1016/j.jada.2009.03.006| pmid = 19465191 | pmc = 2701654 }}</ref>\n\n===Formulation===\nFish oil supplements are available as liquids or capsules. Some capsules are enteric-coated to pass through the stomach before dissolving in the small intestine, thus helping prevent indigestion and \"fish burps\". Poorly manufactured enteric-coated products have the potential to release ingredients too early. ConsumerLab.com, a for-profit supplement testing company, reported that 1 of the 24 enteric-coated fish oil supplements it evaluated released ingredients prematurely.<ref name=clpr />\n\n===Prescription fish oil===\n{{Expand section | reason = The information here isn't that useful: doesn't lose much just dropping it. | date = January 2019 }}\nFish oil preparations that are only available with a doctor's prescription undergo the same [[Food and Drug Administration|FDA]] regulatory requirements as other prescription pharmaceuticals, with regard to both efficacy and safety.<ref name=\"bays2007\">{{cite journal | author=Bays H E | title=Safety Considerations with Omega-3 Fatty Acid Therapy | volume=99 | journal=The American Journal of Cardiology | issue=6 (Supplement 1) | date=19 March 2007 | pages=S35\u2013S43 | doi=10.1016/j.amjcard.2006.11.020 | pmid=17368277}}</ref> The prescription fish oil drugs are not similar to over-the-counter fish oil supplements. They are not be confused with each other.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicalxpress.com/news/2019-03-prescription-fish-oil-pill-lowers.html|title=Prescription fish oil pill lowers heart attack risk in those already on statins|website=medicalxpress.com|language=en-us|access-date=2019-09-25}}</ref> Prescription fish oil is considered a safe and effective option to reduce [[Triglyceride|triglycerides]]. There are various prescription fish oil products that have been approved and permitted by [[Food and Drug Administration|FDA]] for increasing triglyceride levels. Prescription fish oil products having DHA raise up the LDL-C levels to reduce triglycerides, like [[Fibrate|fibrates]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.medpagetoday.com/cardiology/dyslipidemia/81701|title=AHA Endorses Prescription Fish Oil for High Triglycerides|date=2019-08-20|website=www.medpagetoday.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-25}}</ref> Even the heart experts advise that prescription fish oil helps in decreasing additional levels of blood fats. As per the latest guideline, prescription fish oils might only help when triglycerides reaches a specific upper level.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.webmd.com/cholesterol-management/news/20190819/heart-experts-support-use-of-prescription-fish-oil|title=Heart Experts Support Use of Prescription Fish Oil|website=WebMD|language=en|access-date=2019-09-25}}</ref> Prescription fish oil pills, capsules and tablets have more omega-3 fatty acids than those which are non-prescribed. FDA regularly monitor those drugs for standards, quality and safety.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.webmd.com/diet/omega-3s-in-fish-oil-and-supplements-whats-your-best-strategy|title=Omega-3 Fish Oil: Supplements and Prescriptions|website=WebMD|language=en|access-date=2019-09-25}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2019, there are four fish oil-based prescription drugs approved by FDA for the treatment of hypertriglyceridemia,<ref name=\"skulas19\"/> namely:\n#Lovaza (omega-3 acid ethyl esters), approved on 10 November 2004.<ref>{{cite web |title=Drugs@FDA: FDA-Approved Drugs |url=https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/scripts/cder/daf/index.cfm?event=overview.process&ApplNo=021654 |website=www.accessdata.fda.gov |accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n#Vascepa (ethyl eicosapentaenoic acid), approved on 26 July 2012.<ref>{{cite web |title=Drug Approval Package: VASCEPA (icosapent ethyl) NDA #202057 |url=https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/drugsatfda_docs/nda/2012/202057_vascepa_toc.cfm |website=www.accessdata.fda.gov |accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref> On 13 December 2019, FDA also approved it as the first drug specifically \"to reduce cardiovascular risk among patients with elevated triglyceride levels.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=FDA approves use of drug to reduce risk of cardiovascular events in certain adult patient groups |url=https://www.fda.gov/news-events/press-announcements/fda-approves-use-drug-reduce-risk-cardiovascular-events-certain-adult-patient-groups |website=FDA |accessdate=15 January 2020 |language=en |date=17 December 2019}}</ref>\n#Epanova (omega-3 carboxylic acids), approved on 23 April 2014.<ref>{{cite web |title=Drugs@FDA: FDA-Approved Drugs |url=https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/scripts/cder/daf/index.cfm?event=overview.process&ApplNo=204977 |website=www.accessdata.fda.gov |accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref> Clinical trial on mixed [[dyslipidaemia]] (hypertriglyceridemia  with hypocholesterolemia) started in 2014<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Nicholls |first1=Stephen J. |last2=Lincoff |first2=A. Michael |last3=Bash |first3=Dianna |last4=Ballantyne |first4=Christie M. |last5=Barter |first5=Philip J. |last6=Davidson |first6=Michael H. |last7=Kastelein |first7=John J. P. |last8=Koenig |first8=Wolfgang |last9=McGuire |first9=Darren K. |last10=Mozaffarian |first10=Dariush |last11=Pedersen |first11=Terje R. |last12=Ridker |first12=Paul M. |last13=Ray |first13=Kausik |last14=Karlson |first14=Bj\u00f6rn W. |last15=Lundstr\u00f6m |first15=Torbj\u00f6rn |last16=Wolski |first16=Kathy |last17=Nissen |first17=Steven E. |title=Assessment of omega-3 carboxylic acids in statin-treated patients with high levels of triglycerides and low levels of high-density lipoprotein cholesterol: Rationale and design of the STRENGTH trial |journal=Clinical Cardiology |date=2018 |volume=41 |issue=10 |pages=1281\u20131288 |doi=10.1002/clc.23055 |pmid=30125052 |display-authors=8 |pmc=6489732}}</ref> found that it has no medical benefits, and the clinical trial was called of on 13 January 2019.<ref name=\"reuters20\">{{cite news |title=AstraZeneca to discontinue Epanova trial, expects $100 million writedown |url=https://in.reuters.com/article/us-astrazeneca-study/astrazeneca-to-discontinue-epanova-trial-expects-100-million-writedown-idINKBN1ZC0JQ |accessdate=15 January 2020 |work=Reuters |date=13 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n#Omtryg (omega-3 acid ethyl esters), approved on 5 May 2014.<ref>{{cite web |title=Drug Approval Package: Epanova (Omega-3-carboxylic acids) |url=https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/drugsatfda_docs/nda/2014/205060Orig1EpanovaTOC.cfm |website=www.accessdata.fda.gov |accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Dangers ==\nA 2013 review concluded that the potential for adverse events amongst older adults taking fish oil \"appear mild\u2013moderate at worst and are unlikely to be of clinical significance\".<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1186/1471-2318-13-41 |title=Fish oil administration in older adults: Is there potential for adverse events? A systematic review of the literature |year=2013 |last1=Villani |first1=Anthony M |last2=Crotty |first2=Maria |last3=Cleland |first3=Leslie G |last4=James |first4=Michael J |last5=Fraser |first5=Robert J |last6=Cobiac |first6=Lynne |last7=Miller |first7=Michelle D |journal=BMC Geriatrics |volume=13 |page=41 |pmid=23634646 |pmc=3664575 |issue=1}}</ref>\n\n=== Maximum intake ===\nThe FDA recommends that consumers do not exceed more than three grams per day of EPA and DHA combined, with no more than 2 grams from a dietary supplement.<ref>{{cite web|title=FDA Announces Qualified Health Claims for Omega-3 Fatty Acids|date=2004-09-08|url=https://www.fda.gov/SiteIndex/ucm108351.htm|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090722101454/https://www.fda.gov/SiteIndex/ucm108351.htm|accessdate=2017-08-21|archive-date=2009-07-22}}</ref> This is not the same as 3000&nbsp;mg of fish oil. A 1000&nbsp;mg pill typically has only 300&nbsp;mg of omega-3; 10 such pills would equal 3000&nbsp;mg of omega-3. \nAccording to the [[European Food Safety Authority]]'s (EFSA) Panel on Dietetic Products, Nutrition and Allergies, supplementation of 5 grams of EPA and DHA combined does not pose a safety concern for adults.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Scientific Opinion on the Tolerable Upper Intake Level of eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA), docosahexaenoic acid (DHA) and docosapentaenoic acid (DPA)|url=http://www.efsa.europa.eu/en/efsajournal/pub/2815|journal=EFSA Journal|volume=10|issue=7|accessdate=14 September 2014|doi=10.2903/j.efsa.2012.2815|year=2012}}</ref> A 1987 study found that healthy [[Greenlandic Inuit]] had an average intake of 5.7 grams of omega-3 EPA per day which had many effects including prolonged bleeding times, i.e., slower blood clotting.<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=3551346 |year=1987 |last1=Kantha |first1=SS |title=Dietary effects of fish oils on human health: A review of recent studies |volume=60 |issue=1 |pages=37\u201344 |pmc=2590235 |journal=The Yale Journal of Biology and Medicine}}</ref>\n\n=== Vitamins ===\nThe liver and liver products (such as [[cod liver oil]]) of fish and many animals (such as seals and whales) contain omega-3, but also the active form of [[vitamin A]]. At high levels, this form of the vitamin can be dangerous ([[Hypervitaminosis A]]).<ref name=\"lips2003\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1056/NEJMe020167 |title=Hypervitaminosis a and Fractures |year=2003 |last1=Lips |first1=Paul |journal=New England Journal of Medicine |volume=348 |issue=4 |pages=347\u201349 |pmid=12540650}}</ref>\n\n=== Toxic pollutants ===\nConsumers of oily fish should be aware of the potential presence of [[heavy metals]] and fat-soluble pollutants like [[Polychlorinated biphenyl|PCBs]] and [[Polychlorinated dibenzodioxins|dioxins]], which are known to [[Biomagnification|accumulate up the food chain]]. After extensive review, researchers from [[Harvard School of Public Health|Harvard's School of Public Health]] in the ''Journal of the American Medical Association'' (2006) reported that the benefits of fish intake generally far outweigh the potential risks.\n\nFish oil supplements came under scrutiny in 2006, when the [[Food Standards Agency]] in the UK and the [[Food Safety Authority of Ireland]] reported [[Polychlorinated biphenyl|PCB]] levels that exceeded the European maximum limits in several fish oil brands,<ref name=foodprod>{{cite web\n |url= http://www.foodproductiondaily.com/news/ng.asp?n=67059-boots-seven-seas-dioxins-fish-oil\n |title=Dioxins prompt second UK fish oil withdrawal|author=Jess Halliday\n |date=2006-04-13|accessdate=8 February 2007}}</ref><ref name=bbc>{{cite news\n | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/1911312.stm\n | date= 2002-04-06| title=Pollutants found in fish oil capsules\n |accessdate=8 February 2007 | work=BBC News}}</ref>\nwhich required temporary withdrawal of these brands. To address the concern over contaminated fish oil supplements, the International Fish Oil Standards (IFOS) Program, a third-party testing and accreditation program for fish oil products, was created by Nutrasource Diagnostics Inc. in Guelph, Ontario, Canada.<ref>[http://www.ifosprogram.com/IFOS/default.aspx International Fish Oil Standards] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120518181053/http://www.ifosprogram.com/IFOS/default.aspx |date=18 May 2012 }}.</ref>\n\nA March 2010 lawsuit filed by a California environmental group claimed that eight brands of fish oil supplements contained excessive levels of PCB's, including [[CVS/pharmacy]], [[Nature Made]], [[Rite Aid]], [[General Nutrition Centers|GNC]], Solgar, [[Twinlab]], Now Health, [[Omega Protein]] and Pharmavite. The majority of these products were either cod liver or shark liver oils. Those participating in the lawsuit claim that because the liver is the major filtering and detoxifying organ, PCB content may be higher in liver-based oils than in fish oil produced from the processing of whole fish.<ref name=abcnews>{{cite web\n |url= http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/ConsumerNews/truth-fish-oil-concerns/story?id=9994049\n |title= Lawsuit Raises Fish Oil Supplement Concerns|author=Elisabeth Leamy\n |date=2010-03-03|accessdate=5 March 2010|author-link= Elisabeth Leamy}}</ref><ref>[http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2010/03/03/BARO1C9RD3.DTL \"Lawsuit says fish oil supplements contain PCB\"], ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'', 3 March 2010.</ref>\n\nAn analysis based on data from the Norwegian Women and Cancer Study (NOWAC) with regards to the dangers of persistent organic pollutants (POPs) in cod liver came to the conclusion that \"in Norwegian women, fish liver consumption was not associated with an increased cancer risk in breast, uterus, or colon. In contrast, a decreased risk for total cancer was found.\"<ref>{{Cite journal |pages=682\u20136 |doi=10.1039/B706302B |title=POP exposure from fish liver consumption and risk of cancer?the Norwegian Women and Cancer Study |year=2007 |last1=Brustad |first1=Magritt |last2=Sandanger |first2=Torkjel Manning |last3=Andersen |first3=Vegard |last4=Lund |first4=Eiliv |journal=Journal of Environmental Monitoring |volume=9 |issue=7 |pmid=17607388}}</ref>\n\nA report by the [[Harvard Medical School]] studied five popular brands of fish oil, including Nordic Ultimate, Kirkland and CVS. They found that the brands had \"negligible amounts of mercury, suggesting either that mercury is removed during the manufacturing of purified fish oil or that the fish sources used in these commercial preparations are relatively mercury-free\".<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=14632570 |url=https://www.archivesofpathology.org/doi/full/10.1043/1543-2165%282003%29127%3C1603%3AMOMLIC%3E2.0.CO%3B2 |year=2003 |volume=127 |pages=1603\u201305 |last1=Foran |first1=Stacy E. |last2=Flood |first2=James G. |last3=Lewandrowski |first3=Kent B. |title=Measurement of Mercury Levels in Concentrated Over-the-Counter Fish Oil Preparations: Is Fish Oil Healthier Than Fish? |issue=12 |journal=Archives of Pathology & Laboratory Medicine |doi=10.1043/1543-2165(2003)127<1603:MOMLIC>2.0.CO;2 |doi-broken-date=2019-12-11 }}</ref>\n\n[[Microalgae]] oil is a [[vegetarian]] alternative to fish oil. Supplements produced from microalgae oil provide a balance of omega-3 fatty acids similar to fish oil, with a lower risk of pollutant exposure.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.2174/157339907781368968 |title=Omega-3 Fatty Acids for Nutrition and Medicine: Considering Microalgae Oil as a Vegetarian Source of EPA and DHA |year=2007 |first1=Scott D. |last1=Doughman |first2=Srirama |last2=Krupanidhi |first3=Carani B. |last3=Sanjeevi |journal=Current Diabetes Reviews |volume=3 |issue=3 |pages=198\u2013203 |pmid=18220672}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n<!-- Please keep entries in alphabetical order & add a short description [[WP:SEEALSO]] -->\n{{div col|small=yes|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Algae]]\n* [[Docosahexaenoic acid]]\n* [[Eicosapentaenoic acid]]\n* [[Krill oil]]\n* [[Lovaza]]\n* [[Shark liver oil]]\n* [[Cod liver oil]]\n{{div col end}}\n<!-- please keep entries in alphabetical order -->\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n* FAO (1986) [http://www.fao.org/DOCREP/003/X6899E/X6899E00.HTM ''The production of fish meal and oil''] FAO Fishery Technical Paper 142. {{ISBN|92-5-102464-2}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Fish oil}}\n* [http://www.nutrasource.ca/ifos/ International Fish Oil Standards] \u2014 An [[organization]] concerned with the [[Quality (business)|quality]] of omega-3 products as it relates to the [[international standard]]s established by the [[World Health Organization]] and the Council For Responsible Nutrition for purity and concentration.\n* {{cite web| url=http://www.fatsoflife.com|title=PUFA Newsletter|author=Joyce A. Nettleton, ed|accessdate=20 February 2006}} Two newsletters, both quarterly, reviewing recent publications in essential fatty acids. One is written for researchers, the second is for consumers. Industry sponsored, academic contributors.\n* [http://www.cancer.org/Treatment/TreatmentsandSideEffects/ComplementaryandAlternativeMedicine/DietandNutrition/omega-3-fatty-acids Omega-3 Fatty Acids] ''American Cancer Society''. Updated 11 January 2008.\n\n{{seafood|state=expanded}}\n{{fatsandoils}}\n{{dietary supplement}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fish Oil}}\n[[Category:Dietary supplements]]\n[[Category:Fish products]]\n[[Category:Animal fats]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Oil derived from the tissues of oily fish}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}\n\n[[File:Lachs\u00f6lkapsel.jpg|thumb|Fish oil capsules]]\n\n'''Fish oil''' is [[oil]] derived from the [[biological tissue|tissues]] of [[oily fish]]. Fish oils contain the [[omega-3 fatty acid]]s [[eicosapentaenoic acid]] (EPA) and [[docosahexaenoic acid]] (DHA), precursors of certain [[eicosanoid]]s that are known to reduce [[inflammation]] in the body<ref>{{cite journal |pages=402\u201310 |doi=10.1080/10408390701424303 |title=Advances in Dietary Enrichment with N-3 Fatty Acids |year=2008 |last1=Moghadasian |first1=Mohammed H. |journal=Critical Reviews in Food Science and Nutrition |volume=48 |issue=5 |pmid=18464030}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |pages=679\u201381 |doi=10.1186/ar1876 |year=2006 |last1=Cleland |first1=Leslieg |last2=James |first2=Michaelj |last3=Proudman |first3=Susannam |journal=[[Arthritis Research & Therapy]] |volume=8 |pmid=16542466 |pmc=1526555 |title=Fish oil: What the prescriber needs to know |issue=1}}</ref> and improve [[hypertriglyceridemia]]. There has been a great deal of controversy in recent years about the role of fish oil in [[cardiovascular disease]], with recent [[meta-analysis|meta-analyses]] reaching different conclusions about its potential impact. The most promising evidence supports supplementation for prevention of [[cardiac arrest|cardiac death]].<ref name=\"half full\"/>\n\nFish oil and omega-3 fatty acids have also been studied in a wide variety of other conditions such as [[clinical depression]],<ref name=\"Su2003\">{{cite journal |pages=267\u201371 |doi=10.1016/S0924-977X(03)00032-4 |title=Omega-3 fatty acids in major depressive disorder |year=2003 |last1=Su |first1=Kuan-Pin |last2=Huang |first2=Shih-Yi |last3=Chiu |first3=Chih-Chiang |last4=Shen |first4=Winston W. |journal=European Neuropsychopharmacology |volume=13 |issue=4 |pmid=12888186}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |pages=91\u201399 |doi=10.1080/10284150410001704525 |title=Effects of Fish Oil on the Central Nervous System: A New Potential Antidepressant? |year=2004 |last1=Naliwaiko |first1=K. |last2=Ara\u00fajo |first2=R.L.F. |last3=Da Fonseca |first3=R.V. |last4=Castilho |first4=J.C. |last5=Andreatini |first5=R. |last6=Bellissimo |first6=M.I. |last7=Oliveira |first7=B.H. |last8=Martins |first8=E.F. |last9=Curi |first9=R. |journal=Nutritional Neuroscience |volume=7 |issue=2 |pmid=15279495 |last10=Fernandes |first10=L.C. |last11=Ferraz |first11=A.C.}}</ref> [[anxiety]],<ref>{{cite journal |pages=107\u201313 |doi=10.1016/j.euroneuro.2005.07.005 |title=Red cell membrane omega-3 fatty acids are decreased in nondepressed patients with social anxiety disorder |year=2006 |last1=Green |first1=Pnina |last2=Hermesh |first2=Haggai |last3=Monselise |first3=Assaf |last4=Marom |first4=Sofi |last5=Presburger |first5=Gadi |last6=Weizman |first6=Abraham |journal=European Neuropsychopharmacology |volume=16 |issue=2 |pmid=16243493}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |pages=265\u201367 |doi=10.1080/10284150500445795 |title=Mixture of essential fatty acids lowers test anxiety |year=2005 |last1=Yehuda |first1=Shlomo |last2=Rabinovitz |first2=Sharon |last3=Mostofsky |first3=David I. |journal=Nutritional Neuroscience |volume=8 |issue=4 |pmid=16491653}}</ref><ref name=\"Pp\">{{cite journal |pages=477\u201379 |doi=10.1176/appi.ajp.159.3.477 |title=Addition of Omega-3 Fatty Acid to Maintenance Medication Treatment for Recurrent Unipolar Depressive Disorder |year=2002 |last1=Nemets |first1=B. |journal=American Journal of Psychiatry |volume=159 |issue=3 |pmid=11870016 |last2=Stahl |first2=Z |last3=Belmaker |first3=RH}}</ref> [[cancer]], and [[macular degeneration]], yet their benefit in these conditions has also not been verified.<ref name=\"medline\"/> \n\nThe fish used as sources do not actually produce omega-3 fatty acids, but instead accumulate them by consuming either [[microalgae]] or [[prey fish]] that have accumulated [[omega-3 fatty acid]]s. Fatty predatory fish like [[shark]]s, [[swordfish]], [[tilefish]], and [[albacore tuna]] may be high in omega-3 fatty acids, but due to their position at the top of the [[food chain]], these species may also accumulate [[toxic]] substances through [[biomagnification]]. For this reason, the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency]] recommends limiting consumption (especially for women of childbearing age) of certain (predatory) fish species (e.g. [[albacore tuna]], [[shark]], [[king mackerel]], [[tilefish]] and [[swordfish]]) due to high levels of the toxic contaminant [[Mercury (element)|mercury]]. [[Polychlorinated dibenzodioxins|Dioxin]], [[polychlorinated biphenyl|PCBs]] and [[chlordane]] are also present.<ref name=petsworldtoday>{{cite web|url=https://www.petsworldtoday.in/2020/02/best-fish-to-eat.html |title= Best fish to eat|author=Venus Nandi|date=2020-02-09|accessdate=9 February 2020}}</ref> Fish is rich in protein and other vitamins [[aquaculture]] feed. More than 50 percent of the world's fish oil used in [[Commercial fish feed|aquaculture feed]] is fed to [[Aquaculture of salmon|farmed salmon]].<ref>[[FAO]]: World Review of Fisheries and Aquaculture 2008: [ftp://ftp.fao.org/docrep/fao/011/i0250e/i0250e03.pdf Highlights of Special Studies]|date=February 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Rome.</ref>\n\nMarine and freshwater fish oil vary in contents of [[arachidonic acid]], EPA and DHA.<ref name=\"pmid7666244\">{{cite journal |pmid=7666244 |year=1995 |last1=Innis |first1=Sheila M. |last2=Rioux |first2=France M. |last3=Auestad |first3=Nancy |last4=Ackman |first4=Robert G. |title=Marine and freshwater fish oil varying in arachidonic, eicosapentaenoic and docosahexaenoic acids differ in their effects on organ lipids and fatty acids in growing rats |volume=125 |issue=9 |pages=2286\u201393 |journal=The Journal of Nutrition |url=http://jn.nutrition.org/content/125/9/2286.short|doi=10.1093/jn/125.9.2286 }}</ref> The various species range from lean to fatty and their oil content in the tissues has been shown to vary from 0.7% to 15.5%.<ref name=Gruger1964>{{cite journal |last1=Gruger |first1=E. H. |author2=Nelson, R. W.; Stansby, M. E.|title=Fatty acid composition of oils from 21 species of marine fish, freshwater fish and shellfish|journal=Journal of the American Oil Chemists' Society|date=1 October 1964|volume=41|issue=10|pages=662\u201367|doi=10.1007/BF02661403}}</ref> They also differ in their effects on organ lipids.<ref name=\"pmid7666244\" /> Studies have revealed that there is no relation between total fish intake or estimated omega\u22123 fatty acid intake from all fish, and serum omega\u22123 fatty acid concentrations.<ref name=\"pmid17158409\">{{cite journal|last1=Philibert|first1=A|author2=Vanier, C; Abdelouahab, N; Chan, HM; Mergler, D|title=Fish intake and serum fatty acid profiles from freshwater fish|journal=The American Journal of Clinical Nutrition|date=December 2006|volume=84|issue=6|pages=1299\u2013307|pmid=17158409|doi=10.1093/ajcn/84.6.1299}}</ref> Only fatty fish intake, particularly salmonid, and estimated EPA + DHA intake from fatty fish has been observed to be significantly associated with increase in serum EPA + DHA.<ref name=\"pmid17158409\" />\n\nAs of 2019, the US [[Food and Drug Administration]] has approved four fish oil-based prescription drugs, such as Lovaza, Omtryg (both [[omega-3 acid ethyl esters]]), Vascepa ([[ethyl eicosapentaenoic acid]]), and Epanova ([[omega-3 carboxylic acids]]).<ref name=\"skulas19\">{{cite journal |last1=Skulas-Ray |first1=Ann C. |last2=Wilson |first2=Peter W.F. |last3=Harris |first3=William S. |last4=Brinton |first4=Eliot A. |last5=Kris-Etherton |first5=Penny M. |last6=Richter |first6=Chesney K. |last7=Jacobson |first7=Terry A. |last8=Engler |first8=Mary B. |last9=Miller |first9=Michael |last10=Robinson |first10=Jennifer G. |last11=Blum |first11=Conrad B. |last12=Rodriguez-Leyva |first12=Delfin |last13=de Ferranti |first13=Sarah D. |last14=Welty |first14=Francine K. |title=Omega-3 Fatty Acids for the Management of Hypertriglyceridemia: A Science Advisory From the American Heart Association |journal=Circulation |date=2019 |volume=140 |issue=12 |doi=10.1161/CIR.0000000000000709 |pmid=31422671 |display-authors=8}}</ref>\n\n== Uses ==\nOften marketed and sold for consumption as part of the diet or in dietary supplements in contemporary societies, fish oils also have found roles in external use, as [[emollient]]s<ref>\n{{cite book\n| last1                 = Talakoub\n| first1                = Lily\n| last2                 = Neuhaus\n| first2                = Isaac M.\n| last3                 = Yu\n| first3                = Siegrid S.\n| chapter               = Chapter 2: Cosmoceuticals\n| editor1-last          = Alam\n| editor1-first         = Murad\n| editor1-link          = Murad Alam\n| editor2-last          = Gladstone\n| editor2-first         = Hayes B.\n| editor3-last          = Tung\n| editor3-first         = Rebecca\n| title                 = Cosmetic Dermatology\n| chapter-url                   = https://books.google.com/books?id=lUI9zg7GDuUC\n| series                = Requisites in dermatology\n| publisher             = Elsevier Health Sciences\n| date      = 2008\n| page                  = 9 \n| isbn                  = 9780702031434\n| accessdate            = 2014-10-23\n| quote                 = Other oils used as emollients include fish oil, petrolatum, shea butter, and sunflower seed oil.\n}}\n</ref>\nor as general [[ointment]]s<ref>\n{{cite book\n| last1                 = Burch\n| first1                = Ernest S.\n| title                 = Social Life in Northwest Alaska: The Structure of I\u00f1upiaq Eskimo Nations\n| url                   = https://books.google.com/books?id=tfQzWXTtifsC\n| publisher             = University of Alaska Press\n| date      = 2006\n| page                  = 278\n| isbn                  = 9781889963921\n| accessdate            = 2014-10-23\n| quote                 = Oil was also used externally as an ointment to heal cold sores, cuts, insect bites, frostbite, rashes - in short, skin problems of all kinds. Duck or goose body-cavity fat was apparently as useful as seal or fish oil in dealing with skin problems.\n}}\n</ref>\nas well as in [[body art]],<ref>\n{{cite book\n| last1                 = Heartney\n| first1                = Eleanor\n| chapter               = Zhang Huan: Becoming the Body\n| title                 = Zhang Huan: Altered States\n| chapter-url                   = http://www.zhanghuan.com/ShowText.asp?id=30&sClassID=1\n| publisher             = Charta and Asia Society\n| date      = 2007\n| isbn                  = 978-8881586417\n| accessdate            = 2014-10-23\n| quote                 = This becomes abundantly clear in the work of Chinese body artist Zhang Huan. In the course of his career, Zhang Huan has subjected himself to painful trials: sitting motionless for hours in an outhouse covered in honey and fish oil while flies crawled over his body [...].\n}}\n</ref>\nor for alleged insulation against cold.<ref>\nIlse Schreiber: ''Die Schwestern aus Memel'' (1936), quoted, and extract translated in:\n{{cite book\n| last1                 = Strzelczyk\n| first1                = Florentine\n| chapter               = 16: 'Fighting against Manitou': German Identity and Ilse Schreiber's Canada Novels ''Die Schwestern aus Memel'' (1936) and ''Die Flucht in Paradies'' (1939)\n| editor1-last          = McFarland\n| editor1-first         = Rob\n| editor2-last          = James\n| editor2-first         = Michelle Stott\n| title                 = Sophie Discovers Amerika: German-Speaking Women Write the New World\n| chapter-url                   = https://books.google.com/books?id=G_ezAwAAQBAJ\n| series                = Studies in German Literature Linguistics and Culture\n| volume                = 148\n| publisher             = Boydell & Brewer\n| date      = 2014\n| page                  = 207\n| isbn                  = 9781571135865\n| quote                 = Hoffentlich zogen die Eltern in eine Gegend, wo es recht viele Eingeborene gab. Indianer, die nur von Jagd und Fischfang leben. Ach, und wom\u00f6glich Eskimos, die sich mit Tran einschmieren, um sich gegen die K\u00e4lte zu sch\u00fctzen und rohes Fleisch essen [...]. [She hoped her parents would move to an area where there were many aboriginals. Indians who live solely by hunting and fishing. Oh, and if possible Eskimos who smear themselves with fish oil to protect themselves from the cold, and who eat raw meat.]\n}}\n</ref>\n\n[[File:FMIB 36337 Rendering Room where the Fish Waste was Treated to Separate the Valuable Oil Content, Port Dover, Ont.jpeg|thumb|Fish oil rendering in [[Port Dover, Ontario]], 1918]]\n\n== Nutritional details ==\nThe most widely available dietary source of EPA and DHA is cold-water [[oily fish]], such as [[salmon]], [[herring]], [[mackerel]], [[anchovies]], and [[sardine]]s. Oils from these fish have a profile of around seven times as much [[omega-3 oil]]s as [[Omega-6 fatty acid|omega-6 oils]]. Other oily fish, such as [[tuna]], also contain omega-3 in somewhat lesser amounts. Although fish is a dietary source of omega-3 oils, fish do not synthesize them; they obtain them from the [[algae]] ([[microalgae]] in particular) or [[plankton]] in their diets.<ref>\n{{cite journal \n|id={{INIST|2356641}} \n|doi=10.1007/s003000050274 \n|title=Lipids and fatty acids in ice algae and phytoplankton from the Marginal Ice Zone in the Barents Sea |year=1998 |last1=Falk-Petersen |first1=S. |last2=Sargent |first2=J. R. |last3=Henderson |first3=J. |last4=Hegseth |first4=E. N. |last5=Hop |first5=H. |last6=Okolodkov |first6=Y. B. |journal=Polar Biology |volume=20 |issue=1 \n|pages=41\u201347\n}}\n</ref>\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=1 style=\"border-collapse:collapse;width:300px;\"\n|+Grams of omega-3 fatty acids per 3oz (85g) serving of popular fish.<ref name=\"ahao3\">{{cite web\n| url = http://www.americanheart.org/presenter.jhtml?identifier=3013797\n| title = Fish, Levels of Mercury and Omega-3 Fatty Acids\n| publisher = American Heart Association\n| accessdate = 6 October 2010\n| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100709203304/http://www.americanheart.org/presenter.jhtml?identifier=3013797\n| archive-date = 9 July 2010\n| url-status = dead\n}}</ref><ref name=\"KrisEtherton2002\">{{Cite journal\n | last1 = Kris-Etherton\n | first1 = Penny M.\n | author2 = William S. Harris, Lawrence J. Appel\n | title = Fish Consumption, Fish Oil, Omega-3 Fatty Acids, and Cardiovascular Disease\n | journal = Circulation\n | volume = 106\n | issue = 21\n | pages = 2747\u201357\n | year = 2002\n | doi = 10.1161/01.CIR.0000038493.65177.94\n | pmid=12438303}}</ref>\n!| Common name             || grams\n|-\n| [[Herring]], [[sardine]]s  || 1.3\u20132\n|-\n| [[Spanish mackerel]], [[Atlantic mackerel|Atlantic]], [[Pacific mackerel|Pacific]]        || 1.1\u20131.7\n|-\n| [[Salmon]]               || 1.1\u20131.9\n|-\n| [[Halibut]]              || 0.60\u20131.12\n|-\n| [[Tuna]]                 || 0.21\u20131.1\n|-\n| [[Swordfish]]            || 0.97\n|-\n| [[New Zealand green-lipped mussel|Greenshell/lipped mussels]] || 0.95<ref name=\"o3c\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.omega-3centre.com/sources_long_chain.html |title=Omega-3 Centre\n|accessdate=27 July 2008\n|work=Omega-3 sources\n|publisher=Omega-3 Centre\n|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080718174524/http://www.omega-3centre.com/sources_long_chain.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2008-07-18}}</ref><!--Source: Fatty acid database, RMIT University-->\n|-\n| [[Tilefish]]             || 0.9\n|-\n| [[Tuna]] (canned, light) || 0.17\u20130.24\n|-\n| [[Pollock]]              || 0.45\n|-\n| [[Cod]]                  || 0.15\u20130.24\n|-\n| [[Catfish]]              || 0.22\u20130.3\n|-\n| [[Flounder]]             || 0.48\n|-\n| [[Grouper]]              || 0.23\n|-\n| [[Mahi mahi]]            || 0.13\n|-\n| [[Orange roughy]]        || 0.028\n|-\n| [[Red snapper (fish)|Red snapper]]          || 0.29\n|-\n| [[Shark]]                || 0.83\n|-\n| [[King mackerel]]        || 0.36\n|-\n| [[Blue grenadier|Hoki (blue grenadier)]]          || 0.41\n|-\n| [[Silver gemfish]]                                       || 0.40\n|-\n| [[Cod#Perciformes|Blue eye cod]]                  || 0.31\n|-\n| [[Sydney rock oyster]]               || 0.30\n|-\n| [[Canned tuna|Tuna, canned]]                  || 0.23\n|-\n| [[Lutjanidae|Snapper]]                                       || 0.22\n|-\n| [[Barramundi|Barramundi, saltwater]]               || 0.100\n|-\n| [[Giant tiger prawn]]                             || 0.100\n|}\n\nFor comparison, note the omega-3 levels in some common non-fish foods:\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" border=1 cellspacing=0 cellpadding=1 style=\"border-collapse:collapse;width:300px;\"\n|+Grams of omega-3 fatty acids per 3oz (85g) serving of common non-fish foods.<ref name=\"ahao3\" />\n!| Name             || grams\n|-\n| [[Flaxseeds]]                || 19.55\n|-\n| [[Chia seeds]]                || 14.8\n|-\n| [[Hemp seeds]]                || 7.4\n|-\n| [[Walnut]]                || 1.7\n|-\n| [[Soybean]]                || 1.1\n|-\n| [[Butter]]          || 0.27\n|-\n| [[Egg (food)|Eggs, large regular]]                || 0.109<ref name=\"o3c\"/>\n|-\n| [[Red meat|Lean red meat]]                        || 0.031\n|-\n| [[Turkey]]                                        || 0.030\n|-\n| [[Cereal|Cereals, rice, pasta, etc.]]             ||   0.00\n|-\n| [[Fruit]]                                         ||   0.00\n|-\n| [[Milk|Milk, regular]]                             ||   0.00\n|-\n| [[Bread|Bread, regular]]                           ||   0.00\n|-\n| [[Vegetables]]                                    ||   0.00\n|}\n\n== Health effects==\n[[File:Kepler Cod Liver Oil, by Burroughs Wellcome & Co Wellcome L0016947.jpg|thumb|Kepler Cod Liver Oil with Malt Extract]]\n\n=== Various recommendations ===\nIn a 2009 letter on a pending revision to the Dietary Guidelines for Americans, the American Heart Association recommended 250\u2013500&nbsp;mg/day of EPA and DHA.<ref name=\"AHA-2012\">{{cite web |title=Re: 2010 Dietary Guidelines for Americans |url=http://www.heart.org/idc/groups/heart-public/@wcm/@adv/documents/downloadable/ucm_312853.pdf |work=Jan 2009 |publisher=American Heart Association}}</ref> The Guidelines were revised again for 2015-2020; included is a recommendation that adults consume at least eight ounces of a variety of types of fish per week, equating to at least 250&nbsp;mg/day of EPA + DHA.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}} The Food and Drug Administration recommends not exceeding 3 grams per day of EPA + DHA from all sources, with no more than 2 grams per day from dietary supplements.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fda.gov/NewsEvents/Newsroom/PressAnnouncements/2004/ucm108351.htm|title=2004 \u2013 FDA Announces Qualified Health Claims for Omega-3 Fatty Acids|website=www.fda.gov|language=en|access-date=2016-05-25}}</ref>\n\n=== Prostate cancer ===\nThe effect of fish oil consumption on [[prostate cancer]] is controversial,<ref name=Hein2012>{{cite journal|last1=Heinze|first1=VM|author2=Actis, AB|title=Dietary conjugated linoleic acid and long-chain n-3 fatty acids in mammary and prostate cancer protection: a review|journal=International Journal of Food Sciences and Nutrition|date=February 2012|volume=63|issue=1|pages=66\u201378|pmid=21762028|doi=10.3109/09637486.2011.598849}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title = Circulating fatty acids and prostate cancer risk: individual participant meta-analysis of prospective studies|journal = Journal of the National Cancer Institute|date = 2014-09-01|issn = 1460-2105|pmc = 4188122|pmid = 25210201|volume = 106|issue = 9|doi = 10.1093/jnci/dju240|first = Francesca L.|last = Crowe|first2 = Paul N.|last2 = Appleby|first3 = Ruth C.|last3 = Travis|first4 = Matt|last4 = Barnett|first5 = Theodore M.|last5 = Brasky|first6 = H. Bas|last6 = Bueno-de-Mesquita|first7 = Veronique|last7 = Chajes|first8 = Jorge E.|last8 = Chavarro|first9 = Maria-Dolores|last9 = Chirlaque|page=dju240}}</ref> as one study showed decreased risk with higher blood levels of [[Docosapentaenoic acid#all-cis-7,10,13,16,19-docosapentaenoic acid (clupanodonic acid)|DPA]], whereas another reported increased risk of more aggressive prostate cancer with higher blood levels of combined [[Eicosapentaenoic acid|EPA]] and [[Docosahexaenoic acid|DHA]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Chua|first1=Michael E.|last2=Sio|first2=Maria Christina D.|last3=Sorongon|first3=Mishell C.|last4=Morales Jr|first4=Marcelino L. Jr.|date=May\u2013June 2013|title=The relevance of serum levels of long chain omega-3 polyunsaturated fatty acids and prostate cancer risk: a meta-analysis|journal=Canadian Urological Association Journal|volume=7|issue=5\u20136|pages=E333\u201343|doi=10.5489/cuaj.1056|pmid=23766835|pmc=3668400}}</ref> Some evidence indicated an association between high blood levels of omega-3 fatty acids and an increased prostate cancer risk.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Brasky TM, Darke AK, Song X |title=Plasma phospholipid fatty acids and prostate cancer risk in the SELECT trial |journal=J. Natl. Cancer Inst. |volume=105 |issue=15 |pages=1132\u201341 | date=August 2013 |pmid=23843441 |pmc=3735464 |doi=10.1093/jnci/djt174|display-authors=etal}}</ref>\n\n=== Cardiovascular ===\nThere has been a great deal of controversy in recent years about the role of fish oil in cardiovascular disease, with recent meta-analyses reaching different conclusions about its potential impact.<ref name=\"half full\">{{cite journal |last1=Maki |first1=KC |last2=Dicklin |first2=MR |title=Omega-3 Fatty Acid Supplementation and Cardiovascular Disease Risk: Glass Half Full or Time to Nail the Coffin Shut? |journal=Nutrients |date=4 July 2018 |volume=10 |issue=7 |pages=864 |doi=10.3390/nu10070864 |pmid=29973554|pmc=6073248 }}</ref> Multiple evaluations suggest fish oil has little or no reduction in cardiovascular mortality, in distinction to earlier observational data, though there appears to be a small reduction in the incidence of actual cardiac events and strokes with its use.<ref name=\"Cochrane 2018 1\">{{cite journal|last1=Abdelhamid|first1=AS|last2=Brown|first2=TJ|last3=Brainard|first3=JS|last4=Biswas|first4=P|last5=Thorpe|first5=GC|last6=Moore|first6=HJ|last7=Deane|first7=KH|last8=AlAbdulghafoor|first8=FK|last9=Summerbell|first9=CD|last10=Worthington|first10=HV|last11=Song|first11=F|date=November 2018|title=Omega-3 fatty acids for the primary and secondary prevention of cardiovascular disease.|url=|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|volume=11|pages=CD003177|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD003177.pub4|pmc=6517311|pmid=30521670|last12=Hooper|first12=L}}</ref><ref name=\"Cochrane 2018 2\">{{cite journal|last1=Abdelhamid|first1=AS|last2=Martin|first2=N|last3=Bridges|first3=C|last4=Brainard|first4=JS|last5=Wang|first5=X|last6=Brown|first6=TJ|last7=Hanson|first7=S|last8=Jimoh|first8=OF|last9=Ajabnoor|first9=SM|last10=Deane|first10=KH|last11=Song|first11=F|date=November 2018|title=Polyunsaturated fatty acids for the primary and secondary prevention of cardiovascular disease.|url=|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|volume=11|pages=CD012345|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD012345.pub3|pmc=6517012|pmid=30484282|last12=Hooper|first12=L}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Goel |first1=A |last2=Pothineni |first2=NV |last3=Singhal |first3=M |last4=Paydak |first4=H |last5=Saldeen |first5=T |last6=Mehta |first6=JL |title=Fish, Fish Oils and Cardioprotection: Promise or Fish Tale? |journal=International Journal of Molecular Sciences |date=22 November 2018 |volume=19 |issue=12 |pages=3703 |doi=10.3390/ijms19123703 |pmid=30469489|pmc=6321588 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |pmid=30763028 |year=2007 |author1=John M. Eisenberg Center for Clinical Decisions Communications Science |title=Omega-3 Fatty Acids and Cardiovascular Disease: Current State of the Evidence }}</ref>  In 2007, the [[American Heart Association]] had recommended the consumption of 1 [[gram]] of fish oil daily, preferably by eating fish, for patients with [[coronary artery disease]], but cautioned pregnant and nursing women to avoid eating fish with high potential for [[mercury (element)|mercury]] contaminants including mackerel, shark, and swordfish.<ref name=\"AHA-2007\">{{cite web |url=http://www.americanheart.org/presenter.jhtml?identifier=4632 | title= Fish and Omega-3 Fatty Acids|accessdate=9 February 2007 |publisher=American Heart Association}}</ref> (Optimal dosage was related to body weight.)\n\nThe US [[National Institutes of Health]] lists three conditions for which fish oil and other omega-3 sources are most highly recommended: [[hypertriglyceridemia]] (high triglyceride level), preventing secondary [[cardiovascular disease]], and [[hypertension]] (high blood pressure). It then lists 27 other conditions for which there is less evidence. It also lists possible safety concerns: \"Intake of 3 grams per day or greater of omega-3 fatty acids may increase the risk of bleeding, although there is little evidence of significant bleeding risk at lower doses. Very large intakes of fish oil/omega-3 fatty acids may increase the risk of hemorrhagic (bleeding) stroke.\"<ref name=\"medline\">{{cite web |url=https://nccih.nih.gov/health/omega3/introduction.htm#hed4|title=Omega-3 Supplements: In Depth |author = NIH Medline Plus |date=August 2015|accessdate=13 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nThere is also some evidence that fish oil may have a beneficial effect on certain [[cardiac dysrhythmia|abnormal heart rhythms]].<ref>{{cite journal|author=Charnock John S |year=1999 |title=The role of omega-3 polyunsaturated fatty acid-enriched diets in the prevention of ventricular fibrillation |url=http://apjcn.nhri.org.tw/server/apjcn/Volume8/vol8.3/Charnock.pdf |journal=Asia Pacific Journal of Clinical Nutrition |volume=8 |issue=3 |pages=226\u201330 |doi=10.1046/j.1440-6047.1999.00115.x |pmid=24394167}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|vauthors=Li GR, Sun HY, Zhang XH, Cheng LC, Chiu SW, Tse HF, Lau CP |year=2009 |title=Omega-3 polyunsaturated fatty acids inhibit transient outward and ultra-rapid delayed rectifier K+currents and Na+current in human atrial myocytes|url=http://cardiovascres.oxfordjournals.org/content/81/2/286.full |journal=Cardiovasc Res |volume=81 |issue=2 |pages=286\u201393 |doi=10.1093/cvr/cvn322 |pmid=19029136 }}</ref> However, a 2012 [[meta-analysis]] found no such significant benefit.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = A meta-analysis of omega-3 fatty acids and incidence of atrial fibrillation|journal = Journal of the American College of Nutrition|date = 2012-02-01|issn = 1541-1087|pmid = 22661621|pages = 4\u201313|volume = 31|issue = 1|first = Owais|last = Khawaja|first2 = J. Michael|last2 = Gaziano|first3 = Luc|last3 = Djouss\u00e9|doi=10.1080/07315724.2012.10720003}}</ref>\n\nA 2008 [[meta-study]] by the ''[[Canadian Medical Association Journal]]'' found fish oil supplementation did not demonstrate any preventative benefit to cardiac patients with [[ventricular arrhythmia]]s.<ref>{{cite journal |pages=181\u201382 |doi=10.1503/cmaj.071654 |title=Should patients with cardiovascular disease take fish oil? |year=2008 |last1=Nair |first1=G. M. |last2=Connolly |first2=S. J. |journal=Canadian Medical Association Journal |volume=178 |issue=2 |pmid=18195293 |pmc=2174997}}</ref> A 2012 meta-analysis published in the [[Journal of the American Medical Association]], covering 20 studies and 68,680 patients, found that Omega-3 Fatty Acid supplementation did not reduce the chance of death, cardiac death, heart attack or stroke.<ref>{{cite journal |pages=1024\u201333 |doi=10.1001/2012.jama.11374 |title=Association Between Omega-3 Fatty Acid Supplementation and Risk of Major Cardiovascular Disease Events: A Systematic Review and Meta-analysis |year=2012 |last1=Rizos |first1=E. C. |last2=Ntzani |first2=E. E. |journal=Journal of the American Medical Association |volume=308 |issue=10 |pmid=22968891 |last3=Bika |first3=E |last4=Kostapanos |first4=MS |last5=Elisaf |first5=MS}}</ref>\n\n=== Hypertension ===\nThere have been some human trials that have concluded that consuming omega-3 fatty acids slightly reduces blood pressure (DHA could be more effective than EPA). It is important to note that because omega-3 fatty acids can increase the risk of bleeding, a qualified healthcare provider should be consulted before supplementing with fish oil.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mayoclinic.org/drugs-supplements/omega-3-fatty-acids-fish-oil-alpha-linolenic-acid/evidence/HRB-20059372 |title=Omega-3 fatty acids, fish oil, alpha-linolenic acid |url-status=live |accessdate=4 February 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Mental health ===\nA 2008 [[Cochrane Library|Cochrane]] [[systematic review]] found that limited data is available. In the one eligible study, omega-3s were an effective adjunctive therapy for depressed but not manic symptoms in [[bipolar disorder]]. The authors found an \"acute need\" for more randomised controlled trials.<ref>{{cite journal |vauthors=Montgomery P, Richardson AJ|title=Omega-3 fatty acids for bipolar disorder |journal=Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews |year=2008 |issue=2 |doi=10.1002/14651858.CD005169.pub2 |pmid=18425912 |page=CD005169 |editor1-last=Montgomery |editor1-first=Paul}}</ref>\n\nA 2009 metastudy found that patients taking omega-3 supplements with a higher EPA:DHA ratio experienced fewer depressive symptoms. The studies provided evidence that EPA may be more efficacious than DHA in treating depression. However, this metastudy concluded that due to the identified limitations of the included studies, larger, randomized trials are needed to confirm these findings.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1080/07315724.2009.10719785 |title=EPA but Not DHA Appears to Be Responsible for the Efficacy of Omega-3 Long Chain Polyunsaturated Fatty Acid Supplementation in Depression: Evidence from a Meta-Analysis of Randomized Controlled Trials |year=2009 |last1=Martins |first1=Julian G |journal=Journal of the American College of Nutrition |volume=28 |issue=5 |pages=525\u201342 |pmid=20439549}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2011 [[meta-analysis]] of [[PubMed]] articles about fish oil and depression from 1965 to 2010, researchers found that \"nearly all of the treatment efficacy observed in the published literature may be attributable to publication bias.\"<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/mp.2011.100 |title=Omega-3 fatty acids for the treatment of depression: Systematic review and meta-analysis |year=2011 |last1=Bloch |first1=M H |last2=Hannestad |first2=J |journal=Molecular Psychiatry |volume=17 |issue=12 |pages=1272\u201382 |pmid=21931319 |pmc=3625950}}</ref>\n\nA 2014 meta-analysis of eleven trials conducted respectively on patients with a DSM-defined diagnosis of major depressive disorder (MDD) and of eight trials with patients with depressive symptomatology but no diagnosis of MDD demonstrated significant clinical benefit of omega-3 PUFA treatment compared to placebo. The study concluded that: \"The use of omega-3 PUFA is effective in patients with diagnosis of MDD and on depressive patients without diagnosis of MDD.\"<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Grosso | first1 = G. | last2 = Pajak | first2 = A. | last3 = Marventano | first3 = S. | last4 = Castellano | first4 = S. | last5 = Galvano | first5 = F. | last6 = Bucolo | first6 = C. | last7 = Caraci | first7 = F. | year = 2014 | title = Role of Omega-3 Fatty Acids in the Treatment of Depressive Disorders: A Comprehensive Meta-Analysis of Randomized Clinical Trials | journal = PLoS ONE | volume = 9 | issue = 5| page = e96905 | doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0096905 | pmid=24805797 | pmc=4013121| bibcode = 2014PLoSO...996905G }}</ref>\n\n=== Alzheimer's disease ===\nA [[Cochrane Library|Cochrane]] [[meta-analysis]] published in June 2012 found no significant protective effect for cognitive decline for those aged 60 and over and who started taking fatty acids after this age. A co-author of the study said to ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'', \"Our analysis suggests that there is currently no evidence that omega-3 fatty acid supplements provide a benefit for memory or concentration in later life\".<ref>{{cite news |author=Sifferlin, Alexandra |date=13 June 2012|title=Fish Oil Fail: Omega-3s May Not Protect Brain Health After All |url=http://healthland.time.com/2012/06/13/fish-oil-fail-omega-3s-may-not-protect-brain-health-after-all/ |work=Time |accessdate=19 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Psoriasis ===\nDiets supplemented with [[cod liver oil]] have shown beneficial\neffects on [[psoriasis]].<ref>{{cite journal |pages=706\u201314 |doi=10.1111/j.1365-2133.2005.06781.x |title=Diet and psoriasis: experimental data and clinical evidence |year=2005 |last1=Wolters |first1=M. |journal=British Journal of Dermatology |volume=153 |issue=4 |pmid=16181450}}</ref>\n\n=== Pregnancy ===\nSome studies reported better psychomotor development at 30 months of age in infants whose mothers received fish oil supplements for the first four months of lactation.<ref name=Jensen10>{{cite journal |pages=900\u201305 |doi=10.1016/j.jpeds.2010.06.006 |title=Effects of Early Maternal Docosahexaenoic Acid Intake on Neuropsychological Status and Visual Acuity at Five Years of Age of Breast-Fed Term Infants |year=2010 |last1=Jensen |first1=Craig L. |last2=Voigt |first2=Robert G. |last3=Llorente |first3=Antolin M. |last4=Peters |first4=Sarika U. |last5=Prager |first5=Thomas C. |last6=Zou |first6=Yali L. |last7=Rozelle |first7=Judith C. |last8=Turcich |first8=Marie R. |last9=Fraley |first9=J. Kennard |journal=The Journal of Pediatrics |volume=157 |issue=6 |pmid=20655543 |last10=Anderson |first10=Robert E. |last11=Heird |first11=William C.}}</ref> In addition, five-year-old children whose mothers received modest algae based docosahexaenoic acid supplementation for the first 4 months of breastfeeding performed better on a test of sustained attention. This suggests that [[docosahexaenoic acid]] intake during early infancy confers long-term benefits on specific aspects of neurodevelopment.<ref name=Jensen10 />\n\nIn addition, provision of fish oil during pregnancy may reduce an infant\u2019s sensitization to common food allergens and reduce the prevalence and severity of certain skin diseases in the first year of life. This effect may persist until adolescence with a reduction in prevalence and/or severity of eczema, hay fever and asthma.<ref name=Calder10>{{cite journal |pages=373\u201380 |doi=10.1017/S0029665110001552 |title=Is there a role for fatty acids in early life programming of the immune system? |year=2010 |last1=Calder |first1=Philip C. |last2=Kremmyda |first2=Lefkothea-Stella |last3=Vlachava |first3=Maria |last4=Noakes |first4=Paul S. |last5=Miles |first5=Elizabeth A. |journal=Proceedings of the Nutrition Society |volume=69 |issue=3 |pmid=20462467}}</ref>\n\n=== Crohn's disease ===\nA 2014 Cochrane review found that, based on two large studies, fish oil supplements did not appear to be effective for maintenance of remission in [[Crohn's disease]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lev-Tzion|first1=R|last2=Griffiths|first2=AM|last3=Leder|first3=O|last4=Turner|first4=D|title=Omega 3 fatty acids (fish oil) for maintenance of remission in Crohn's disease.|journal=The Cochrane Database of Systematic Reviews|date=28 February 2014|volume=2|issue=2|pages=CD006320|pmid=24585498|doi=10.1002/14651858.CD006320.pub4}}</ref>\n\n==Supplement quality and concerns==\nFish oil is a commonly used [[dietary supplement]], with sales in the U.S. alone reaching $976 million in 2009.<ref name=clpr>{{cite web |title=ConsumerLab.com Finds Quality Problems with Nearly Thirty Percent of Fish Oil Supplements Reviewed; \"Fishy\" Claims Identified: Softgels and Liquids for Adults, Children and Pets Tested, Including Krill Oil and Algal Oil Supplements|url=http://www.consumerlab.com/news/fish_oil_supplements_reviewed/09_28_2010/|publisher=ConsumerLab.com|accessdate=20 October 2012|date=28 September 2010}}{{dubious|date=December 2012}}</ref>\nProblems of quality have been identified in periodic tests by independent researchers of marketed supplements containing fish oil and other marine oils. These problems include contamination, inaccurate listing of EPA and DHA levels, spoilage and formulation issues.<ref>[http://www.consumerlab.com/results/index.asp Reviews of Supplements and Health Products] ''ConsumerLab''.</ref>\n\n===Contamination===\nFish can accumulate toxins such as mercury, dioxins, and [[polychlorinated biphenyl]]s (PCBs), and spoiled fish oil may produce peroxides.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Levels of dioxins, dibenzofurans, PCB and DDE congeners in pooled food samples collected in 1995 at supermarkets across the United States|journal = Chemosphere|date = 1997-04-01|issn = 0045-6535|pmid = 9134677|pages = 1437\u201347|volume = 34|issue = 5\u20137|first = A.|last = Schecter|first2 = P.|last2 = Cramer|first3 = K.|last3 = Boggess|first4 = J.|last4 = Stanley|first5 = J. R.|last5 = Olson|doi=10.1016/s0045-6535(97)00440-2|bibcode = 1997Chmsp..34.1437S}}</ref> There appears to be little risk of contamination by microorganisms, proteins, lysophospholipids, cholesterol, and trans-fats.<ref name=norstudy>{{cite book |title=Description of the processes in the value chain and risk assessment of decomposition substances and oxidation products in fish oils |url=http://english.vkm.no/dav/0fd42c8b08.pdf |publisher=Norwegian Scientific Committee for Food Safety |accessdate=19 October 2012 |year=2011 |isbn=978-82-8259-035-8 |first1=Marit |last1=Aursand |first2=Revilija |last2=Mozuraityte |first3=Kristin |last3=Hamre |first4=Helle |last4=Knutsen |first5=Amund |last5=Maage |first6=Augustine |last6=Arukwe |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160909213119/http://english.vkm.no/dav/0fd42c8b08.pdf |archive-date=9 September 2016 |url-status=dead }}{{page needed|date=December 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Dioxins and PCBs===\nDioxins and PCBs may be carcinogenic at low levels of exposure over time. These substances are identified and measured in one of two categories, dioxin-like PCBs and total PCBs. While the U.S. FDA has not set a limit for PCBs in supplements, the Global Organization for EPA and DHA (GOED) has established a guideline allowing for no more than 3 picograms of dioxin-like PCBs per gram of fish oil. In 2012, samples from 35 fish oil supplements were tested for PCBs. Trace amounts of PCBs were found in all samples, and two samples exceeded the GOED\u2018s limit.<ref name=review12>{{cite web |title=ConsumerLab.com Review: Fish Oil and Omega-3 Fatty Acid Supplements Review (Including Krill, Algae, and Calamari Oil)|url=https://www.consumerlab.com/reviews/fish_oil_supplements_review/omega3/ |publisher=ConsumerLab.com |accessdate=19 October 2012 |date=13 August 2012}}{{registration required|date=December 2012}}</ref> Although trace amounts of PCBs contribute to overall PCB exposure, Consumerlab.com claims the amounts reported by tests it ordered on fish oil supplements are far below those found in a single typical serving of fish.<ref name=review12 />\n\n===Spoilage===\nPeroxides can be produced when fish oil spoils. A study commissioned by the government of Norway concluded there would be some health concern related to the regular consumption of oxidized (rancid) fish/marine oils, particularly in regards to the gastrointestinal tract, but there is not enough data to determine the risk. The amount of spoilage and contamination in a supplement depends on the raw materials and processes of extraction, refining, concentration, encapsulation, storage and transportation.<ref name=norstudy /> ConsumerLab.com reports in its review that it found spoilage in test reports it ordered on some fish oil supplement products.<ref name=review12 />\n\n===EPA and DHA content===\nAccording to [[ConsumerLab.com]] tests, the concentrations of EPA and DHA in supplements can vary from between 8 and 80% fish oil content. The concentration depends on the source of the omega-3s, how the oil is processed, and the amounts of other ingredients included in the supplement.<ref name=review12 />\nA 2012 report claims 4 of 35 fish oil supplements it covered contained less{{quantify|date=December 2012}} EPA or DHA than was claimed on the label, and 3 of 35 contained more.{{quantify|date=December 2012}}<ref name=review12 />\nA ConsumerLab.com publication in 2010 claims 3 of 24 fish oil supplements it covered contained less{{quantify|date=December 2012}} EPA and/or DHA than was claimed on the label.<ref name=clpr /> However, the bioavailability of EPA and DHA from both capsular and emulsified fish oils has been shown to be high.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Raatz | first1 = SK | last2 = Redmon | first2 = JB | last3 = Wimmergren | first3 = N | last4 = Donadio | first4 = JV | last5 = Bibus | first5 = DM | year = 2009 | title = Enhanced absorption of omega-3 fatty acids after emulsified compared with encapsulated fish oil | url = | journal = Journal of the American Dietetic Association | volume = 109 | issue = 6| pages = 1076\u201381 | doi=10.1016/j.jada.2009.03.006| pmid = 19465191 | pmc = 2701654 }}</ref>\n\n===Formulation===\nFish oil supplements are available as liquids or capsules. Some capsules are enteric-coated to pass through the stomach before dissolving in the small intestine, thus helping prevent indigestion and \"fish burps\". Poorly manufactured enteric-coated products have the potential to release ingredients too early. ConsumerLab.com, a for-profit supplement testing company, reported that 1 of the 24 enteric-coated fish oil supplements it evaluated released ingredients prematurely.<ref name=clpr />\n\n===Prescription fish oil===\n{{Expand section | reason = The information here isn't that useful: doesn't lose much just dropping it. | date = January 2019 }}\nFish oil preparations that are only available with a doctor's prescription undergo the same [[Food and Drug Administration|FDA]] regulatory requirements as other prescription pharmaceuticals, with regard to both efficacy and safety.<ref name=\"bays2007\">{{cite journal | author=Bays H E | title=Safety Considerations with Omega-3 Fatty Acid Therapy | volume=99 | journal=The American Journal of Cardiology | issue=6 (Supplement 1) | date=19 March 2007 | pages=S35\u2013S43 | doi=10.1016/j.amjcard.2006.11.020 | pmid=17368277}}</ref> The prescription fish oil drugs are not similar to over-the-counter fish oil supplements. They are not be confused with each other.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medicalxpress.com/news/2019-03-prescription-fish-oil-pill-lowers.html|title=Prescription fish oil pill lowers heart attack risk in those already on statins|website=medicalxpress.com|language=en-us|access-date=2019-09-25}}</ref> Prescription fish oil is considered a safe and effective option to reduce [[Triglyceride|triglycerides]]. There are various prescription fish oil products that have been approved and permitted by [[Food and Drug Administration|FDA]] for increasing triglyceride levels. Prescription fish oil products having DHA raise up the LDL-C levels to reduce triglycerides, like [[Fibrate|fibrates]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.medpagetoday.com/cardiology/dyslipidemia/81701|title=AHA Endorses Prescription Fish Oil for High Triglycerides|date=2019-08-20|website=www.medpagetoday.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-25}}</ref> Even the heart experts advise that prescription fish oil helps in decreasing additional levels of blood fats. As per the latest guideline, prescription fish oils might only help when triglycerides reaches a specific upper level.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.webmd.com/cholesterol-management/news/20190819/heart-experts-support-use-of-prescription-fish-oil|title=Heart Experts Support Use of Prescription Fish Oil|website=WebMD|language=en|access-date=2019-09-25}}</ref> Prescription fish oil pills, capsules and tablets have more omega-3 fatty acids than those which are non-prescribed. FDA regularly monitor those drugs for standards, quality and safety.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.webmd.com/diet/omega-3s-in-fish-oil-and-supplements-whats-your-best-strategy|title=Omega-3 Fish Oil: Supplements and Prescriptions|website=WebMD|language=en|access-date=2019-09-25}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2019, there are four fish oil-based prescription drugs approved by FDA for the treatment of hypertriglyceridemia,<ref name=\"skulas19\"/> namely:\n#Lovaza (omega-3 acid ethyl esters), approved on 10 November 2004.<ref>{{cite web |title=Drugs@FDA: FDA-Approved Drugs |url=https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/scripts/cder/daf/index.cfm?event=overview.process&ApplNo=021654 |website=www.accessdata.fda.gov |accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n#Vascepa (ethyl eicosapentaenoic acid), approved on 26 July 2012.<ref>{{cite web |title=Drug Approval Package: VASCEPA (icosapent ethyl) NDA #202057 |url=https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/drugsatfda_docs/nda/2012/202057_vascepa_toc.cfm |website=www.accessdata.fda.gov |accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref> On 13 December 2019, FDA also approved it as the first drug specifically \"to reduce cardiovascular risk among patients with elevated triglyceride levels.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=FDA approves use of drug to reduce risk of cardiovascular events in certain adult patient groups |url=https://www.fda.gov/news-events/press-announcements/fda-approves-use-drug-reduce-risk-cardiovascular-events-certain-adult-patient-groups |website=FDA |accessdate=15 January 2020 |language=en |date=17 December 2019}}</ref>\n#Epanova (omega-3 carboxylic acids), approved on 23 April 2014.<ref>{{cite web |title=Drugs@FDA: FDA-Approved Drugs |url=https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/scripts/cder/daf/index.cfm?event=overview.process&ApplNo=204977 |website=www.accessdata.fda.gov |accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref> Clinical trial on mixed [[dyslipidaemia]] (hypertriglyceridemia  with hypocholesterolemia) started in 2014<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Nicholls |first1=Stephen J. |last2=Lincoff |first2=A. Michael |last3=Bash |first3=Dianna |last4=Ballantyne |first4=Christie M. |last5=Barter |first5=Philip J. |last6=Davidson |first6=Michael H. |last7=Kastelein |first7=John J. P. |last8=Koenig |first8=Wolfgang |last9=McGuire |first9=Darren K. |last10=Mozaffarian |first10=Dariush |last11=Pedersen |first11=Terje R. |last12=Ridker |first12=Paul M. |last13=Ray |first13=Kausik |last14=Karlson |first14=Bj\u00f6rn W. |last15=Lundstr\u00f6m |first15=Torbj\u00f6rn |last16=Wolski |first16=Kathy |last17=Nissen |first17=Steven E. |title=Assessment of omega-3 carboxylic acids in statin-treated patients with high levels of triglycerides and low levels of high-density lipoprotein cholesterol: Rationale and design of the STRENGTH trial |journal=Clinical Cardiology |date=2018 |volume=41 |issue=10 |pages=1281\u20131288 |doi=10.1002/clc.23055 |pmid=30125052 |display-authors=8 |pmc=6489732}}</ref> found that it has no medicial benefits, and the clinical trial was called of on 13 January 2019.<ref name=\"reuters20\">{{cite news |title=AstraZeneca to discontinue Epanova trial, expects $100 million writedown |url=https://in.reuters.com/article/us-astrazeneca-study/astrazeneca-to-discontinue-epanova-trial-expects-100-million-writedown-idINKBN1ZC0JQ |accessdate=15 January 2020 |work=Reuters |date=13 January 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n#Omtryg (omega-3 acid ethyl esters), approved on 5 May 2014.<ref>{{cite web |title=Drug Approval Package: Epanova (Omega-3-carboxylic acids) |url=https://www.accessdata.fda.gov/drugsatfda_docs/nda/2014/205060Orig1EpanovaTOC.cfm |website=www.accessdata.fda.gov |accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Dangers ==\nA 2013 review concluded that the potential for adverse events amongst older adults taking fish oil \"appear mild\u2013moderate at worst and are unlikely to be of clinical significance\".<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1186/1471-2318-13-41 |title=Fish oil administration in older adults: Is there potential for adverse events? A systematic review of the literature |year=2013 |last1=Villani |first1=Anthony M |last2=Crotty |first2=Maria |last3=Cleland |first3=Leslie G |last4=James |first4=Michael J |last5=Fraser |first5=Robert J |last6=Cobiac |first6=Lynne |last7=Miller |first7=Michelle D |journal=BMC Geriatrics |volume=13 |page=41 |pmid=23634646 |pmc=3664575 |issue=1}}</ref>\n\n=== Maximum intake ===\nThe FDA recommends that consumers do not exceed more than three grams per day of EPA and DHA combined, with no more than 2 grams from a dietary supplement.<ref>{{cite web|title=FDA Announces Qualified Health Claims for Omega-3 Fatty Acids|date=2004-09-08|url=https://www.fda.gov/SiteIndex/ucm108351.htm|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090722101454/https://www.fda.gov/SiteIndex/ucm108351.htm|accessdate=2017-08-21|archive-date=2009-07-22}}</ref> This is not the same as 3000&nbsp;mg of fish oil. A 1000&nbsp;mg pill typically has only 300&nbsp;mg of omega-3; 10 such pills would equal 3000&nbsp;mg of omega-3. \nAccording to the [[European Food Safety Authority]]'s (EFSA) Panel on Dietetic Products, Nutrition and Allergies, supplementation of 5 grams of EPA and DHA combined does not pose a safety concern for adults.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Scientific Opinion on the Tolerable Upper Intake Level of eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA), docosahexaenoic acid (DHA) and docosapentaenoic acid (DPA)|url=http://www.efsa.europa.eu/en/efsajournal/pub/2815|journal=EFSA Journal|volume=10|issue=7|accessdate=14 September 2014|doi=10.2903/j.efsa.2012.2815|year=2012}}</ref> A 1987 study found that healthy [[Greenlandic Inuit]] had an average intake of 5.7 grams of omega-3 EPA per day which had many effects including prolonged bleeding times, i.e., slower blood clotting.<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=3551346 |year=1987 |last1=Kantha |first1=SS |title=Dietary effects of fish oils on human health: A review of recent studies |volume=60 |issue=1 |pages=37\u201344 |pmc=2590235 |journal=The Yale Journal of Biology and Medicine}}</ref>\n\n=== Vitamins ===\nThe liver and liver products (such as [[cod liver oil]]) of fish and many animals (such as seals and whales) contain omega-3, but also the active form of [[vitamin A]]. At high levels, this form of the vitamin can be dangerous ([[Hypervitaminosis A]]).<ref name=\"lips2003\">{{cite journal |doi=10.1056/NEJMe020167 |title=Hypervitaminosis a and Fractures |year=2003 |last1=Lips |first1=Paul |journal=New England Journal of Medicine |volume=348 |issue=4 |pages=347\u201349 |pmid=12540650}}</ref>\n\n=== Toxic pollutants ===\nConsumers of oily fish should be aware of the potential presence of [[heavy metals]] and fat-soluble pollutants like [[Polychlorinated biphenyl|PCBs]] and [[Polychlorinated dibenzodioxins|dioxins]], which are known to [[Biomagnification|accumulate up the food chain]]. After extensive review, researchers from [[Harvard School of Public Health|Harvard's School of Public Health]] in the ''Journal of the American Medical Association'' (2006) reported that the benefits of fish intake generally far outweigh the potential risks.\n\nFish oil supplements came under scrutiny in 2006, when the [[Food Standards Agency]] in the UK and the [[Food Safety Authority of Ireland]] reported [[Polychlorinated biphenyl|PCB]] levels that exceeded the European maximum limits in several fish oil brands,<ref name=foodprod>{{cite web\n |url= http://www.foodproductiondaily.com/news/ng.asp?n=67059-boots-seven-seas-dioxins-fish-oil\n |title=Dioxins prompt second UK fish oil withdrawal|author=Jess Halliday\n |date=2006-04-13|accessdate=8 February 2007}}</ref><ref name=bbc>{{cite news\n | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/1911312.stm\n | date= 2002-04-06| title=Pollutants found in fish oil capsules\n |accessdate=8 February 2007 | work=BBC News}}</ref>\nwhich required temporary withdrawal of these brands. To address the concern over contaminated fish oil supplements, the International Fish Oil Standards (IFOS) Program, a third-party testing and accreditation program for fish oil products, was created by Nutrasource Diagnostics Inc. in Guelph, Ontario, Canada.<ref>[http://www.ifosprogram.com/IFOS/default.aspx International Fish Oil Standards] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120518181053/http://www.ifosprogram.com/IFOS/default.aspx |date=18 May 2012 }}.</ref>\n\nA March 2010 lawsuit filed by a California environmental group claimed that eight brands of fish oil supplements contained excessive levels of PCB's, including [[CVS/pharmacy]], [[Nature Made]], [[Rite Aid]], [[General Nutrition Centers|GNC]], Solgar, [[Twinlab]], Now Health, [[Omega Protein]] and Pharmavite. The majority of these products were either cod liver or shark liver oils. Those participating in the lawsuit claim that because the liver is the major filtering and detoxifying organ, PCB content may be higher in liver-based oils than in fish oil produced from the processing of whole fish.<ref name=abcnews>{{cite web\n |url= http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/ConsumerNews/truth-fish-oil-concerns/story?id=9994049\n |title= Lawsuit Raises Fish Oil Supplement Concerns|author=Elisabeth Leamy\n |date=2010-03-03|accessdate=5 March 2010|author-link= Elisabeth Leamy}}</ref><ref>[http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2010/03/03/BARO1C9RD3.DTL \"Lawsuit says fish oil supplements contain PCB\"], ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'', 3 March 2010.</ref>\n\nAn analysis based on data from the Norwegian Women and Cancer Study (NOWAC) with regards to the dangers of persistent organic pollutants (POPs) in cod liver came to the conclusion that \"in Norwegian women, fish liver consumption was not associated with an increased cancer risk in breast, uterus, or colon. In contrast, a decreased risk for total cancer was found.\"<ref>{{Cite journal |pages=682\u20136 |doi=10.1039/B706302B |title=POP exposure from fish liver consumption and risk of cancer?the Norwegian Women and Cancer Study |year=2007 |last1=Brustad |first1=Magritt |last2=Sandanger |first2=Torkjel Manning |last3=Andersen |first3=Vegard |last4=Lund |first4=Eiliv |journal=Journal of Environmental Monitoring |volume=9 |issue=7 |pmid=17607388}}</ref>\n\nA report by the [[Harvard Medical School]] studied five popular brands of fish oil, including Nordic Ultimate, Kirkland and CVS. They found that the brands had \"negligible amounts of mercury, suggesting either that mercury is removed during the manufacturing of purified fish oil or that the fish sources used in these commercial preparations are relatively mercury-free\".<ref>{{cite journal |pmid=14632570 |url=https://www.archivesofpathology.org/doi/full/10.1043/1543-2165%282003%29127%3C1603%3AMOMLIC%3E2.0.CO%3B2 |year=2003 |volume=127 |pages=1603\u201305 |last1=Foran |first1=Stacy E. |last2=Flood |first2=James G. |last3=Lewandrowski |first3=Kent B. |title=Measurement of Mercury Levels in Concentrated Over-the-Counter Fish Oil Preparations: Is Fish Oil Healthier Than Fish? |issue=12 |journal=Archives of Pathology & Laboratory Medicine |doi=10.1043/1543-2165(2003)127<1603:MOMLIC>2.0.CO;2 |doi-broken-date=2019-12-11 }}</ref>\n\n[[Microalgae]] oil is a [[vegetarian]] alternative to fish oil. Supplements produced from microalgae oil provide a balance of omega-3 fatty acids similar to fish oil, with a lower risk of pollutant exposure.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.2174/157339907781368968 |title=Omega-3 Fatty Acids for Nutrition and Medicine: Considering Microalgae Oil as a Vegetarian Source of EPA and DHA |year=2007 |first1=Scott D. |last1=Doughman |first2=Srirama |last2=Krupanidhi |first3=Carani B. |last3=Sanjeevi |journal=Current Diabetes Reviews |volume=3 |issue=3 |pages=198\u2013203 |pmid=18220672}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n<!-- Please keep entries in alphabetical order & add a short description [[WP:SEEALSO]] -->\n{{div col|small=yes|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Algae]]\n* [[Docosahexaenoic acid]]\n* [[Eicosapentaenoic acid]]\n* [[Krill oil]]\n* [[Lovaza]]\n* [[Shark liver oil]]\n* [[Cod liver oil]]\n{{div col end}}\n<!-- please keep entries in alphabetical order -->\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n* FAO (1986) [http://www.fao.org/DOCREP/003/X6899E/X6899E00.HTM ''The production of fish meal and oil''] FAO Fishery Technical Paper 142. {{ISBN|92-5-102464-2}}.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Fish oil}}\n* [http://www.nutrasource.ca/ifos/ International Fish Oil Standards] \u2014 An [[organization]] concerned with the [[Quality (business)|quality]] of omega-3 products as it relates to the [[international standard]]s established by the [[World Health Organization]] and the Council For Responsible Nutrition for purity and concentration.\n* {{cite web| url=http://www.fatsoflife.com|title=PUFA Newsletter|author=Joyce A. Nettleton, ed|accessdate=20 February 2006}} Two newsletters, both quarterly, reviewing recent publications in essential fatty acids. One is written for researchers, the second is for consumers. Industry sponsored, academic contributors.\n* [http://www.cancer.org/Treatment/TreatmentsandSideEffects/ComplementaryandAlternativeMedicine/DietandNutrition/omega-3-fatty-acids Omega-3 Fatty Acids] ''American Cancer Society''. Updated 11 January 2008.\n\n{{seafood|state=expanded}}\n{{fatsandoils}}\n{{dietary supplement}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fish Oil}}\n[[Category:Dietary supplements]]\n[[Category:Fish products]]\n[[Category:Animal fats]]\n", "name_user": "LilHelpa", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo: medicial\u2192medical", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fish_oil"}
{"title_page": "2020 Tablighi Jamaat coronavirus hotspot in Delhi", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=2020 Tablighi Jamaat coronavirus hotspot in Delhi|timestamp=20200402133413|year=2020|month=April|day=2|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=2020 Tablighi Jamaat coronavirus hotspot in Delhi|date=2 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Infobox event\n| title                    = <!-- Title to display, if other than page name -->\n| image                    =\n| image_upright            = \n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  =\n| native_name              = \n| native_name_lang         = \n| english_name             = \n| time                     =\n| duration                 = \n| date                     = 1 March - 21 March (congregation) \n| venue                    =  [[Banglewali Mosque|Nizamuddin Markaz Mosque]] \n| location                 = [[Nizamuddin West]], [[Delhi]], India\n| coordinates              = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|region:XXXX_type:event|display=inline,title}} -->\n| also_known_as            = Nizamuddin Markaz hotspot\n| type                     = Religious congregation \n| theme                    = \n| cause                    = \n| motive                   =\n| target                   = \n| first_reporter           = \n| budget                   = \n| patron                   = <!-- or |patrons= -->\n| organisers               = <!-- or |organizers= -->\n| filmed_by                = \n| participants             =atleast 9000 people \n| awards                   = \n| url                      = \n| blank_label              = <!-- or |blank_data= -->\n| blank1_label             = <!-- or |blank1_data= -->\n| blank2_label             = <!-- or |blank2_data= -->\n| website                  = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| notes                    = \n}}\n\nA [[Tablighi Jamaat]] religious congregation that took place in Delhi's [[Banglewali Mosque|Nizamuddin Markaz Mosque]] in early March has emerged as a [[Coronavirus disease 2019|coronavirus]] [[super-spreader]] event, after more than 400 confirmed cases and at least 10 deaths linked to the event were reported across the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=India confronts its first coronavirus \u2018super-spreader\u2019 \u2014 a Muslim missionary group with more than 400 members infected |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/india-coronavirus-tablighi-jamaat-delhi/2020/04/02/abdc5af0-7386-11ea-ad9b-254ec99993bc_story.html |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=Washington Post}}</ref> The congregation was attended by people from various states in India as well as 960 foreigners from 40 countries.<ref>{{cite news |title=379 Indonesians among foreigners from 40 countries attended Tablighi Jamaat gathering: Sources |url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/379-indonesians-among-foreigners-from-40-countries-attended-tablighi-jamaat-gathering-sources20200403152720/ |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=ANI}}</ref>\n\nTablighi Jamaat has received widespread criticism from the Muslim community for holding the congregation despite a ban on public gatherings being issued by the [[Government of Delhi]] on 13 March.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tablighi Jamaat draws widespread condemnation from Muslim society |url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/academics-among-muslims-condemn-the-act-of-tablighi-jamaat-in-nizamuddin/article31218658.ece |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=The Hindu Business Line}}</ref> According to the Home Ministry, there were 1,746 people in the Markaz on 21 March.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tablighi Jamaat's defiance spreads concern {{!}} India Today Insight |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/web-exclusive/story/the-new-threat-from-tablighi-jamaat-1661938-2020-04-01 |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=India Today}}</ref>\n\n==Attendees==\n\nAt least 9000 attendees from all over the country and from abroad participated in the congregation.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/americans-british-among-960-foreign-tablighi-jamaat-members-blacklisted-visas-cancelled-2563029.html|title=Americans, British Among 960 Foreign Tablighi Jamaat Members Blacklisted, Visas Cancelled|website=News18|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/1400-nizamuddin-event-attendees-from-maha-traced-tope/articleshow/74965665.cms|title=1,400 Nizamuddin event attendees from Maha traced: Tope|date=2020-04-03|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> Over 800 Indonesian and Malaysian preachers present. Many of these attendees are untraceable and are absconding.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/india/1828919/delhis-tablighi-jamaat-event-becomes-indias-coronavirus-hotspot/|title=A religious congregation in Delhi could be the coronavirus hotspot India was trying to escape|first=Niharika|last=Sharma|website=Quartz India}}</ref> 281 foreigners among 1830 people who had been staying at the mosque since 8 March were found by Delhi Police.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAbout 200 people have shown symptoms of COVID-19 of which, 53 people have been confirmed positive in Delhi.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-52104753|title=India event sparks massive search for Covid-19 cases|date=2020-03-31|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-31|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/opinion/tablighi-jamaat-congregation-and-how-religion-has-been-the-super-spreader-of-coronavirus/392531/|title=Tablighi Jamaat congregation and how religion has been the 'super spreader' of coronavirus|last=Team|first=ThePrint|date=2020-04-01|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gulte.com/news/83733/More-Than-330-Cases-Linked-to-Delhi-Mosque|title=More Than 330 Cases Linked to Delhi Mosque|last=13|date=2020-04-02|website=Gulte|language=english|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The state of [[Tamil Nadu]] reported more than 190 cases linked to the event.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/coronavirus-india-delhi-markaz-nizamuddin-mosque-sealed-after-7-covid-19-deaths-850-moved-out-for-qu-2203336|title=50 Coronavirus Cases In Tamil Nadu After Delhi Mosque Event: 10 Points|website=NDTV.com|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThere was Ijtema (congregation) in every week of March till March 21.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/2100-foreigners-visited-india-for-tablighi-activities-this-year-mha/articleshow/74915572.cms|title=2100 foreigners visited India for Tablighi activities this year: MHA|date=March 31, 2020|via=The Economic Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/nizamuddin-corona-cases-govts-race-to-curb-spread-as-hundreds-from-tablighi-meet-show-coronavirus-symptoms/articleshow/74921860.cms|title=Nizamuddin corona cases: Govts race to curb spread as hundreds from Tablighi meet show symptoms &#124; India News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> There were also other violation of rules by foreign speakers including misuse of tourist visa for missionary activities and not taking 14-day home quarantine for travellers from abroad.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Singh|first=Vijaita|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/home-ministry-to-blacklist-800-tablighi-preachers-from-indonesia-for-violation-of-visa-rules/article31214048.ece|title=Home Ministry asked States to identify 824 foreign Tablighi members|date=2020-03-31|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-02|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> It is believed that the sources of infection were preachers from Indonesia. At least 24 of the attendees had tested positive for the virus among 300 who showed symptom by 31 March 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-india-52104753 |title=Coronavirus: Search for hundreds of people after Delhi prayer meeting |date=31 March 2020 |work=BBC }}</ref> Many had returned to their states and also provided refuge to foreign speakers without the knowledge of local governments.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Saravanan|first=S. p|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/covid-19-five-tourists-from-thailand-admitted-to-isolation-ward-at-erode-hospital/article31088949.ece|title=COVID-19 {{!}} Five tourists from Thailand admitted to isolation ward at Erode hospital|date=2020-03-17|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-02|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> and eventually started local transmissions especially in [[Tamil Nadu]], [[Telengana]], [[Karnataka]], [[Jammu and Kashmir]] and [[Assam]]. On 16 March 2020, Delhi Government ordered that no religious, social, political gatherings of over 50 will be allowed in Delhi till 31 March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/covid-19-no-religious-social-political-gatherings-protests-of-over-50-in-delhi-till-mar-31/articleshow/74650645.cms|title=Coronavirus in Delhi: No religious, social, political gatherings, protests of over 50 in Delhi till Mar 31 &#124; India News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/coronavirus-outbreak-no-religious-social-political-gatherings-of-over-50-in-delhi-till-march-31/articleshow/74650421.cms?from=mdr|title=Coronavirus outbreak: No religious, social, political gatherings of over 50 in Delhi till March 31|date=March 16, 2020|via=The Economic Times}}</ref> As of 30 March 2020 the entire [[Nizamuddin West]] area has been cordoned off by the Police and medical camps have been set up.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/coronavirus-200-people-from-nizamuddin-develop-symptoms-area-cordoned-off/article31204617.ece|title=Coronavirus &#124; 200 people in Nizamuddin develop symptoms; area cordoned off|first=Saurabh|last=Trivedi|date=March 30, 2020|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref> After evacuation from the markaz, of the scores of jamaat attendees, 167 of them were quarantined in a railway facility in south east Delhi amid concerns over their safety and transmission of the virus. There were further complications after the staff at the quarantine facility reported the Tablighi jamaat followers misbehaved with the staff and spit at the doctors looking after them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-india-tablighi-jamaat-attendees-misbehave-staffers-spit-doctors-delhi-quarantine-units-1662322-2020-04-01|title=Tablighi Jamaat attendees misbehave with staffers, spit at doctors at Delhi quarantine units|last=DelhiApril 1|first=Press Trust of India New|last2=April 1|first2=2020UPDATED:|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02|last3=Ist|first3=2020 22:59}}</ref>\n\nAdministration of TJ had said they are willing to dispatch hundreds of missionary to their respective nation & states but as the lockdown is in place they are helpless.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/nizamuddin-markaz-had-sought-help-from-authorities-for-vacating-premises/article31214305.ece|title=Nizamuddin markaz had sought help from authorities for vacating premises|first=Staff|last=Reporter|date=March 31, 2020|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref><ref>Press Release and relevant letters released by the Markaz</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://khabar.ndtv.com/news/india/coronavirus-total-case-in-india-nizamuddin-markaz-organiser-says-continuously-asking-curfew-pass-and-2203440|title=\u0915\u094c\u0928 \u0939\u0948 '\u0918\u094b\u0930 \u0905\u092a\u0930\u093e\u0927\u0940': \u0905\u0917\u0930 \u0924\u092c\u0932\u0940\u0917\u0940 \u091c\u092e\u093e\u0924 \u0928\u0947 \u092e\u093e\u0902\u0917\u093e \u0925\u093e 17 \u0917\u093e\u0921\u093c\u093f\u092f\u094b\u0902 \u0915\u093e \u0915\u0930\u094d\u092b\u094d\u092f\u0942 \u092a\u093e\u0938, \u0924\u094b \u0915\u093f\u0938\u0928\u0947 \u0928\u0939\u0940\u0902 \u0938\u0941\u0928\u0940 \u092c\u093e\u0924|website=NDTVIndia}}</ref>\n\n==Cases linked==\n\nAccording health authorities, until 2. April, among 2000 positive cases in India nearly 400 cases epidemiological linkage can be traced to the Tablighi Jamaat cluster.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/india/one-in-indias-five-covid-19-patients-is-linked-to-tablighi-jamaat-and-its-delhi-event/393993/|title=One in India\u2019s five Covid-19 patients is linked to Tablighi Jamaat and its Delhi event|last=Yadavar|first=Swagata|date=2020-04-02|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/400-covid-19-cases-with-linkage-to-tablighi-jamaat-found-health-ministry/articleshow/74951562.cms|title=400 COVID-19 cases with linkage to Tablighi Jamaat found: Health Ministry {{!}} India News - Times of India|last=Apr 2|first=ANI {{!}}|last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03|last3=Ist|first3=18:55}}</ref> By 3.April, 647 cases are reported which are related to this cluster.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/647-positive-cases-from-14-states-in-last-two-days-are-linked-to-tablighi-jamaat-health-ministry/articleshow/74967407.cms|title=647 coronavirus positive cases from 14 states in last two days are linked to Tablighi Jamaat: Health Ministry|date=2020-04-03|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> Following are some of the  positive cases from different states as reported in media.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! State or UT !! Positive Cases\n!Deaths!! Ref(s)\n|-\n|[[Andaman and Nicobar Islands|Andman and Nicobar]]|| 9\n|{{ndash}}\n|<ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n|[[Andhra Pradesh|Andhra pradesh]]|| 140 \n|1||<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|ur