positive-haryana-govt-120040201310_1.html|title=Five people who attended Jamaat gathering in Delhi test positive: Haryana govt|date=2020-04-02|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Jammu and Kashmir]]|| 22\n|2||<ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n|[[Jharkhand]]\n| -\n| -\n|<ref name=\":4\" />\n|-\n| [[Karnataka]]|| 11\n|1||<ref name=\":2\" />\n|-\n|[[Maharashtra]]\n|{{ndash}}\n|2\n|\n|-\n|[[Puducherry]]|| 2\n|{{ndash}}\n|<ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n|[[Rajasthan]]|| 16\n|{{ndash}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/jaipur/seven-more-covid-19-cases-in-rajasthan-count-rises-to-140/articleshow/74959836.cms|title=Seven more Covid-19 cases in Rajasthan, count rises to 140 {{!}} Jaipur News - Times of India|last=Apr 3|first=ANI {{!}} Updated:|last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03|last3=Ist|first3=09:15}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Tamil Nadu]]|| 190\n|{{ndash}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/in-tn-190-from-tablighi-cluster-test-positive/articleshow/74940016.cms|title=In TN, 190 from Tablighi cluster test positive {{!}} India News - Times of India|last=Narayan|first=Pushpa|last2=Apr 2|first2=Jaya Menon {{!}} TNN {{!}}|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03|last3=2020|last4=Ist|first4=03:06}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Telangana]]|| 50\n|9||<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=691949|title=Tablighi super spreaders cause Covid-19 explosion in India|website=www.daijiworld.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Uttar Pradesh]]|| 42\n|{{ndash}}\n|<ref name=\":2\" />\n|-\n|[[Uttarakhand]]\n| -\n| -\n|<ref name=\":4\" />\n|}\n\n*\n\n\n==Action==\n\nDelhi government ordered an FIR against [[Muhammad Saad Kandhlawi]], the head of Nizamuddin faction of the Tablighi Jamat.<ref name=\"standard\">{{cite web |title=Nizamuddin congregation: Arvind Kejriwal orders FIR against maulana |url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/nizamuddin-congregation-arvind-kejriwal-orders-fir-against-maulana-120033100007_1.html |website=business-standard |publisher=[[Business Standard]] |accessdate=30 March 2020 |date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"indiatoday\">{{cite web |title=Nizamuddin congregation: Arvind Kejriwal orders FIR against maulana |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/nizamuddin-congregation-arvind-kejriwal-orders-fir-against-maulana-1661514-2020-03-30 |website=India Today |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> On 31 March 2020, FIR was filed against [[Muhammad Saad Kandhlawi]] and others by Delhi Police Crime Branch under Section 3 (penalty for offence) of the [[Epidemic Diseases Act, 1897]] and Sections 269 (Negligent act likely to spread infection of disease), 270 (malignant act likely to spread infection of disease), 271 (disobedience to quarantine rule) and 120b (punishment of criminal conspiracy) of the IPC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-in-india-tablighi-jamaat-preacher-others-booked-for-violating-govt-guidelines-on-religious-gatherings-1661870-2020-03-31|title=Coronavirus in India: Tablighi Jamaat preacher, others booked for violating govt guidelines on religious gatherings|first1=India Today Web Desk New|last1=DelhiMarch 31|first2=2020UPDATED:|last2=March 31|first3=2020 21:56|last3=Ist|website=India Today}}</ref>\n\nUnion home Ministry has cancelled tourist visas of 960 foreigners for their involvement in Tablighi Jamaat activities. These include American, British, Chinese, Malaysian, Thai, Vietnamese, Saudi and French Nationals.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in India]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in India]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=2020 Tablighi Jamaat coronavirus hotspot in Delhi|timestamp=20200402133413|year=2020|month=April|day=2|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=2020 Tablighi Jamaat coronavirus hotspot in Delhi|date=2 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Infobox event\n| title                    = <!-- Title to display, if other than page name -->\n| image                    =\n| image_upright            = \n| image_alt                = \n| caption                  =\n| native_name              = \n| native_name_lang         = \n| english_name             = \n| time                     =\n| duration                 = \n| date                     = 1 March - 21 March (congregation) \n| venue                    =  [[Banglewali Mosque|Nizamuddin Markaz Mosque]] \n| location                 = [[Nizamuddin West]], [[Delhi]], India\n| coordinates              = <!-- {{coord|LAT|LON|region:XXXX_type:event|display=inline,title}} -->\n| also_known_as            = Nizamuddin Markaz hotspot\n| type                     = Religious congregation \n| theme                    = \n| cause                    = \n| motive                   =\n| target                   = \n| first_reporter           = \n| budget                   = \n| patron                   = <!-- or |patrons= -->\n| organisers               = <!-- or |organizers= -->\n| filmed_by                = \n| participants             =atleast 9000 people \n| awards                   = \n| url                      = \n| blank_label              = <!-- or |blank_data= -->\n| blank1_label             = <!-- or |blank1_data= -->\n| blank2_label             = <!-- or |blank2_data= -->\n| website                  = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| notes                    = \n}}\n\nA [[Tablighi Jamaat]] religious congregation that took place in Delhi's [[Banglewali Mosque|Nizamuddin Markaz Mosque]] in early March has emerged as a [[Coronavirus disease 2019|coronavirus]] [[super-spreader]] event, after more than 400 confirmed cases and at least 10 deaths linked to the event were reported across the country.<ref>{{cite news |title=India confronts its first coronavirus \u2018super-spreader\u2019 \u2014 a Muslim missionary group with more than 400 members infected |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/india-coronavirus-tablighi-jamaat-delhi/2020/04/02/abdc5af0-7386-11ea-ad9b-254ec99993bc_story.html |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=Washington Post}}</ref> The congregation was attended by people from various states in India as well as 960 foreigners from 40 countries.<ref>{{cite news |title=379 Indonesians among foreigners from 40 countries attended Tablighi Jamaat gathering: Sources |url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/379-indonesians-among-foreigners-from-40-countries-attended-tablighi-jamaat-gathering-sources20200403152720/ |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=ANI}}</ref>\n\nTablighi Jamaat has received widespread criticism from the Muslim community for holding the congregation despite a ban on public gatherings being issued by the [[Government of Delhi]] on 13 March.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tablighi Jamaat draws widespread condemnation from Muslim society |url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/national/academics-among-muslims-condemn-the-act-of-tablighi-jamaat-in-nizamuddin/article31218658.ece |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=The Hindu Business Line}}</ref> According to the Home Ministry, there were 1,746 people in the Markaz on 21 March.<ref>{{cite news |title=Tablighi Jamaat's defiance spreads concern {{!}} India Today Insight |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/web-exclusive/story/the-new-threat-from-tablighi-jamaat-1661938-2020-04-01 |accessdate=3 April 2020 |work=India Today}}</ref>\n\n==Attendees==\n\nAt least 9000 attendees from all over the country and from abroad participated in the congregation.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/americans-british-among-960-foreign-tablighi-jamaat-members-blacklisted-visas-cancelled-2563029.html|title=Americans, British Among 960 Foreign Tablighi Jamaat Members Blacklisted, Visas Cancelled|website=News18|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/1400-nizamuddin-event-attendees-from-maha-traced-tope/articleshow/74965665.cms|title=1,400 Nizamuddin event attendees from Maha traced: Tope|date=2020-04-03|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> Over 800 Indonesian and Malaysian preachers present. Many of these attendees are untraceable and are absconding.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/india/1828919/delhis-tablighi-jamaat-event-becomes-indias-coronavirus-hotspot/|title=A religious congregation in Delhi could be the coronavirus hotspot India was trying to escape|first=Niharika|last=Sharma|website=Quartz India}}</ref> 281 foreigners among 1830 people who had been staying at the mosque since 8 March were found by Delhi Police.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAbout 200 people have shown symptoms of COVID-19 of which, 53 people have been confirmed positive in Delhi.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-52104753|title=India event sparks massive search for Covid-19 cases|date=2020-03-31|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-03-31|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/opinion/tablighi-jamaat-congregation-and-how-religion-has-been-the-super-spreader-of-coronavirus/392531/|title=Tablighi Jamaat congregation and how religion has been the 'super spreader' of coronavirus|last=Team|first=ThePrint|date=2020-04-01|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gulte.com/news/83733/More-Than-330-Cases-Linked-to-Delhi-Mosque|title=More Than 330 Cases Linked to Delhi Mosque|last=13|date=2020-04-02|website=Gulte|language=english|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> The state of [[Tamil Nadu]] reported more than 190 cases linked to the event.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/coronavirus-india-delhi-markaz-nizamuddin-mosque-sealed-after-7-covid-19-deaths-850-moved-out-for-qu-2203336|title=50 Coronavirus Cases In Tamil Nadu After Delhi Mosque Event: 10 Points|website=NDTV.com|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n==Aftermath==\nThere was Ijtema (congregation) in every week of March till March 21.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/2100-foreigners-visited-india-for-tablighi-activities-this-year-mha/articleshow/74915572.cms|title=2100 foreigners visited India for Tablighi activities this year: MHA|date=March 31, 2020|via=The Economic Times}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/nizamuddin-corona-cases-govts-race-to-curb-spread-as-hundreds-from-tablighi-meet-show-coronavirus-symptoms/articleshow/74921860.cms|title=Nizamuddin corona cases: Govts race to curb spread as hundreds from Tablighi meet show symptoms &#124; India News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref> There were also other violation of rules by foreign speakers including misuse of tourist visa for missionary activities and not taking 14-day home quarantine for travellers from abroad.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Singh|first=Vijaita|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/home-ministry-to-blacklist-800-tablighi-preachers-from-indonesia-for-violation-of-visa-rules/article31214048.ece|title=Home Ministry asked States to identify 824 foreign Tablighi members|date=2020-03-31|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-02|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> It is believed that the sources of infection were preachers from Indonesia. At least 24 of the attendees had tested positive for the virus among 300 who showed symptom by 31 March 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-india-52104753 |title=Coronavirus: Search for hundreds of people after Delhi prayer meeting |date=31 March 2020 |work=BBC }}</ref> Many had returned to their states and also provided refuge to foreign speakers without the knowledge of local governments.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Saravanan|first=S. p|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/covid-19-five-tourists-from-thailand-admitted-to-isolation-ward-at-erode-hospital/article31088949.ece|title=COVID-19 {{!}} Five tourists from Thailand admitted to isolation ward at Erode hospital|date=2020-03-17|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-04-02|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> and eventually started local transmissions especially in [[Tamil Nadu]], [[Telengana]], [[Karnataka]], [[Jammu and Kashmir]] and [[Assam]]. On 16 March 2020, Delhi Government ordered that no religious, social, political gatherings of over 50 will be allowed in Delhi till 31 March 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/covid-19-no-religious-social-political-gatherings-protests-of-over-50-in-delhi-till-mar-31/articleshow/74650645.cms|title=Coronavirus in Delhi: No religious, social, political gatherings, protests of over 50 in Delhi till Mar 31 &#124; India News - Times of India|website=The Times of India}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/coronavirus-outbreak-no-religious-social-political-gatherings-of-over-50-in-delhi-till-march-31/articleshow/74650421.cms?from=mdr|title=Coronavirus outbreak: No religious, social, political gatherings of over 50 in Delhi till March 31|date=March 16, 2020|via=The Economic Times}}</ref> As of 30 March 2020 the entire [[Nizamuddin West]] area has been cordoned off by the Police and medical camps have been set up.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Delhi/coronavirus-200-people-from-nizamuddin-develop-symptoms-area-cordoned-off/article31204617.ece|title=Coronavirus &#124; 200 people in Nizamuddin develop symptoms; area cordoned off|first=Saurabh|last=Trivedi|date=March 30, 2020|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref> After evacuation from the markaz, of the scores of jamaat attendees, 167 of them were quarantined in a railway facility in south east Delhi amid concerns over their safety and transmission of the virus. There were further complications after the staff at the quarantine facility reported the Tablighi jamaat followers misbehaved with the staff and spit at the doctors looking after them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-india-tablighi-jamaat-attendees-misbehave-staffers-spit-doctors-delhi-quarantine-units-1662322-2020-04-01|title=Tablighi Jamaat attendees misbehave with staffers, spit at doctors at Delhi quarantine units|last=DelhiApril 1|first=Press Trust of India New|last2=April 1|first2=2020UPDATED:|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02|last3=Ist|first3=2020 22:59}}</ref>\n\nAdministration of TJ had said they are willing to dispatch hundreds of missionary to their respective nation & states but as the lockdown is in place they are helpless.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/nizamuddin-markaz-had-sought-help-from-authorities-for-vacating-premises/article31214305.ece|title=Nizamuddin markaz had sought help from authorities for vacating premises|first=Staff|last=Reporter|date=March 31, 2020|via=www.thehindu.com}}</ref><ref>Press Release and relevant letters released by the Markaz</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://khabar.ndtv.com/news/india/coronavirus-total-case-in-india-nizamuddin-markaz-organiser-says-continuously-asking-curfew-pass-and-2203440|title=\u0915\u094c\u0928 \u0939\u0948 '\u0918\u094b\u0930 \u0905\u092a\u0930\u093e\u0927\u0940': \u0905\u0917\u0930 \u0924\u092c\u0932\u0940\u0917\u0940 \u091c\u092e\u093e\u0924 \u0928\u0947 \u092e\u093e\u0902\u0917\u093e \u0925\u093e 17 \u0917\u093e\u0921\u093c\u093f\u092f\u094b\u0902 \u0915\u093e \u0915\u0930\u094d\u092b\u094d\u092f\u0942 \u092a\u093e\u0938, \u0924\u094b \u0915\u093f\u0938\u0928\u0947 \u0928\u0939\u0940\u0902 \u0938\u0941\u0928\u0940 \u092c\u093e\u0924|website=NDTVIndia}}</ref>\n\n==Cases linked==\n\nAccording health authorities, until 2. April, among 2000 positive cases in India nearly 400 cases epidemiological linkage can be traced to the Tablighi Jamaat cluster.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theprint.in/india/one-in-indias-five-covid-19-patients-is-linked-to-tablighi-jamaat-and-its-delhi-event/393993/|title=One in India\u2019s five Covid-19 patients is linked to Tablighi Jamaat and its Delhi event|last=Yadavar|first=Swagata|date=2020-04-02|website=ThePrint|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/400-covid-19-cases-with-linkage-to-tablighi-jamaat-found-health-ministry/articleshow/74951562.cms|title=400 COVID-19 cases with linkage to Tablighi Jamaat found: Health Ministry {{!}} India News - Times of India|last=Apr 2|first=ANI {{!}}|last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03|last3=Ist|first3=18:55}}</ref> By 3.April, 647 cases are reported which are related to this cluster.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/647-positive-cases-from-14-states-in-last-two-days-are-linked-to-tablighi-jamaat-health-ministry/articleshow/74967407.cms|title=647 coronavirus positive cases from 14 states in last two days are linked to Tablighi Jamaat: Health Ministry|date=2020-04-03|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> Following are some of the  positive cases from different states as reported in media.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! State or UT !! Positive Cases\n!Deaths!! Ref(s)\n|-\n|[[Andaman and Nicobar Islands|Andman and Nicobar]]|| 9\n|{{ndash}}\n|<ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n|[[Andhra Pradesh|Andhra pradesh]]|| 140 \n|1||<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://english.jagran.com/india/coronavirus-outbreak-295-linked-to-tablighi-jamaat-test-positive-for-covid19-960-foreign-attendees-blacklisted-by-mha-10010317|title=Coronavirus Outbreak: Nizamuddin Markaz trail widens with sharp spike in cases in Telangana, Delhi and UP|date=2020-04-03|website=Jagran English|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Assam]]|| 16\n|{{ndash}}\n|<ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n| [[Arunachal Pradesh]]  || 1 \n|{{ndash}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/health/coronavirus-outbreak-arunachal-pradesh-registers-first-covid-19-case-after-31-year-old-tablighi-jamaat-attendee-tests-positive-8219381.html|title=Coronavirus Outbreak: Arunachal Pradesh registers first COVID-19 case after 31-year-old Tablighi Jamaat attendee tests positive|website=Firstpost|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Bihar]]\n|{{ndash}}\n|1\n|\n|-\n| [[Delhi]]|| 259\n|2||<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/arvind-kejriwal-delhi-cm-pc-total-cases-tablighi-jamaat-link-coronavirus-covid19-1662684-2020-04-02|title=Delhi coronavirus toll rises to 4, total cases now 293, half of these linked to Tablighi meet: CM Kejriwal|last=DelhiApril 2|first=Press Trust of India New|last2=April 2|first2=2020UPDATED:|website=India Today|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03|last3=Ist|first3=2020 23:10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/delhi-reports-91-new-covid-19-positive-cases-in-last-24-hrs-total-rises-to-384/articleshow/74968571.cms?from=mdr|title=Delhi reports 91 new COVID-19 positive cases in last 24 hrs; total rises to 384|date=2020-04-03|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Gujarat]]\n|{{ndash}}\n|1\n|\n|-\n|[[Himachal Pradesh]]|| 3\n|{{ndash}}\n|<ref name=\":3\" />\n|-\n|[[Haryana]]\n| -\n| -\n|<ref name=\":4\" />\n|-\n| [[Jammu and Kashmir]]|| 22\n|2||<ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n|[[Jharkhand]]\n| -\n| -\n|<ref name=\":4\" />\n|-\n| [[Karnataka]]|| 11\n|1||<ref name=\":2\" />\n|-\n|[[Maharashtra]]\n|{{ndash}}\n|2\n|\n|-\n|[[Puducherry]]|| 2\n|{{ndash}}\n|<ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n|[[Rajasthan]]|| 16\n|{{ndash}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/jaipur/seven-more-covid-19-cases-in-rajasthan-count-rises-to-140/articleshow/74959836.cms|title=Seven more Covid-19 cases in Rajasthan, count rises to 140 {{!}} Jaipur News - Times of India|last=Apr 3|first=ANI {{!}} Updated:|last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03|last3=Ist|first3=09:15}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Tamil Nadu]]|| 190\n|{{ndash}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/in-tn-190-from-tablighi-cluster-test-positive/articleshow/74940016.cms|title=In TN, 190 from Tablighi cluster test positive {{!}} India News - Times of India|last=Narayan|first=Pushpa|last2=Apr 2|first2=Jaya Menon {{!}} TNN {{!}}|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03|last3=2020|last4=Ist|first4=03:06}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Telangana]]|| 50\n|9||<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=691949|title=Tablighi super spreaders cause Covid-19 explosion in India|website=www.daijiworld.com|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Uttar Pradesh]]|| 42\n|{{ndash}}\n|<ref name=\":2\" />\n|-\n|[[Uttarakhand]]\n| -\n| -\n|<ref name=\":4\" />\n|}\n\n*\n\n\n==Action==\n\nDelhi government ordered an FIR against [[Muhammad Saad Kandhlawi]], the head of Nizamuddin faction of the Tablighi Jamat.<ref name=\"standard\">{{cite web |title=Nizamuddin congregation: Arvind Kejriwal orders FIR against maulana |url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/nizamuddin-congregation-arvind-kejriwal-orders-fir-against-maulana-120033100007_1.html |website=business-standard |publisher=[[Business Standard]] |accessdate=30 March 2020 |date=30 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"indiatoday\">{{cite web |title=Nizamuddin congregation: Arvind Kejriwal orders FIR against maulana |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/nizamuddin-congregation-arvind-kejriwal-orders-fir-against-maulana-1661514-2020-03-30 |website=India Today |accessdate=30 March 2020}}</ref> On 31 March 2020, FIR was filed against [[Muhammad Saad Kandhlawi]] and others by Delhi Police Crime Branch under Section 3 (penalty for offence) of the [[Epidemic Diseases Act, 1897]] and Sections 269 (Negligent act likely to spread infection of disease), 270 (malignant act likely to spread infection of disease), 271 (disobedience to quarantine rule) and 120b (punishment of criminal conspiracy) of the IPC.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/coronavirus-in-india-tablighi-jamaat-preacher-others-booked-for-violating-govt-guidelines-on-religious-gatherings-1661870-2020-03-31|title=Coronavirus in India: Tablighi Jamaat preacher, others booked for violating govt guidelines on religious gatherings|first1=India Today Web Desk New|last1=DelhiMarch 31|first2=2020UPDATED:|last2=March 31|first3=2020 21:56|last3=Ist|website=India Today}}</ref>\n\nUnion home Ministry has cancelled tourist visas of 960 foreigners for their involvement in Tablighi Jamaat activities. These include American, British, Chinese, Malaysian, Thai, Vietnamese, Saudi and French Nationals.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in India]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in India]]\n", "name_user": "XGammaRay", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCases linked:Number of cases in Haryana updated", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_Tablighi_Jamaat_coronavirus_hotspot_in_Delhi"}
{"title_page": "Wilhelm Sollmann", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=February 2015}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=February 2015}}\n[[File:Rathausturm K\u00f6ln - Haubrich - Sollmann (5934-36).jpg|thumb|Right: Statue of Wilhelm Sollmann at the city hall tower of Cologne, Germany]]\n\n'''Friedrich Wilhelm Sollmann''', later '''William Frederick Sollmann''' (1 April 1881 \u2013 6 January 1951) was a [[Germany|German]] journalist, politician, and interior minister of the [[Weimar Republic]]. In 1919, he was on the staff of the German delegation that was to receive the [[Treaty of Versailles]]. In 1933, he emigrated and eventually moved to the [[United States]] where he became an advocate for the peaceful resolution of conflicts.\n\n==Life==\n\n===Early life in the German Empire===\nWilhelm Sollmann was born on 2 April 1881 in {{Interlanguage link multi|Oberlind|de|3=Oberlind (Sonneberg)|lt=Oberlind}}, [[Saxe-Meiningen]] (today a part of [[Sonneberg]], [[Thuringia]]). His father was Johan Jakob Sollmann, a brewer and farmer in Oberlind and after 1889 tenant of the ''Ratskeller'' at [[Coburg, Germany|Coburg]]. His mother was Christiane Sollmann, inn keeper. After the move to Coburg, Wilhelm attended the Casimirianum [[Gymnasium (Germany)|gymnasium]] from 1891 to 1897, when he had to leave due to the family's financial difficulties. That year, his family moved to [[Cologne]]. There, he began work as an apprentice (''kaufm\u00e4nnische Lehre''). From 1901-11 he worked as a ''Handlungsgehilfe'' whilst attending night school at the ''Handelshochschule K\u00f6ln''. Originally rooted in Lutheran Christianity, he was a member of the ''[[International Organisation of Good Templars|Internationaler Guttempler-Orden]]'' and the [[YMCA|CVJM]]. However, in 1902 he joined the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany]] (SPD) and in 1907 co-founded the Workers' Youth at Cologne. He was also active in the [[temperance movement]] and was chairman of the ''Arbeiter-Abstinenzbewegung'' (workers' temperance movement, 1906\u201310). He was also a member of the ''Angestelltengwerkschaft'' (white-collar workers' union). In 1906, Sollmann married Anna Katharina (K\u00e4the, Kate) n\u00e9e Gr\u00fcmmer (born 1883, died before 1975). They had one daughter, Elfriede (1912\u201397). In 1908, Sollmann became a ''[[Freethought|Freidenker]]''.<ref name=Bio>{{cite web|url=http://www.deutsche-biographie.de/sfz122761.html|title=Biografie Friedrich Wilhem Sollmann (German)|publisher=Bayerische Nationalbibliothek|accessdate=26 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1911, Sollmann became editor of the socialdemocratic newspaper ''Fr\u00e4nkischer Volksfreund'' at [[W\u00fcrzburg]], but soon returned to Cologne where he became editor (1912) and later editor-in-chief (1920\u201333) of the ''[[Rheinische Zeitung]]''. During [[World War I]], Sollmann was the chairman of the socialdemocratic union (''Verein'') of Cologne.<ref name=\"Bio\"/>\n\n===German Revolution and Weimar Republic===\nDuring the [[German Revolution of 1918-19|German Revolution]] of 1918 he played a key role in the formed Workers' and soldiers' council of Cologne. From 1918-24, Sollmann was a member of the Cologne municipal parliament (''Stadtverordneter''). In 1919, he was elected to the [[Weimar National Assembly]] and held his seat until the new elections to the Reichstag in 1920. Working closely with [[Konrad Adenauer]], whom he later described as \"a personal friend and political enemy\", Sollmann helped turn the ''Handelshochschule'' into the [[University of Cologne]] in 1919. He rejected an honorific doctorate in 1919 (and again in 1928) for personal reasons.<ref name=\"Bio\"/>\n\nIn 1919, Sollmann also was a staff member of the German delegation to the [[Paris Peace Conference, 1919|Paris Peace Conference]] in Versailles, where he served as an expert on problems of the Rheinland occupation. He was a member of the [[Reichstag (Weimar Republic)|Reichstag]] from 1920 until 1933. In 1921, he initiated the establishment of the ''Sozialdemokratischer Parlamentsdienst'' (after 1924: ''Sozialdemokratischer Pressedienst''), a political news service. From 13 August 1923 until his resignation on 3 November, he served as ''Reichsminister des Innern'' (Reich Minister of the Interior) in the cabinets of [[Gustav Stresemann]].<ref name=\"Bio\"/>\n\nIn parliament, he served as a member of the Committee for Foreign Affairs, and as an expert on disarmament and adult education.{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\n===Germany 1933 and emigration===\nIn 1933, he was elected to the executive board of the SPD and as such persecuted by the Nazis after the ''[[Machtergreifung]]''. On 9 March, he was taken into ''Schutzhaft'' (\"protective custody\") and tortured. After being released, he fled in May via Luxembourg to the [[Saar (League of Nations)|occupied Saar]]. There he briefly worked as the editor-in-chief of the socialdemocratic ''Volskstimme''. After the [[1935 Saar status referendum|referendum]] he returned to Luxembourg, in 1936 went on to the [[United Kingdom]] and in 1937 emigrated to the United States.<ref name=\"Bio\"/>\n\n===In America===\nIn the U.S., Sollmann worked as a writer, speaker, radio announcer and faculty member (1937\u20131950) of the [[Pendle Hill Quaker Center for Study and Contemplation]], a Quaker study center located in Wallingford, Pennsylvania.<ref name=\"Bio\"/>\n\nIn the next years, Sollmann travelled through most of the United States, giving lectures on world affairs. He became a visiting professor of international affairs at [[Haverford College|Haverford]], [[Bard College|Bard]], and [[Reed college|Reed Colleges]].{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\nHaving lost his German citizenship in 1936, in 1943 he was naturalized and changed his name to William Frederick Sollmann. That year, he also became a Quaker.<ref name=\"Bio\"/>\n\nA member of the SPD's right wing, in exile he was one of the leading proponents of the ''volkssozialistische Richtung'' within the party. At the request of the [[American Friends Service Committee]], a Quaker organization, Sollmann briefly visited occupied Germany in 1948, where he held speeches and radio addresses. On another visit the following year he served as visiting professor at the University of Cologne. In 1949/50, the U.S. government consulted him on setting up a new German Civil Liberties Union (''Bund f\u00fcr B\u00fcrgerrechte'') and he worked for the [[Allied High Commission]], but he had to return to the United States due to the onset of illness. During his visits, he met with politicians like Adenauer and [[Kurt Schumacher]] and also was Adenauer's guest of honour at the inaugural meeting of the ''[[Deutscher Bundestag]]''. Sollmann was co-founder of the [[Carl Schurz]]-Gesellschaft, member of the ''Verbands deutscher Journalisten im Ausland'' and of the Legion for American Unity.<ref name=\"Bio\"/><ref name=Bio2>{{cite web|url=https://www.bundesarchiv.de/aktenreichskanzlei/1919-1933/0000/adr/adrsz/kap1_1/para2_387.html|title=Akten der Reichskanzlei: Biografie Friedrich Wilhem Sollmann (German)|publisher=Bundesarchiv|accessdate=26 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 January 1951, Sollmann died in [[Mount Carmel, Connecticut]].<ref name=\"Bio\"/>\n\nA street in Cologne is named after him.<ref name=\"Bio\"/>\n\n==Works==\n* ''Zum Ausbau unserer sozialistischen Jugendbewegung'', in: Die neue Zeit, Wochenschrift der deutschen Sozialdemokratie, 1911\n* ''Der K\u00f6lner Polizeiproze\u00df vom 7. \u2013 17. 1. 1914'', 1914\n* ''Ern\u00e4hrungsbeirat von Frauen'', in: Die Gleichheit 26, 1916\n* ''Die Revolution in K\u00f6ln'', 1918\n* ''Sozialismus der Tat'', 1925\n* ''Untergang Amerikas'', in: Studierstube 23, 1927\n* ''Antwort an Josef Wirth, Wahlrecht und Parteien'', in: Deutsche Republik 3, 1929\n* ''Presse und Kommunalverwaltung'', in: Vortr\u00e4ge und Abhandlungen internationaler Institute (K\u00f6ln), R. 11, 1930\n* ''Jugend und Partei'', in: Neue Bl\u00e4tter f\u00fcr den Sozialismus 2, 1931\n* ''Alkohol und \u00f6ffentliche Meinung'', in: Alkoholismus, Gesundheitspolitik, Gesundheitswirtschaft, 1931\n* ''Schankst\u00e4tten und Sozialhygiene'', in: Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Gesundheitsverwaltung und Gesundheitsf\u00fcrsorge 1, 1932\n* ''Der politische Antisemitismus'', in: Gegen die Phrase vom j\u00fcdischen Sch\u00e4dling, 1933\n* ''Sozialistische Machtpolitik, in: Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Sozialismus 2, 1935, pp.&nbsp;758\u201365\n* Religion and Politics, 1941\n* German Labour, Hitler's Nemesis, in: Peace Aim Leaflets 1, 1943\n* Educational Reconstruction in Germany, in: Schoolmen's Week Proceedings, 1944\n* ''Zwischen Krieg und Frieden'', 1948\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.swarthmore.edu/Library/peace/DG026-050/dg045wfsoll.htm Wilhelm Sollmann papers at the Swarthmore College Peace Collection]\n\n{{Interior Ministers of Germany}}\n{{First Stresemann cabinet}}\n{{Second Stresemann cabinet}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sollmann, Wilhelm}}\n[[Category:1881 births]]\n[[Category:1951 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Sonneberg]]\n[[Category:People from Saxe-Meiningen]]\n[[Category:Social Democratic Party of Germany politicians]]\n[[Category:Interior ministers of Germany]]\n[[Category:Members of the Weimar National Assembly]]\n[[Category:Members of the Reichstag of the Weimar Republic]]\n[[Category:Bard College faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=February 2015}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=February 2015}}\n[[File:Rathausturm K\u00f6ln - Haubrich - Sollmann (5934-36).jpg|thumb|Right: Statue of Wilhelm Sollmann at the city hall tower of Cologne, Germany]]\n\n'''Friedrich Wilhelm Sollmann''', later '''William Frederick Sollmann''' (1 April 1881 \u2013 6 January 1951) was a [[Germany|German]] journalist, politician, and interior minister of the [[Weimar Republic]]. In 1919, he was on the staff of the German delegation that was to receive the [[Treaty of Versailles]]. In 1933, he emigrated and eventually moved to the [[United States]] where he became an advocate for the peaceful resolution of conflicts.\n\n==Life==\n\n===Early life in the German Empire===\nWilhelm Sollmann was born on 2 April 1881 in {{Interlanguage link multi|Oberlind|de|3=Oberlind (Sonneberg)|lt=Oberlind}}, [[Saxe-Meiningen]] (today a part of [[Sonneberg]], [[Thuringia]]). His father was Johan Jakob Sollmann, a brewer and farmer in Oberlind and after 1889 tenant of the ''Ratskeller'' at [[Coburg, Germany|Coburg]]. His mother was Christiane Sollmann, inn keeper. After the move to Coburg, Wilhelm attended the Casimirianum [[Gymnasium (Germany)|gymnasium]] from 1891 to 1897, when he had to leave due to the family's financial difficulties. That year, his family moved to [[Cologne]]. There, he began work as an apprentice (''kaufm\u00e4nnische Lehre''). From 1901-11 he worked as a ''Handlungsgehilfe'' whilst attending night school at the ''Handelshochschule K\u00f6ln''. Originally rooted in Lutheran Christianity, he was a member of the ''[[International Organisation of Good Templars|Internationaler Guttempler-Orden]]'' and the [[YMCA|CVJM]]. However, in 1902 he joined the [[Social Democratic Party of Germany]] (SPD) and in 1907 co-founded the Workers' Youth at Cologne. He was also active in the [[temperance movement]] and was chairman of the ''Arbeiter-Abstinenzbewegung'' (workers' temperance movement, 1906\u201310). He was also a member of the ''Angestelltengwerkschaft'' (white-collar workers' union). In 1906, Sollmann married Anna Katharina (K\u00e4the, Kate) n\u00e9e Gr\u00fcmmer (born 1883, died before 1975). They had one daughter, Elfriede (1912\u201397). In 1908, Sollmann became a ''[[Freethought|Freidenker]]''.<ref name=Bio>{{cite web|url=http://www.deutsche-biographie.de/sfz122761.html|title=Biografie Friedrich Wilhem Sollmann (German)|publisher=Bayerische Nationalbibliothek|accessdate=26 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1911, Sollmann became editor of the socialdemocratic newspaper ''Fr\u00e4nkischer Volksfreund'' at [[W\u00fcrzburg]], but soon returned to Cologne where be became editor (1912) and later editor-in-chief (1920\u201333) of the ''[[Rheinische Zeitung]]''. During [[World War I]], Sollmann was the chairman of the socialdemocratic union (''Verein'') of Cologne.<ref name=\"Bio\"/>\n\n===German Revolution and Weimar Republic===\nDuring the [[German Revolution of 1918-19|German Revolution]] of 1918 he played a key role in the formed Workers' and soldiers' council of Cologne. From 1918-24, Sollmann was a member of the Cologne municipal parliament (''Stadtverordneter''). In 1919, he was elected to the [[Weimar National Assembly]] and held his seat until the new elections to the Reichstag in 1920. Working closely with [[Konrad Adenauer]], whom he later described as \"a personal friend and political enemy\", Sollmann helped turn the ''Handelshochschule'' into the [[University of Cologne]] in 1919. He rejected an honorific doctorate in 1919 (and again in 1928) for personal reasons.<ref name=\"Bio\"/>\n\nIn 1919, Sollmann also was a staff member of the German delegation to the [[Paris Peace Conference, 1919|Paris Peace Conference]] in Versailles, where he served as an expert on problems of the Rheinland occupation. He was a member of the [[Reichstag (Weimar Republic)|Reichstag]] from 1920 until 1933. In 1921, he initiated the establishment of the ''Sozialdemokratischer Parlamentsdienst'' (after 1924: ''Sozialdemokratischer Pressedienst''), a political news service. From 13 August 1923 until his resignation on 3 November, he served as ''Reichsminister des Innern'' (Reich Minister of the Interior) in the cabinets of [[Gustav Stresemann]].<ref name=\"Bio\"/>\n\nIn parliament, he served as a member of the Committee for Foreign Affairs, and as an expert on disarmament and adult education.{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\n===Germany 1933 and emigration===\nIn 1933, he was elected to the executive board of the SPD and as such persecuted by the Nazis after the ''[[Machtergreifung]]''. On 9 March, he was taken into ''Schutzhaft'' (\"protective custody\") and tortured. After being released, he fled in May via Luxembourg to the [[Saar (League of Nations)|occupied Saar]]. There he briefly worked as the editor-in-chief of the socialdemocratic ''Volskstimme''. After the [[1935 Saar status referendum|referendum]] he returned to Luxembourg, in 1936 went on to the [[United Kingdom]] and in 1937 emigrated to the United States.<ref name=\"Bio\"/>\n\n===In America===\nIn the U.S., Sollmann worked as a writer, speaker, radio announcer and faculty member (1937\u20131950) of the [[Pendle Hill Quaker Center for Study and Contemplation]], a Quaker study center located in Wallingford, Pennsylvania.<ref name=\"Bio\"/>\n\nIn the next years, Sollmann travelled through most of the United States, giving lectures on world affairs. He became a visiting professor of international affairs at [[Haverford College|Haverford]], [[Bard College|Bard]], and [[Reed college|Reed Colleges]].{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\nHaving lost his German citizenship in 1936, in 1943 he was naturalized and changed his name to William Frederick Sollmann. That year, he also became a Quaker.<ref name=\"Bio\"/>\n\nA member of the SPD's right wing, in exile he was one of the leading proponents of the ''volkssozialistische Richtung'' within the party. At the request of the [[American Friends Service Committee]], a Quaker organization, Sollmann briefly visited occupied Germany in 1948, where he held speeches and radio addresses. On another visit the following year he served as visiting professor at the University of Cologne. In 1949/50, the U.S. government consulted him on setting up a new German Civil Liberties Union (''Bund f\u00fcr B\u00fcrgerrechte'') and he worked for the [[Allied High Commission]], but he had to return to the United States due to the onset of illness. During his visits, he met with politicians like Adenauer and [[Kurt Schumacher]] and also was Adenauer's guest of honour at the inaugural meeting of the ''[[Deutscher Bundestag]]''. Sollmann was co-founder of the [[Carl Schurz]]-Gesellschaft, member of the ''Verbands deutscher Journalisten im Ausland'' and of the Legion for American Unity.<ref name=\"Bio\"/><ref name=Bio2>{{cite web|url=https://www.bundesarchiv.de/aktenreichskanzlei/1919-1933/0000/adr/adrsz/kap1_1/para2_387.html|title=Akten der Reichskanzlei: Biografie Friedrich Wilhem Sollmann (German)|publisher=Bundesarchiv|accessdate=26 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 January 1951, Sollmann died in [[Mount Carmel, Connecticut]].<ref name=\"Bio\"/>\n\nA street in Cologne is named after him.<ref name=\"Bio\"/>\n\n==Works==\n* ''Zum Ausbau unserer sozialistischen Jugendbewegung'', in: Die neue Zeit, Wochenschrift der deutschen Sozialdemokratie, 1911\n* ''Der K\u00f6lner Polizeiproze\u00df vom 7. \u2013 17. 1. 1914'', 1914\n* ''Ern\u00e4hrungsbeirat von Frauen'', in: Die Gleichheit 26, 1916\n* ''Die Revolution in K\u00f6ln'', 1918\n* ''Sozialismus der Tat'', 1925\n* ''Untergang Amerikas'', in: Studierstube 23, 1927\n* ''Antwort an Josef Wirth, Wahlrecht und Parteien'', in: Deutsche Republik 3, 1929\n* ''Presse und Kommunalverwaltung'', in: Vortr\u00e4ge und Abhandlungen internationaler Institute (K\u00f6ln), R. 11, 1930\n* ''Jugend und Partei'', in: Neue Bl\u00e4tter f\u00fcr den Sozialismus 2, 1931\n* ''Alkohol und \u00f6ffentliche Meinung'', in: Alkoholismus, Gesundheitspolitik, Gesundheitswirtschaft, 1931\n* ''Schankst\u00e4tten und Sozialhygiene'', in: Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Gesundheitsverwaltung und Gesundheitsf\u00fcrsorge 1, 1932\n* ''Der politische Antisemitismus'', in: Gegen die Phrase vom j\u00fcdischen Sch\u00e4dling, 1933\n* ''Sozialistische Machtpolitik, in: Zeitschrift f\u00fcr Sozialismus 2, 1935, pp.&nbsp;758\u201365\n* Religion and Politics, 1941\n* German Labour, Hitler's Nemesis, in: Peace Aim Leaflets 1, 1943\n* Educational Reconstruction in Germany, in: Schoolmen's Week Proceedings, 1944\n* ''Zwischen Krieg und Frieden'', 1948\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.swarthmore.edu/Library/peace/DG026-050/dg045wfsoll.htm Wilhelm Sollmann papers at the Swarthmore College Peace Collection]\n\n{{Interior Ministers of Germany}}\n{{First Stresemann cabinet}}\n{{Second Stresemann cabinet}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sollmann, Wilhelm}}\n[[Category:1881 births]]\n[[Category:1951 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Sonneberg]]\n[[Category:People from Saxe-Meiningen]]\n[[Category:Social Democratic Party of Germany politicians]]\n[[Category:Interior ministers of Germany]]\n[[Category:Members of the Weimar National Assembly]]\n[[Category:Members of the Reichstag of the Weimar Republic]]\n[[Category:Bard College faculty]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo fixing, replaced: be became \u2192 he became", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilhelm_Sollmann"}
{"title_page": "Helmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen", "text_new": "{{Infobox Organization\n| name = Helmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen\n| native_name = Helmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen - German Research Center for Environmental Health\n| native_name_lang = de\n| Form of organization = GmbH\n| Foundation = {{start date and age|paren=yes|1960}}\n| Address = Ingolst\u00e4dter Landstr. 1, 85764 Neuherberg, Germany\n| CEO and President = Prof. Dr. Matthias H. Tsch\u00f6p\n| CFO and CTO = Kerstin G\u00fcnther\n| Institutes and Units = 57\n| Employees = 2546 (2018)\n| Trainee positions = 60\n| homepage = {{url|https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/helmholtz-zentrum-muenchen/index.html/}}\n}}\n'''Helmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen''' is a member of the [[Helmholtz Association of German Research Centres]]. It was founded in 1960 and is a joint venture by the [[Federal Ministry of Education and Research (Germany)|Federal Ministry of Education and Research]] and [[:de:Bayerisches_Staatsministerium_der_Finanzen_und_f\u00fcr_Heimat|Bavarian State Ministry of Finance and Home]].\n\n==='''Mission'''===\nThe mission of Helmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen is to find new personalized medical solutions for the prevention, diagnosis and therapy of environmentally triggered diseases to promote a healthier society in a rapidly changing world.\n\n==='''Management'''===\n[[Matthias Tsch\u00f6p|Prof. Dr. H. Matthias Tsch\u00f6p]] has been the Scientific Director and Chief Executive Officer of the Center since 2018.\nIn 2019 [[Kerstin G\u00fcnther]] joined the Center and is now the Chief Financial and Technology Officer.\n\n==='''[https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/about-us/locations/index.html Campus]'''===\nThe main campus is located in Neuherberg, a district of Oberschlei\u00dfheim, right outside of [[Munich]]\u2019s city borders. The campus has a size of 52.3 hectares. In addition, the Center maintains research facilities inside the city area of Munich, Augsburg, T\u00fcbingen, Hanover, Dresden and Leipzig.\n\n==='''Legal form'''===\nHelmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen is a limited liability company according to German law and is financed by a ratio of 90:10 by its two shareholders, the Federal Government and the Free State of Bavaria.\n\n=== '''[https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/helmholtz-zentrum-muenchen/index.html Research Focus]''' ===\nThe Center focuses its research on five key areas:\n\n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/research/research-institutions/metabolic-health/index.html Metabolic Health]\n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/research/research-institutions/environmental-health/index.html Environmental Health] \n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/research/research-institutions/molecular-targets-therapies/index.html Molecular Targets and Therapies] \n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/research/research-institutions/cellprogramming-repair/index.html Cell Programming and Repair] \n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/research/research-institutions/bioengineering-digital-health/index.html Bioengineering and Digital Health]\n\n=== '''[https://www.pioneercampus.org/ Helmholtz Pioneer Campus] (HPC)''' ===\nHPC is an innovation campus where young investigators research for novel solutions in the fields of biomedical sciences, engineering and digitization in the research environment of Helmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen.\n\n=== '''[https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/innovationen/translational-and-clinical-projects/translational-research-centers/index.html Translational and Clinical Projects]''' ===\nTranslational research approaches at the Center are developed in cooperation with clinical partners within a dynamic project portfolio: \n\n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/idf/index.html Diabetes Study Center]\n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/ilbd/index.html Comprehensive Pneumology Center]\n* [https://www.zaum-online.de/ Center of Allergy and Environment]\n\n=== '''[https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/career/graduates-entry-level-professionals/research/index.html Career development]''' ===\nThe Center has one Helmholtz Graduate School (HELENA) in cooperation with the Ludwig Maximilian University Munich (LMU) and the Technical University Munich (TUM), and five Helmholtz Research Schools. The schools offer doctoral students in-depth research in the fields of diabetes, lung and radiation research, epigenetics and data science:\n\n* [https://www.helmholtz-helena.de/ Helmholtz Graduate School Environmental Health (HELENA)]\n* [https://www.helmholtzresearchschool-diabetes.org/ International Helmholtz Research School for Diabetes]\n* [https://www.helmholtzresearchschool-epigenetics.org/ Helmholtz International Epigenetics Research School]\n* [https://www.cpc-researchschool.org/ CPC-Research School Lung Biology and Disease]\n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/helmholtz-research-school-of-radiation-sciences-rs2/index.html Helmholtz Research School of Radiation Science]\n* [https://www.mu-ds.de/ Munich School for Data Science]\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/index.html Helmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen]\n* [http://www.helmholtz-helena.de Helmholtz Graduate School Environmental Health ]\n* [http://www.helmholtz.de/en/ Helmholtz Association]\n* [http://www.cpc-munich.org/ Comprehensive Pneumology Center]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{coord|48|13|21|N|11|35|36|E|region:DE-BY_type:landmark_source:kolossus-dewiki|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Helmholtz Zentrum Munchen}}\n[[Category:Medical research institutes in Germany]]\n[[Category:Medical and health organisations based in Bavaria]]\n__FORCETOC__\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Organization\n| name = Helmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen\n| native_name = Helmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen - German Research Center for Environmental Health\n| native_name_lang = de\n| Form of organization = GmbH\n| Foundation = {{start date and age|paren=yes|1960}}\n| Address = Ingolst\u00e4dter Landstr. 1, 85764 Neuherberg, Germany\n| CEO and President = Prof. Dr. Matthias H. Tsch\u00f6p\n| CFO and CTO = Kerstin G\u00fcnther\n| Institutes and Units = 57\n| Employees = 2546 (2018)\n| Trainee positions = 60\n| homepage = {{url|https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/helmholtz-zentrum-muenchen/index.html/}}\n\n\n'''Helmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen''' is a member of the [[Helmholtz Association of German Research Centres]]. It was founded in 1960 and is a joint venture by the [[Federal Ministry of Education and Research (Germany)|Federal Ministry of Education and Research]] and [[:de:Bayerisches_Staatsministerium_der_Finanzen_und_f\u00fcr_Heimat|Bavarian State Ministry of Finance and Home]].\n\n==='''Mission'''===\nThe mission of Helmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen is to find new personalized medical solutions for the prevention, diagnosis and therapy of environmentally triggered diseases to promote a healthier society in a rapidly changing world.\n\n==='''Management'''===\n[[Matthias Tsch\u00f6p|Prof. Dr. H. Matthias Tsch\u00f6p]] has been the Scientific Director and Chief Executive Officer of the Center since 2018.\nIn 2019 [[Kerstin G\u00fcnther]] joined the Center and is now the Chief Financial and Technology Officer.\n\n==='''[https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/about-us/locations/index.html Campus]'''===\nThe main campus is located in Neuherberg, a district of Oberschlei\u00dfheim, right outside of [[Munich]]\u2019s city borders. The campus has a size of 52.3 hectares. In addition, the Center maintains research facilities inside the city area of Munich, Augsburg, T\u00fcbingen, Hanover, Dresden and Leipzig.\n\n==='''Legal form'''===\nHelmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen is a limited liability company according to German law and is financed by a ratio of 90:10 by its two shareholders, the Federal Government and the Free State of Bavaria.\n\n=== '''[https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/helmholtz-zentrum-muenchen/index.html Research Focus]''' ===\nThe Center focuses its research on five key areas:\n\n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/research/research-institutions/metabolic-health/index.html Metabolic Health]\n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/research/research-institutions/environmental-health/index.html Environmental Health] \n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/research/research-institutions/molecular-targets-therapies/index.html Molecular Targets and Therapies] \n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/research/research-institutions/cellprogramming-repair/index.html Cell Programming and Repair] \n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/research/research-institutions/bioengineering-digital-health/index.html Bioengineering and Digital Health]\n\n=== '''[https://www.pioneercampus.org/ Helmholtz Pioneer Campus] (HPC)''' ===\nHPC is an innovation campus where young investigators research for novel solutions in the fields of biomedical sciences, engineering and digitization in the research environment of Helmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen.\n\n=== '''[https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/innovationen/translational-and-clinical-projects/translational-research-centers/index.html Translational and Clinical Projects]''' ===\nTranslational research approaches at the Center are developed in cooperation with clinical partners within a dynamic project portfolio: \n\n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/idf/index.html Diabetes Study Center]\n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/ilbd/index.html Comprehensive Pneumology Center]\n* [https://www.zaum-online.de/ Center of Allergy and Environment]\n\n=== '''[https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/career/graduates-entry-level-professionals/research/index.html Career development]''' ===\nThe Center has one Helmholtz Graduate School (HELENA) in cooperation with the Ludwig Maximilian University Munich (LMU) and the Technical University Munich (TUM), and five Helmholtz Research Schools. The schools offer doctoral students in-depth research in the fields of diabetes, lung and radiation research, epigenetics and data science:\n\n* [https://www.helmholtz-helena.de/ Helmholtz Graduate School Environmental Health (HELENA)]\n* [https://www.helmholtzresearchschool-diabetes.org/ International Helmholtz Research School for Diabetes]\n* [https://www.helmholtzresearchschool-epigenetics.org/ Helmholtz International Epigenetics Research School]\n* [https://www.cpc-researchschool.org/ CPC-Research School Lung Biology and Disease]\n* [https://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/helmholtz-research-school-of-radiation-sciences-rs2/index.html Helmholtz Research School of Radiation Science]\n* [https://www.mu-ds.de/ Munich School for Data Science]\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.helmholtz-muenchen.de/en/index.html Helmholtz Zentrum M\u00fcnchen]\n* [http://www.helmholtz-helena.de Helmholtz Graduate School Environmental Health ]\n* [http://www.helmholtz.de/en/ Helmholtz Association]\n* [http://www.cpc-munich.org/ Comprehensive Pneumology Center]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n{{coord|48|13|21|N|11|35|36|E|region:DE-BY_type:landmark_source:kolossus-dewiki|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Helmholtz Zentrum Munchen}}\n[[Category:Medical research institutes in Germany]]\n[[Category:Medical and health organisations based in Bavaria]]\n__FORCETOC__\n", "name_user": "Ako helmholtz", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Helmholtz_Zentrum_M%C3%BCnchen"}
{"title_page": "Richard Erdman", "text_new": "{{about||the American artist|Richard Erdman (artist)|the American diplomat|Richard W. Erdman}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Richard Erdman\n| image        = Richard Erdman (1950) The Admiral Was a Lady.jpg\n| image_size   = \n| alt          = \n| caption      = Erdman in ''[[The Admiral Was a Lady]]'' (1950)\n| birth_name   = John Richard Erdmann \n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1925|6|1|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Enid, Oklahoma|Enid]], [[Oklahoma]], U.S.\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|2019|3|16|1925|6|1}}\n| death_place  = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| nationality  =\n| other_names  = Dick Erdman \n| ethnicity    = \n| citizenship  = \n| education    = \n| alma_mater   = \n| occupation   =  {{flatlist|\n*Actor\n*director}}\n| years_active = 1944\u20132017\n| known_for    = ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]'' (2009-2015) <br/> ''[[Stalag 17]]'' (1953) <br/> ''[[Tora! Tora! Tora!]]'' (1970)\n| spouse       = {{ubl|{{marriage|Leza Holland|1948|1950|reason=div}}|{{marriage|Sharon Randall|1953|2016|reason=d.}}}} \n| partner      = \n| children     = 1 \n}}\n\n'''John Richard Erdman''' (June 1, 1925 \u2013 March 16, 2019) was an [[United States|American]] [[character actor]] and occasional film and television [[Film director|director]].<ref>{{cite web| work=[[The New York Times]]| title=Richard Erdman| url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/89065/Richard-Erdman}}</ref> He appeared in more than 160 films, and television productions between 1944 and 2017, mostly in supporting roles.<ref name=\"Utah\">{{cite news| url=https://newspaperarchive.com/us/utah/salt-lake-city/salt-lake-tribune/1967/07-21/page-17| title=Nothing Serious| newspaper=[[Salt Lake Tribune]]| date=July 21, 1967| accessdate=February 19, 2017| last=Valentine| first=Dan}}</ref> He is most known for his recurring role in the critically acclaimed comedy series ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]'' (2009-2015), and the classic films, ''[[Stalag 17]]'' (1953), and ''[[Tora! Tora! Tora!]]'' (1970).\n \nHe has guest starred in a wide variety of shows such as ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]'', ''[[Alfred Hitchcock Presents]]'', ''[[The Twilight Zone (1959 TV series)|The Twilight Zone]]'', ''[[The Dick Van Dyke Show]]'',  ''[[The Man from U.N.C.L.E.]]'', ''[[I Dream of Jeannie]]'', ''[[The Beverly Hillbillies]]'', ''[[Here's Lucy]]'', ''[[That Girl]]'', ''[[The Six Million Dollar Man]]'', ''[[The Bionic Woman]]'', ''[[One Day at a Time (1975 TV series)|One Day at a Time]]'', ''[[Lou Grant]]'', ''[[Quincy, M.E.]]'', ''[[Cheers]]'', and ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]''. \n\nHe is also known as a voice artist, contributing to the animated shows, ''[[Scooby-Doo and Scrappy-Doo (1979 TV series)|Scooby-Doo and Scrappy-Doo]]'', ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man (TV series)|The Amazing Spider-Man]]'', ''[[Johnny Quest]]'', ''[[DuckTales]]'', ''[[Snorks]]'', ''[[Paddington (TV series)|Paddington]]'', and ''[[Batman: The Animated Series]]''.\n\n==Early life and career==\nErdman was born '''John Richard Erdmann''' in [[Enid, Oklahoma|Enid]] in northern [[Oklahoma]]. His mother was Allie J. Erdman. His parents divorced during his childhood. Erdman, his sibling, and his mother moved to [[Colorado Springs]] when he was a teenager. He graduated from [[General William J. Palmer High School|Palmer High School]], where he would perform on stage. During his youth, he worked as a paper boy for the ''Colorado Springs Evening Telegraph''. A stage director named Newton Winburne encouraged him to try his luck in [[Hollywood]].<ref name=\"RErdman\">{{cite news| url=https://newspaperarchive.com/us/colorado/colorado-springs/colorado-springs-gazette/1972/10-14/page-128| title=A Character Actor Career Which Began Here Spins a 30-year Cycle, Climaxing in Colorado| newspaper=Colorado Springs Gazette| date=October 14, 1972| accessdate=July 1, 2016| last=Aldridge| first=Dorothy}}</ref>\n\nErdman started his career at [[Warner Bros.]] where he signed a studio contract. Two of his first roles were in the films ''[[Mr. Skeffington]]'', starring [[Bette Davis]] and [[Claude Rains]] and ''[[Janie (1944 film)|Janie]]'', starring [[Joyce Reynolds (actress)|Joyce Reynolds]]. After a few smaller roles he achieved success as a character actor in supporting roles. In a career that spanned seven decades, his best-known roles are that of the barracks chief Hoffy in ''[[Stalag 17]]'', and  the garrulous, tedious barfly McNulty in the ''[[The Twilight Zone (1959 TV series)|Twilight Zone]]'' episode \"[[A Kind of a Stopwatch]]\". He also appeared in ''[[The Men (film)|The Men]]'' (1950) with [[Marlon Brando]] and the [[film noir]] ''[[Cry Danger]]'' (1951) with [[Dick Powell]] and [[Rhonda Fleming]]. In ''[[Tora! Tora! Tora!]]'' (1970) he played Colonel Edward F. French, the officer who responded to the failure to transmit the warning to [[Pearl Harbor]], [[Hawaii]].\n\nHe directed the 1971 TV film ''[[Mooch Goes to Hollywood]]''.<ref>{{cite news| newspaper=The New York Times| title=Mooch Goes to Hollywood| url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/64832/Mooch-Goes-to-Hollywood/overview}}</ref> From 2009 to 2015, Erdman had a recurring role as the old student [[List of Community characters#Leonard Rodriguez|Leonard Rodriguez]] on ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]''. His last role was in 2017 in the sitcom ''[[Dr. Ken]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nErdman married actress Leza Holland in 1948, but they divorced two years later. He was married to his second wife, Sharon Randall, from 1953 until her death in 2016. They had one daughter, Erica, who was born in 1954 and died on February 18, 2010, of an accidental overdose of prescription medicine.<ref name=\"Erica\">{{cite news| url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/latimes/obituary.aspx?pid=140024292| title=Erica E. Erdman| newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]| date=February 26, 2010| accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref> Erica was a poet and illustrator (''The Ellyn Maybe Coloring Book'') and the author of one full-length collection of poems (''The Apocalyptic Kid'').\n\n== Death ==\nErdman died on March 16, 2019, aged 93, in an assisted-living facility in [[Los Angeles, California]]. He had been suffering \"from age-related [[dementia]]\" and recently had a fall.<ref>[https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/richard-erdman-dead-community-stalag-917730 Richard Erdman, Actor in ''Stalag 17'' and TV's ''Community'', Dies at 93], hollywoodreporter.com; accessed March 17, 2019.</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|1944 || ''[[Mr. Skeffington]]'' || Western Union Boy || uncredited\n|-\n|1944 || ''[[Janie (1944 film)|Janie]]'' || Scooper Nolan ||\n|-\n|1944 || ''Musical Movieland'' || Sailor with Tour || uncredited\n|-\n|1944 || ''[[The Very Thought of You (film)|The Very Thought of You]]'' || Soda Jerk ||\n|-\n|1944 || ''[[Hollywood Canteen (film)|Hollywood Canteen]]'' || Soldier on Deck || uncredited\n|- \n|1945 || ''[[Objective, Burma]]'' || Pvt. Nebraska Hooper ||\n|-\n|1945 || ''[[The Horn Blows at Midnight]]'' || Joe Smith || scenes deleted\n|-\n|1945 || ''[[Star in the Night]]'' || Cowboy ||\n|-\n|1945 || ''[[Danger Signal]]'' || Bunkie Taylor ||\n|-\n|1945 || ''[[Too Young to Know]]'' || Tommy ||\n|-\n|1946 || ''[[Janie Gets Married]]'' || Lt. 'Scooper' Nolan ||\n|-\n|1946 ||''[[Night and Day (1946 film)|Night and Day]]'' || Music Store Customer || uncredited\n|-\n|1946 || ''[[Shadow of a Woman]]'' || Joe ||\n|-\n|1946 || ''So You Want to Play the Horses'' || Eddie || uncredited\n|-\n|1946 || ''[[Deception (1946 film)|Deception]]'' || Jerry Spencer || uncredited\n|-\n|1946 || ''[[Nobody Lives Forever (1946 film)|Nobody Lives Forever]]'' || Bellboy, The Marwood Arms ||\n|-\n|1947 || ''[[That Way with Women]]'' || Eddie ||\n|-\n|1947 || ''[[Wild Harvest]]'' || Mark Lewis ||\n|-\n|1948 || ''[[The Time of Your Life (film)|The Time of Your Life]]'' || Willie (the pinball machin