Brothers O'Toole'' || Feature Film || \n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0258757}}\n*{{Find a Grave|197596299}}\n{{Portal|Biography|Oklahoma|California|Film|Television}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Erdman, Richard}}\n[[Category:1925 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Actors from Enid, Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Oklahoma]]\n[[Category:Audiobook narrators]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the American artist|Richard Erdman (artist)|the American diplomat|Richard W. Erdman}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Richard Erdman\n| image        = Richard Erdman (1950) The Admiral Was a Lady.jpg\n| image_size   = \n| alt          = \n| caption      = Erdman in ''[[The Admiral Was a Lady]]'' (1950)\n| birth_name   = John Richard Erdmann \n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1925|6|1|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Enid, Oklahoma|Enid]], [[Oklahoma]], U.S.\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|2019|3|16|1925|6|1}}\n| death_place  = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| nationality  =\n| other_names  = Dick Erdman \n| ethnicity    = \n| citizenship  = \n| education    = \n| alma_mater   = \n| occupation   =  {{flatlist|\n*Actor\n*director}}\n| years_active = 1944\u20132017\n| known_for    = ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]'' (2009-2015) <br/> ''[[Stalag 17]]'' (1953) <br/> ''[[Tora! Tora! Tora!]]'' (1970)\n| spouse       = {{ubl|{{marriage|Leza Holland|1948|1950|reason=div}}|{{marriage|Sharon Randall|1953|2016|reason=d.}}}} \n| partner      = \n| children     = 1 \n}}\n\n'''John Richard Erdman''' (June 1, 1925 \u2013 March 16, 2019) was an [[United States|American]] [[character actor]] and occasional film and television [[Film director|director]].<ref>{{cite web| work=[[The New York Times]]| title=Richard Erdman| url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/person/89065/Richard-Erdman}}</ref> He appeared in more than 160 films, and television productions between 1944 and 2017, mostly in supporting roles.<ref name=\"Utah\">{{cite news| url=https://newspaperarchive.com/us/utah/salt-lake-city/salt-lake-tribune/1967/07-21/page-17| title=Nothing Serious| newspaper=[[Salt Lake Tribune]]| date=July 21, 1967| accessdate=February 19, 2017| last=Valentine| first=Dan}}</ref> He is most known for his recurring role in the critically acclaimed comedy series ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]'' (2009-2015), and the classic films, ''[[Stalag 17]]'' (1953), and ''[[Tora! Tora! Tora!]]'' (1970).\n \nHe has guest starred in a wide variety of shows such as ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]'', ''[[Alfred Hitchcock Presents]]'', ''[[The Twilight Zone (1959 TV series)|The Twilight Zone]]'', ''[[The Dick Van Dyke Show]]'',  ''[[The Man from U.N.C.L.E.]]'', ''[[I Dream of Jeannie]]'', ''[[The Beverly Hillbillies]]'', ''[[Here's Lucy]]'', ''[[That Girl]]'', ''[[The Six Million Dollar Man]]'', ''[[The Bionic Woman]]'', ''[[One Day at a Time (1975 TV series)|One Day at a Time]]'', ''[[Lou Grant]]'', ''[[Quincy, M.E.]]'', ''[[Cheers]]'', and ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]''. \n\nHe is also known as a voice artist, contributing to a the animated shows, ''[[Scooby-Doo and Scrappy-Doo (1979 TV series)|Scooby-Doo and Scrappy-Doo]]'', ''[[The Amazing Spider-Man (TV series)|The Amazing Spider-Man]]'', ''[[Johnny Quest]]'', ''[[DuckTales]]'', ''[[Snorks]]'', ''[[Paddington (TV series)|Paddington]]'', and ''[[Batman: The Animated Series]]''.\n\n==Early life and career==\nErdman was born '''John Richard Erdmann''' in [[Enid, Oklahoma|Enid]] in northern [[Oklahoma]]. His mother was Allie J. Erdman. His parents divorced during his childhood. Erdman, his sibling, and his mother moved to [[Colorado Springs]] when he was a teenager. He graduated from [[General William J. Palmer High School|Palmer High School]], where he would perform on stage. During his youth, he worked as a paper boy for the ''Colorado Springs Evening Telegraph''. A stage director named Newton Winburne encouraged him to try his luck in [[Hollywood]].<ref name=\"RErdman\">{{cite news| url=https://newspaperarchive.com/us/colorado/colorado-springs/colorado-springs-gazette/1972/10-14/page-128| title=A Character Actor Career Which Began Here Spins a 30-year Cycle, Climaxing in Colorado| newspaper=Colorado Springs Gazette| date=October 14, 1972| accessdate=July 1, 2016| last=Aldridge| first=Dorothy}}</ref>\n\nErdman started his career at [[Warner Bros.]] where he signed a studio contract. Two of his first roles were in the films ''[[Mr. Skeffington]]'', starring [[Bette Davis]] and [[Claude Rains]] and ''[[Janie (1944 film)|Janie]]'', starring [[Joyce Reynolds (actress)|Joyce Reynolds]]. After a few smaller roles he achieved success as a character actor in supporting roles. In a career that spanned seven decades, his best-known roles are that of the barracks chief Hoffy in ''[[Stalag 17]]'', and  the garrulous, tedious barfly McNulty in the ''[[The Twilight Zone (1959 TV series)|Twilight Zone]]'' episode \"[[A Kind of a Stopwatch]]\". He also appeared in ''[[The Men (film)|The Men]]'' (1950) with [[Marlon Brando]] and the [[film noir]] ''[[Cry Danger]]'' (1951) with [[Dick Powell]] and [[Rhonda Fleming]]. In ''[[Tora! Tora! Tora!]]'' (1970) he played Colonel Edward F. French, the officer who responded to the failure to transmit the warning to [[Pearl Harbor]], [[Hawaii]].\n\nHe directed the 1971 TV film ''[[Mooch Goes to Hollywood]]''.<ref>{{cite news| newspaper=The New York Times| title=Mooch Goes to Hollywood| url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/64832/Mooch-Goes-to-Hollywood/overview}}</ref> From 2009 to 2015, Erdman had a recurring role as the old student [[List of Community characters#Leonard Rodriguez|Leonard Rodriguez]] on ''[[Community (TV series)|Community]]''. His last role was in 2017 in the sitcom ''[[Dr. Ken]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nErdman married actress Leza Holland in 1948, but they divorced two years later. He was married to his second wife, Sharon Randall, from 1953 until her death in 2016. They had one daughter, Erica, who was born in 1954 and died on February 18, 2010, of an accidental overdose of prescription medicine.<ref name=\"Erica\">{{cite news| url=http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/latimes/obituary.aspx?pid=140024292| title=Erica E. Erdman| newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]| date=February 26, 2010| accessdate=February 19, 2017}}</ref> Erica was a poet and illustrator (''The Ellyn Maybe Coloring Book'') and the author of one full-length collection of poems (''The Apocalyptic Kid'').\n\n== Death ==\nErdman died on March 16, 2019, aged 93, in an assisted-living facility in [[Los Angeles, California]]. He had been suffering \"from age-related [[dementia]]\" and recently had a fall.<ref>[https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/richard-erdman-dead-community-stalag-917730 Richard Erdman, Actor in ''Stalag 17'' and TV's ''Community'', Dies at 93], hollywoodreporter.com; accessed March 17, 2019.</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|1944 || ''[[Mr. Skeffington]]'' || Western Union Boy || uncredited\n|-\n|1944 || ''[[Janie (1944 film)|Janie]]'' || Scooper Nolan ||\n|-\n|1944 || ''Musical Movieland'' || Sailor with Tour || uncredited\n|-\n|1944 || ''[[The Very Thought of You (film)|The Very Thought of You]]'' || Soda Jerk ||\n|-\n|1944 || ''[[Hollywood Canteen (film)|Hollywood Canteen]]'' || Soldier on Deck || uncredited\n|- \n|1945 || ''[[Objective, Burma]]'' || Pvt. Nebraska Hooper ||\n|-\n|1945 || ''[[The Horn Blows at Midnight]]'' || Joe Smith || scenes deleted\n|-\n|1945 || ''[[Star in the Night]]'' || Cowboy ||\n|-\n|1945 || ''[[Danger Signal]]'' || Bunkie Taylor ||\n|-\n|1945 || ''[[